{"title_page": "Tommy Turner (footballer)", "text_new": "{{for|the 1880s Scottish international|Thomas Turner (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Tommy Turner\n| image =\n| fullname = Thomas Turner\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|10|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Johnstone]], Scotland\n| height = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 =\n| years2 = 1984\u20131990 \n| years3 = 1990\u20131994 \n| years4 = 1994\u20131997 \n| years5 = 1997\u20132002 \n| years6 = 1998 \n| years7 = 2002\u20132004 \n| years8 = 2004\u201320??\n| clubs1 = [[Glentyan Thistle F.C.|Glentyan Thistle]]\n| clubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] \n| clubs3 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] \n| clubs4 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] \n| clubs5 = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] \n| clubs6 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]] \n| clubs8 = [[Johnstone Burgh F.C.|Johnstone Burgh]] \n| caps1 =\n| caps2 = 175  \n| caps3 = 139   \n| caps4 = 37   \n| caps5 = 116   \n| caps6 = 5   \n| caps7 = 20   \n| caps8 =    \n|  totalcaps = 492 \n| goals1 =\n| goals2 = 29  \n| goals3 = 7  \n| goals4= 5  \n| goals5 = 9  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = 0  \n| goals8 =   \n|  totalgoals = 50\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Turner''' (born 11 October 1963 in [[Johnstone]], [[Renfrewshire]]) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]].\n\n==Career==\nTurner was captain of the [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] side that won the [[Scottish First Division]] in [[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000]]. Previous to that he played for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. In his second year at St Mirren, Turner went on a month's loan to [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] after an altercation with supporters of his own team. He finished his professional career with [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]] in 2004.\n\nAfter leaving senior football he joined the [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior leagues]] to captain his home town team, [[Johnstone Burgh]].\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner's son, Kyle, currently plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/17669438.stranraer-midfielder-kyle-turner-signs-for-dunfermline/?ref=twtrec |title=Stranraer midfielder Kyle Turner signs for Dunfermline as Myles Hipployte quits |first=Ross |last=Hart |work=Dunfermline Press |publisher=Newsquest |date=28 May 2019 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase|id=9272}}\n\n{{St Mirren F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gretna F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Johnstone Burgh F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:People from Johnstone]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Renfrewshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 1880s Scottish international|Thomas Turner (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Tommy Turner\n| image =\n| fullname = Thomas Turner\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|10|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Johnstone]], Scotland\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 =\n| years2 = 1984\u20131990 \n| years3 = 1990\u20131994 \n| years4 = 1994\u20131997 \n| years5 = 1997\u20132002 \n| years6 = 1998 \n| years7 = 2002\u20132004 \n| years8 = 2004\u201320??\n| clubs1 = [[Glentyan Thistle F.C.|Glentyan Thistle]]\n| clubs2 = [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] \n| clubs3 = [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] \n| clubs4 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] \n| clubs5 = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] \n| clubs6 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] (loan) \n| clubs7 = [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]] \n| clubs8 = [[Johnstone Burgh F.C.|Johnstone Burgh]] \n| caps1 =\n| caps2 = 175  \n| caps3 = 139   \n| caps4 = 37   \n| caps5 = 116   \n| caps6 = 5   \n| caps7 = 20   \n| caps8 =    \n|  totalcaps = 492 \n| goals1 =\n| goals2 = 29  \n| goals3 = 7  \n| goals4= 5  \n| goals5 = 9  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = 0  \n| goals8 =   \n|  totalgoals = 50\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Turner''' (born 11 October 1963 in [[Johnstone]], [[Renfrewshire]]) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] former professional [[association football|football]]er.\n\n==Career==\nTurner was captain of the [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] side that won the [[Scottish First Division]] in [[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000]]. Previous to that he played for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]], [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. In his second year at St Mirren, Turner went on a month's loan to [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] after an altercation with supporters of his own team. He finished his professional career with [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]] in 2004.\n\nAfter leaving senior football he joined the [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior leagues]] to captain his home town team, [[Johnstone Burgh]].\n\n==Personal life==\nTurner's son, Kyle, currently plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/17669438.stranraer-midfielder-kyle-turner-signs-for-dunfermline/?ref=twtrec |title=Stranraer midfielder Kyle Turner signs for Dunfermline as Myles Hipployte quits |first=Ross |last=Hart |work=Dunfermline Press |publisher=Newsquest |date=28 May 2019 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase|id=9272}}\n\n{{St Mirren F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Johnstone F.C. players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gretna F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Johnstone Burgh F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:People from Johnstone]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Renfrewshire]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, remove unref height", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Turner_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Yi Seou", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Korean name|[[Lee (Korean surname)|Yi]]}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|img=\uc1a1\uace1 \uc774\uc11c\uc6b0.jpg\n|caption=Yi Seou\n|hangul=\uc774\uc11c\uc6b0\n|hanja=\u674e\u745e\u96e8\n|rr=I Seou\n|mr=Yi S\u01d2u\n|hangulja=\uc724\ubcf4, \ud734\uc9d5\n|hanjaja=\u6f64\u752b, \u4f11\u5fb5\n|rrja=Yunbo, Hyujing\n|mrja=Yunbo, Hyujing\n|hangulho=\uc1a1\uace1\n|hanjaho=\u677e\u8c37\n|rrho=Songgok\n|mrho=Songgok\n}}\n'''Yi Seou''' (1 March 1633 \u2013 14 October 1709), also spelled as '''Lee Seo-Woo''', was a [[Koreans|Korean]] [[Joseon|Joseon Dynasty]] politician, [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucian]] scholar, and early [[silhak]] writer. He was a member of the [[Southerners (Korean political faction)|Southerners]] [[Political factions in Joseon Dynasty|political faction]].\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Songpa munjip'' (\uc1a1\ud30c\ubb38\uc9d1, \u677e\u5761\u6587\u96c6)\n* ''Gangsa'' (\uac15\uc0ac, \u5eb7\u53f2) \n* ''Jangsanhuji'' (\uc7a5\uc0b0\ud6c4\uc9c0, \u8407\u5c71\u5f8c\u8a8c) \n* ''Dongraeseungramhuji'' (\ub3d9\ub798\uc2b9\ub78c\uc11c\ud6c4\uc9c0, \u6771\u840a\u52dd\u89bd\u66f8\u5f8c\u8a8c)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heo Mok]]\n* [[Yun Hyu]]\n* [[Yun Seondo]]\n* [[Yu Hyeongwon]]\n* [[Seongho Yi Ik]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://koreandb.nate.com/history/people/detail?sn=1126 Yi Seou:Nate]\n* [http://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?docId=542263 Yi Seou]\n* [http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=888064 Yi Seou:Naver]\n* [http://people.aks.ac.kr/front/tabCon/ppl/pplView.aks?pplId=PPL_6JOb_A1633_1_0009709 Yi Seou:Korean historical persons information]\n{{wikisource|Author:Yi Seo-woo|Yi Seou}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yi, Seou}}\n[[Category:Korean scholars]]\n[[Category:Korean writers]]\n[[Category:Joseon Dynasty writers]]\n[[Category:1633 births]]\n[[Category:1709 deaths]]\n[[Category:Neo-Confucianism]]\n\n\n{{korea-writer-stub}}\n{{NeoConfucianism-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Korean name|[[Lee (Korean surname)|Yi]]}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|img=\uc1a1\uace1 \uc774\uc11c\uc6b0.jpg\n|caption=Yi Seou\n|hangul=\uc774\uc11c\uc6b0\n|hanja=\u674e\u745e\u96e8\n|rr=I Seou\n|mr=Yi S\u01d2u\n|hangulja=\uc724\ubcf4, \ud734\uc9d5\n|hanjaja=\u6f64\u752b, \u4f11\u5fb5\n|rrja=Yunbo, Hyujing\n|mrja=Yunbo, Hyujing\n|hangulho=\uc1a1\uace1\n|hanjaho=\u677e\u8c37\n|rrho=Songgok\n|mrho=Songgok\n}}\n'''Yi Seou''' (1 March 1633 \u2013 14 October 1709), also spelled as '''Lee Seo-Woo''', was a [[Koreans|Korean]] [[Joseon|Joseon Dynasty]] politician, [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucian]] scholar, and early [[silhak]] writer. He was a member of the [[Southerners (Korean political faction)|Southerners]] [[Political factions in Joseon Dynasty|political faction]].\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Songpa munjip'' (\uc1a1\ud30c\ubb38\uc9d1, \u677e\u5761\u6587\u96c6)\n* ''Gangsa'' (\uac15\uc0ac, \u5eb7\u53f2) \n* ''Jangsanhuji'' (\uc7a5\uc0b0\ud6c4\uc9c0, \u8407\u5c71\u5f8c\u8a8c) \n* ''Dongraeseungramhuji'' (\ub3d9\ub798\uc2b9\ub78c\uc11c\ud6c4\uc9c0, \u6771\u840a\u52dd\u89bd\u66f8\u5f8c\u8a8c) \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heo Mok]]\n* [[Yun Hyu]]\n* [[Yun Seondo]]\n* [[Yu Hyeongwon]]\n* [[Seongho Yi Ik]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://koreandb.nate.com/history/people/detail?sn=1126 Yi Seou:Nate]\n* [http://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?docId=542263 Yi Seou]\n* [http://100.naver.com/100.nhn?docid=888064 Yi Seou:Naver]\n* [http://people.aks.ac.kr/front/tabCon/ppl/pplView.aks?pplId=PPL_6JOb_A1633_1_0009709 Yi Seou:Korean historical persons information]\n{{wikisource|Author:Yi Seo-woo|Yi Seou}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yi, Seou}}\n[[Category:Korean scholars]]\n[[Category:Korean writers]]\n[[Category:Joseon Dynasty writers]]\n[[Category:1633 births]]\n[[Category:1709 deaths]]\n[[Category:Neo-Confucianism]]\n\n\n{{korea-writer-stub}}\n{{NeoConfucianism-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yi_Seou"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Traynor (Scottish footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Tommy Traynor\n| fullname = Thomas Traynor\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1943|9|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Bonnybridge]], Scotland\n| death_date  = January 1993 (aged 49)\n| death_place = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| height =  \n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Dunipace Juniors]]\n| years1 = 1962\u20131970 \n| years2 = 1970\u20131976 \n| years3 = 1975\u20131976 \n| years4 = 1976\u20131977\n| clubs1 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n| clubs2 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] \n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] (loan) \n| clubs4 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n\n| caps1 = 171  \n| caps2 = 119  \n| caps3 = 4   \n| caps4 = 14   \n|  totalcaps = 308 \n| goals1 = 30  \n| goals2 = 15  \n| goals3 = 0  \n| goals4 = 0  \n|  totalgoals = 45\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n}}\n'''Thomas''' \"'''Tommy'''\" '''Traynor''' (27 September 1943 \u2013 January 1993) was a Scottish [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfield#Winger|winger]]. Traynor spent the majority of his career with [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] and [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], gaining [[Scottish Cup]] runners-up medals with both, in 1968 and 1974 respectively. Traynor also had short spells with [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] and [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]. He was a coach with [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]] after his playing retirement before moving to Australia, where he died from a heart attack.\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] finalist: [[1967\u201368 in Scottish football|1967\u201368]]\n\n;[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] finalist: [[1973\u201374 in Scottish football|1973\u201374]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/tommytraynor1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Traynor, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Heart of Midlothian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Falkirk (council area)]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n\n\n{{scotland-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Tommy Traynor\n| fullname = Thomas Traynor\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1943|9|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Bonnybridge]], Scotland\n| death_date  = January 1993 (aged 49)\n| death_place = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}\n| currentclub  = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Dunipace Juniors]]\n| years1 = 1962\u20131970 \n| years2 = 1970\u20131976 \n| years3 = 1975\u20131976 \n| years4 = 1976\u20131977\n| clubs1 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n| clubs2 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] \n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] (loan) \n| clubs4 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]\n\n| caps1 = 171  \n| caps2 = 119  \n| caps3 = 4   \n| caps4 = 14   \n|  totalcaps = 308 \n| goals1 = 30  \n| goals2 = 15  \n| goals3 = 0  \n| goals4 = 0  \n|  totalgoals = 45\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n}}\n'''Thomas''' \"'''Tommy'''\" '''Traynor''' (27 September 1943 \u2013 January 1993) was a Scottish [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Midfield#Winger|winger]]. Traynor spent the majority of his career with [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] and [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], gaining [[Scottish Cup]] runners-up medals with both, in 1968 and 1974 respectively. Traynor also had short spells with [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] and [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]. He was a coach with [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]] after his playing retirement before moving to Australia, where he died from a heart attack.\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] finalist: [[1967\u201368 in Scottish football|1967\u201368]]\n\n;[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] finalist: [[1973\u201374 in Scottish football|1973\u201374]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/tommytraynor1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Traynor, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Heart of Midlothian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Greenock Morton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Falkirk (council area)]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n\n\n{{scotland-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, remove unref height", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Traynor_(Scottish_footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Yi Kyoung-ja", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Yi}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Yi Kyoung-Ja\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1948|01|28}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = \n| language      = Korean\n| nationality   = South Korean\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n{{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n|title = Korean name\n|hangul = {{linktext|\uc774|\uacbd\uc790}}\n|hanja = \n|rr =  I Gyeongja\n|mr = I Ky\u014fngcha}}\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Yi Kyoung-ja''' (Hangul: \uc774\uacbd\uc790) is a South Korean author whose work focuses on the position of women in Korean society.<ref>\"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n1948\ub144 1\uc6d4 28\uc77c (\uac15\uc6d0\ub3c4 \uc591\uc591) YI Kyoung-ja was born on January 28, 1948, in [[Yangyang]], [[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwan-do]], [[Korea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |title= \uc774\uacbd\uc790 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |publisher= Naver |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Yangyang is famous for its beautiful scenery and this gave Yi a strong attachment to nature from an early age. She graduated from Sorabol College of the Arts (Today [[Chung-Ang University]]) and began submitting her writing to annual spring literary contests at age 19, but not winning until 1973 when she  won the Seoul Daily annual spring literary contest.\n\nLee's writing was intimately connected to her personal life and when she married a banker many people, including the author herself, worried if this would adversely affect her ability to write. Her marriage was a bit of a surprise as she had always planned to not get married and instead concentrate on writing. In the end, however, marriage and children did not affect Yi's ability to write and her strong dedication to writing helped to bring may contradictions in the state of Korean women to light.<ref>\"Yi Kyoung-ja\" LTI Korea Datasheet available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n\nOne of the salient features of Lee's works is the flowing style of her sentences, which makes her writing fast-paced and readable whether it's a short story or full-length novel. It is within internal character dialogue, however, where her lively prose really shines. Lee often uses such dialogue as a means of revealing characters' conflicts and anguish. In these internal conversations, she uses authentic and colloquial language without excessive embellishment. Her novels feel genuine to readers due to the reality effect created by her natural use of everyday language. Even during the 1980s, when ideological discourse dominated literature, author Lee Kyung-ja's prose offered a sentimental view of women's experiences. It is misguided, however, to focus on the mere fact that she is a female author writing about women.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt isn't easy to sum up her universe of published works including short story collections and full-length novels. Nevertheless, there are some keywords that can provide insight into her works. One of the most important themes Lee is interested in is the caged life of women,  similar to that depicted by [[Guy de Maupassant]] in Une Vie. In her works concerned with female transformation, two major types can be identified.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOne of her novels begins by introducing a married female protagonist who is fretting over the institution of marriage and her husband's indifference. The heroine ultimately ends her marriage after meeting another man, her true love. In Lee's works, most women domesticated under the institution of marriage but later reborn as 'warriors of love,' are originally middle-class housewives enjoying comfortable lives. Lee's full-length novel, [Waking up Alone in the Morning] (1993), is a work of this type.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nLee has also used the biographical format in her novels. In one of Lee's works, the reader is introduced to a heroine who had once been full of hope as a little girl, before being cast into tragedy and suffering after marriage, a transformation that Lee describes in minute detail. In the oral tradition that existed before the modern literary era, women verbally recounted their life stories. In the same fashion, narrators in Lee Kyung-ja's works tell us tales from long lives centered on marriage, birth, unfaithful husbands, family feuds, and other critical events. Lee's acclaimed and prize-winning works such as [Love and Hurt] (1998) and [Affection Never Withers] (1999) are good examples of the kind of work described above. Such stories present personal life history in a form that sheds light on modern Korean history magically interwoven with the individual.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nYi has won several awards including the 4th annual Han Mu-sook Literature prize in 1999, the 4th Goh-Jung-hee Literature Prize 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |title= \uc774\uacbd\uc790 > \uc218\uc0c1\ub0b4\uc5ed |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |publisher= Naver |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> and in 2004 the Beautiful Writer's Prize which is awarded to older writers by younger ones.<ref>\"Yi Kyoung-ja\" LTI Korea Datasheet available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Works in translation==\n* Une Fille nomm\u00e9e Deuxi\u00e8me gar\u00e7on (\uc5ec\uc131 \ub2e8\ud3b8\uc120 <\ub458\ub0a8\uc774>)\n\n==Works in Korean (partial)==\n'''Story collections'''\n* Incident at Halmiso\n* Survival\n* Hunchback's Love\n'''Serial novels'''\n* Half a Failure\n'''Full-length novels'''\n* Castle of Betrayal\n* Waking Up Alone in the Morning\n* Rapturous Rebellion\n* Love and Hurt\n* Affection Never Withers\n* Who'll Untie the Knot?\n* Cassia Flower\n\n==Awards==\n* 4th annual Han Mu-sook Literature prize in 1999\n* Beautiful Writer's Prize 2004\n* 4th Goh-Jung-hee Literature Prize 2011\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yi, Kyoung-ja}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Korean writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Yi}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Yi Kyoung-Ja\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1948|01|28}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = \n| language      = Korean\n| nationality   = South Korean\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = \n| period        = \n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n{{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n|title = Korean name\n|hangul = {{linktext|\uc774|\uacbd\uc790}}\n|hanja = \n|rr =  I Gyeongja\n|mr = I Ky\u014fngcha}}\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Yi Kyoung-ja''' (Hangul: \uc774\uacbd\uc790) is a South Korean author whose work focuses on the position of women in Korean society.<ref>\"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n1948\ub144 1\uc6d4 28\uc77c (\uac15\uc6d0\ub3c4 \uc591\uc591) YI Kyoung-ja was born on January 28, 1948, in [[Yangyang]], [[Gangwon Province (South Korea)|Gangwan-do]], [[Korea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |title= \uc774\uacbd\uc790 |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |publisher= Naver |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Yangyang is famous for its beautiful scenery and this gave Yi a strong attachment to nature from an early age. She graduated from Sorabol College of the Arts (Today [[Chung-Ang University]]) and began submitting her writing to annual spring literary contests at age 19, but not winning until 1973 when she  won the Seoul Daily annual spring literary contest.\n\nLee's writing was intimately connected to her personal life and when she married a banker many people, including the author herself, worried if this would adversely affect her ability to write. Her marriage was a bit of a surprise as she had always planned to not get married and instead concentrate on writing. In the end, however, marriage and children did not affect Yi's ability to write and her strong dedication to writing helped to bring may contradictions in the state of Korean women to light.<ref>\"Yi Kyoung-ja\" LTI Korea Datasheet available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n\nOne of the salient features of Lee's works is the flowing style of her sentences, which makes her writing fast-paced and readable whether it's a short story or full-length novel. It is within internal character dialogue, however, where her lively prose really shines. Lee often uses such dialogue as a means of revealing characters' conflicts and anguish. In these internal conversations, she uses authentic and colloquial language without excessive embellishment. Her novels feel genuine to readers due to the reality effect created by her natural use of everyday language. Even during the 1980s, when ideological discourse dominated literature, author Lee Kyung-ja's prose offered a sentimental view of women's experiences. It is misguided, however, to focus on the mere fact that she is a female author writing about women.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt isn't easy to sum up her universe of published works including short story collections and full-length novels. Nevertheless, there are some keywords that can provide insight into her works. One of the most important themes Lee is interested in is the caged life of women,  similar to that depicted by [[Guy de Maupassant]] in Une Vie. In her works concerned with female transformation, two major types can be identified.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOne of her novels begins by introducing a married female protagonist who is fretting over the institution of marriage and her husband's indifference. The heroine ultimately ends her marriage after meeting another man, her true love. In Lee's works, most women domesticated under the institution of marriage but later reborn as 'warriors of love,' are originally middle-class housewives enjoying comfortable lives. Lee's full-length novel, [Waking up Alone in the Morning] (1993), is a work of this type.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nLee has also used the biographical format in her novels. In one of Lee's works, the reader is introduced to a heroine who had once been full of hope as a little girl, before being cast into tragedy and suffering after marriage, a transformation that Lee describes in minute detail. In the oral tradition that existed before the modern literary era, women verbally recounted their life stories. In the same fashion, narrators in Lee Kyung-ja's works tell us tales from long lives centered on marriage, birth, unfaithful husbands, family feuds, and other critical events. Lee's acclaimed and prize-winning works such as [Love and Hurt] (1998) and [Affection Never Withers] (1999) are good examples of the kind of work described above. Such stories present personal life history in a form that sheds light on modern Korean history magically interwoven with the individual.<ref>Source-attribution| \"\uc774\uacbd\uc790\" biographical PDF available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nYi has won several awards including the 4th annual Han Mu-sook Literature prize in 1999, the 4th Goh-Jung-hee Literature Prize 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |title= \uc774\uacbd\uc790 > \uc218\uc0c1\ub0b4\uc5ed |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=people.search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=tab_txc&where=people_profile&ie=utf8&query=%EC%9D%B4%EA%B2%BD%EC%9E%90&os=172816 |publisher= Naver |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> and in 2004 the Beautiful Writer's Prize which is awarded to older writers by younger ones.<ref>\"Yi Kyoung-ja\" LTI Korea Datasheet available at LTI Korea Library or online at: {{cite web|url=http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do# |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 3, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055413/http://klti.or.kr/ke_04_03_011.do |archivedate=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Works in translation==\n* Une Fille nomm\u00e9e Deuxi\u00e8me gar\u00e7on (\uc5ec\uc131 \ub2e8\ud3b8\uc120 <\ub458\ub0a8\uc774>)\n\n==Works in Korean (partial)==\n'''Story collections'''\n* Incident at Halmiso\n* Survival\n* Hunchback's Love\n'''Serial novels'''\n* Half a Failure\n'''Full-length novels'''\n* Castle of Betrayal\n* Waking Up Al