{"title_page": "Pachylepyrium", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Pachylepyrium carbonicola 147687.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| image_caption = ''Pachylepyrium carbonicola''\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Agaricales]]\n| familia = [[Strophariaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Pachylepyrium'''''\n| genus_authority = [[Rolf Singer|Singer]] (1958)\n| type_species = ''Pachylepyrium fulvidula''\n| type_species_authority = (Singer) Singer (1958)\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species (biology)|Species]]\n| subdivision = ''[[Pachylepyrium carbonicola|P. carbonicola]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium chilense|P. chilense]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium fulvidula|P. fulvidula]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium funariophilum|P. funariophilum]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium nubicola|P. nubicola]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium squarrulosum|P. squarrulosum]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium wrightii|P. wrightii]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Pachylepyrium''''' is a [[genus]] of [[fungi]] in the family [[Strophariaceae]]. The genus was circumscribed by [[Rolf Singer]] in 1958.<ref name=Singer1957/> The genus ''Pachylepyrium'' is widespread in northern [[temperate]] areas, and contains seven species.<ref name=Kirk2008/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Fungi}}\n*[[List of Agaricales genera]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Kirk2008>{{cite book |vauthors=Kirk PM, Cannon PF, Minter DW, Stalpers JA |title=Dictionary of the Fungi |edition=10th |publisher=CAB International |location=Wallingford, UK |year=2008 |page=490 |isbn=978-0-85199-826-8}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Singer1957>{{cite journal |author=Singer R. |title=New genera of fungi X |journal=Sydowia |year=1957 |volume=11 |pages=320\u20132 |url=http://www.landesmuseum.at/pdf_frei_remote/Sydowia_11_0320-0322.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7122152}}\n\n[[Category:Bolbitiaceae]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Rolf Singer]]\n\n\n{{Agaricales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Pachylepyrium carbonicola 147687.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| image_caption = ''Pachylepyrium carbonicola''\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Agaricales]]\n| familia = [[Strophariaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Pachylepyrium'''''\n| genus_authority = [[Rolf Singer|Singer]] (1958)\n| type_species = ''Pachylepyrium fulvidula''\n| type_species_authority = (Singer) Singer (1958)\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species (biology)|Species]]\n| subdivision = ''[[Pachylepyrium carbonicola|P. carbonicola]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium chilense|P. chilense]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium fulvidula|P. fulvidula]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium funariophilum|P. funariophilum]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium nubicola|P. nubicola]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium squarrulosum|P. squarrulosum]]''<br>\n''[[Pachylepyrium wrightii|P. wrightii]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Pachylepyrium''''' is a [[genus]] of [[fungi]] in the [[Strophariaceae]] family. The genus was circumscribed by [[Rolf Singer]] in 1958.<ref name=Singer1957/> The genus ''Pachylepyrium'' is widespread in northern [[temperate]] areas, and contains seven species.<ref name=Kirk2008/>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Fungi}}\n*[[List of Agaricales genera]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Kirk2008>{{cite book |vauthors=Kirk PM, Cannon PF, Minter DW, Stalpers JA |title=Dictionary of the Fungi |edition=10th |publisher=CAB International |location=Wallingford, UK |year=2008 |page=490 |isbn=978-0-85199-826-8}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Singer1957>{{cite journal |author=Singer R. |title=New genera of fungi X |journal=Sydowia |year=1957 |volume=11 |pages=320\u20132 |url=http://www.landesmuseum.at/pdf_frei_remote/Sydowia_11_0320-0322.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q7122152}}\n\n[[Category:Bolbitiaceae]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Rolf Singer]]\n\n\n{{Agaricales-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pachylepyrium"}
{"title_page": "Jack Reacher", "text_new": "{{About|the character|the book series|Jack Reacher (book series)|the film|Jack Reacher (film)|}}\n{{short description|Fictional character}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour     = #DEDEE2\n| name       = Jack Reacher\n| image      = JackReacherAlt.jpg\n| caption    = Jack Reacher, as played by Tom Cruise, appearing in the theatrical poster of the 2012 film ''Jack Reacher''<!--This image is a scaled-down, lower-resolution image of the theatrical poster for ''[[Jack Reacher (film)]]''.-->\n| first      = ''[[Killing Floor (novel)]]'' (1997)<br>''[[Jack Reacher (film)]]'' (2012)\n| nickname   = Reacher\n| alias      = <!-- see article body, after it is described -->\n| gender     = Male\n| occupation = {{flatlist |\n* [[U.S. Army]] [[Military Police Corps (United States)|Military Police Corps]] [[Major]]\n* [[Private investigator]]\n* [[Vagrancy (people)|Drifter]]\n* [[Vigilante]]\n}}\n| family     = {{plainlist |\n* Laurent Moutier (maternal grandfather, deceased)\n* William \"Stan\" Reacher (father, deceased)\n* Josephine Moutier-Reacher (mother, deceased)\n* Joe Reacher (brother, deceased)\n}}\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| spouse     =\n| children   =\n| relatives  =\n| creator    = [[Lee Child]]\n| portrayer  = [[Tom Cruise]]\n}}\n\n'''Jack Reacher''' is a black fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of a [[Jack Reacher (book series)|series of crime thriller]] novels by British author [[Lee Child]].<ref name=\"CurtisMarch2013\">{{cite web|last=Curtis|first=Bryan|title=The Curious Case of Lee Child: Before Tom Cruise could become Jack Reacher, Jim Grant had to become Lee Child|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8766396/lee-child-jim-grant-jack-reacher |magazine=[[Grantland]] | accessdate=5 September 2015|date=20 December 2012}}</ref> After leaving the [[US Army]] as a [[Major (military)|major]] in [[Military Police Corps (United States)|its military police]] at age 36, Reacher roams the United States taking [[Temporary work|odd jobs]] and investigating suspicious and frequently dangerous situations. {{as of|2019|10|29}}, 24 novels have been published, the most recent being ''Blue Moon''. The character has also appeared in short stories, and two of the novels have been adapted into successful [[action thriller]] [[Jack Reacher (film)|films]], starring [[Tom Cruise]] as Reacher.\n\n==Development and author's commentary==\n===Development===\nAt the time Lee Child sat down to write his first novel ''[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]]'', he was unemployed, having been fired from his position as a presentation director for [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]].<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/><ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/><ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/> According to Child, authorship was a purely pragmatic decision: \"I wasn't one of these people that felt compelled to write. It had to keep a roof over our heads, so it was totally, totally 110% commercially motivated.\"<ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/>\n\nCritics have perceived other influences in Jack Reacher's creation. Bob Cornwell quotes Lee Child's reply in another interview as having created Reacher \"as an antidote, to all the depressed and miserable alcoholics that increasingly peopled the genre\".<ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/><ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/> Similarly, editor [[Otto Penzler]] published an essay by Child explaining that Jack Reacher was created deliberately in contrast to the prevailing trends in crime fiction. His name is short and commonplace, as opposed to quirky or unusual; Reacher's  personal ethics and wandering lifestyle are reminiscent of the chivalrous [[knight errant]] of medieval lore as opposed to an [[anti-hero]] tormented by addiction and haunted by past misbehavior.<ref>Otto Penzler (editor) ''The lineup: the world's greatest crime writers tell the inside story of their greatest detectives''. Little, Brown (2009)</ref>\n\nThe character's name first came to Child in a supermarket when an old lady, noting the span of Child's arms, asked for his help in reaching out to a can of pears. On seeing this, Child's wife commented that if his writing career did not work out he could \"always get a job as a reacher in a supermarket\".<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/> Reacher's ex-military background was a specific and tactical choice on his behalf. Child has explained, \"I thought that I would do a book that's not the same as everybody else's. Everybody else had their guy working: a private guy in [[Boston]] or a police lieutenant in [[Los Angeles|L.A.]], or wherever. I thought, 'Well, he won't be working, and he won't live anywhere, and let's just take it from there.'\" Child also felt that this origin would lend itself to the character's personality and nomadic lifestyle: \"This idea of the rootless alienation has got to come from somewhere, and I noticed that the most alienated people are always ex-military, because it's like going from one solar system to the other, it's so different. So that was an easy choice: Make him ex-military. Then make him ex-military police because, broadly speaking, these would be crime novels, and he had to have some investigative experience, and he had to understand procedures and forensics and so on. So that part was all set in stone\".<ref name=\"RobertBidinotto2007\">{{cite web|last=Bidinotto |first= Robert |title=Thriller: Lee Child and the creation of Jack Reacher |url= http://atlassociety.org/commentary/commentary-blog/4508-thriller-lee-child-and-the-creation-of-jack-reacher |magazine= The Atlas Society |date= 17 March 2011 |accessdate= 8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Similarities between Reacher and Lee Child====\nNumerous critics have pointed out the various similarities between Lee Child and Jack Reacher. Bryan Curtis, writing for ''[[Grantland]]'', and Natasha Harding and Caroline Iggulden, in a separate article for ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', have brought out the various similarities between Child and Reacher: Child is {{convert|6|ft|4|in|abbr=on}} tall while his protagonist stands  {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}}; both writer and creation constantly consume coffee; Like Reacher, Child \"lives in cheap pairs of jeans and T-shirts and finds the idea of buying expensive clothes to be irrational\"; and that \"Jack Reacher's famous physical qualities are based on Child's playground memories as a child\".<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> Child tends to agree with such observations: \"I was huge as a kid and Reacher's stature is me translated as a kid. I enjoyed being bigger and fighting shamelessly. I've done a fair amount of [[headbutt]]ing. It's an awesome manoeuvre.\"{{refn|group=note|The headbutt is considered Reacher's \"signature move\".<ref name= \"AndyMartin2015\"/>}} Andy Martin notes that \"just as Reacher is half-[[Arthur Rimbaud|Rimbaud]], half-[[John Rambo|Rambo]], Child is both art-for-art's-sake [[Parnassianism|Parnassian]] and ruthless businessman.\"<ref name=\"AndyMartin2015\">{{cite web |last=Martin |first= Andy |title= Lee Child on Jack Reacher: How the best-selling author writes his mysteries |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/lee-child-on-jack-reacher-how-the-best-selling-author-writes-his-mysteries-9959227.html |magazine= [[The Independent]] |date= January 2015 |accessdate= 5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurtis, as well as Harding and Iggulden, have also considered the role Child's dismissal from Granada had on Reacher's development. Curtis also notes that \"Child created Reacher from the smoldering embers of his own rage. It might seem like a simplistic theory, but it's true. Like the author, Reacher was workplace surplus: He was a [[military police]]man in an era of Army [[Layoff|downsizing]]. The act of leaving his job turned Reacher into a protective figure, an avenging angel.\" He finds that Reacher's actions are a manifestation of Child's anger at his sacking and that his violent ways of dealing with villains is 'cathartic' to the author.<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\n===Author's commentary and interpretation===\n[[File:Lee Child, Bouchercon 2010.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lee Child|Jim Grant]], better known by his pen name Lee Child, at [[Bouchercon XLI]], 2010]]\n \nLee Child views Jack Reacher as a \"happy-go-lucky guy. He has quirks and problems, but the thing is, he doesn't know he's got them. Hence, no tedious self-pity. He's smart and strong, an [[introvert]], but any anguish he suffers is caused by others.\"<ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/> When asked about the casting of [[Tom Cruise]] in the role of Jack Reacher (Tom Cruise's casting as Jack Reacher was met with severe criticism from fans of the book series, primarily because the disparity in their heights with Reacher portrayed as a blond, {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}} tall, 250-pound man in the novels, while Cruise is a {{convert|5|ft|7|in|abbr=on}} tall brunette<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\">{{cite web |last=Kellogg |first= Carolyn |title= Reader reactions to 'Jack Reacher': The fans are furious |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/21/entertainment/la-et-jc-tom-cruise-jack-reacher-fans-react-20121220 |magazine= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 21 December 2012}}</ref><ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/>), Child replied that \"Reacher's size in the books is a metaphor for an unstoppable force\".<ref name= DenOfGeek/> Physically and appearance wise, Child has  compared him to Rugby Player [[Lawrence Dallaglio]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Studio 10|title=Author Lee Child Talks 'Jack Reacher' TV Series {{!}} Studio 10|date=2018-11-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YK8rOM1skK4|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHe has also referred to Reacher on multiple occasions as a '[[knight-errant]]'<ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/><ref name= \"AlexBerenson2014\"/> and in an interview for the ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine describes the character as: \" (He's) two things in one. On the surface, he is an ex-military cop who is suddenly dumped out into the civilian world. He doesn't fit in, and he spends his time wandering America, seeing the things that he's never had time to see before. He's trying to stay out of trouble, but masterfully once a year getting into trouble. He's also the descendant of a very ancient tradition: the noble loner, the knight errant, the mysterious stranger, who has shown up in stories forever\u2026 He is a truly universal character... I'm writing the modern iteration of a character who has existed for thousands of years.\"<ref name=\"AndreaSachs2012\">{{cite web |last=Sachs |first= Andrea |title= Lee Child on His New Thriller, Tom Cruise as Jack Reacher and Wandering Heroes |url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/09/19/lee-child-on-his-new-thriller-tom-cruise-as-jack-reacher-and-wandering-heroes/ |magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate= 5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn another interview for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine, Child further analyses the mythology of his character:\n\n<blockquote>The stories that I love are basically about the knight-errant, the mysterious stranger. And the reason why people think that's an essentially American paradigm is the Westerns. The Westerns were absolutely rock solid with that stuff. You know, the mysterious rider comes in off the range, sorts out the problem, and rides off into the sunset. It is just such a total paradigm, but not invented in America. That was imported from the medieval tales of Europe. The knight-errant: literally a knight, somehow banished and forced to wander the land doing good deeds. It's part of storytelling in every culture. Japan has it with the ronin myth; every culture has this Robin Hood idea. So really, that character was forced out of Europe as Europe became more densely populated and more civilized. That character no longer had stories in Europe; it had to migrate to where the frontier was still open and dangerous, which was America, essentially. So the character, I think, is actually universal and historic, most recently, normally represented in America. I think the Westerns saw it firmly adopted by America, so yeah, right now, we think of this as a completely American character, but really, it's more historic than that. But I'm very happy to have that reference made.<ref name=\"AlexBerenson2014\">{{cite web |last=Berenson |first= Alex |title= What Lee Child Has Learned from Writing the Jack Reacher Books |url= http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/books/a30736/jack-reacher-lee-child-interview/ |magazine= [[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate= 5 March 2016 |date=December 2014}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nChild also views Reacher as \"[[Postfeminism|post-feminist]]\" stating that he does not parlay in \"gender distinction...Reacher likes strong, realistic women, and he treats women with respect...he doesn't cut them any slack, but also he has no negative preconceptions. If you're a woman, he will be your friend; but if necessary, he will kill you.\"<ref name= \"RobertBidinotto2007\"/>\n\n==Fictional biography==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2015}}\nJack Reacher is described as being a former major in the United States Military Police Corps.\n\n===Childhood and formative years===\nJack Reacher was born on a [[military base]] in Berlin, on 29 October 1960. He has no middle name, and most people simply call him 'Reacher', even his family as a child. Regular references are made to the fact that Reacher's given name is Jack, which is not a nickname for John, and that he has no middle name.  His military record officially refers to him as Jack (none) Reacher.<ref name= DenOfGeek/> From the time he was a boy, his family, even his mother, simply called him \"Reacher\", an appellation that has stayed with him, but was never given to his brother.<ref name= \"LeeChildOfficial\"/>\n\nReacher's mother Josephine Moutier Reacher (n\u00e9e Moutier) was a French national, and Reacher was fluent in French from early childhood,<ref name=\"Enemy\">Child (2004). ''The Enemy''.</ref> but as he admits in ''The Affair'' (2011) he speaks the language ''Un peu, mais lentement'' (\"A little, but slowly\"). Reacher's maternal grandfather was at the Battle of Verdun in the First World War and in the French Resistance in the Second, and lived to a ripe old age, which in Reacher's view means that his grandfather had \"beaten the odds\".\n\n===Military years and profile===\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:USAMPC-COA.png|thumb|150px|left|Regimental Coat of Arms of the United States Military Police Corps]]\n\nAfter being shunted around the world, growing up on U.S. military bases where his father Stan was stationed, he gained an education in basic survival as well as an opportunity to enter the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point. After four years at West Point (1979 to 1983) Reacher achieved the ranks of [[Second lieutenant#United States|2nd lieutenant]], [[First lieutenant#United States|1st lieutenant]], [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], and [[Major (United States)#Army|major]],<ref>{{Cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|pages = 11}}</ref> including an intervening demotion from major to captain<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Enemy|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = TransworldDigital|year = 2004|isbn = 0-553-81585-7|chapter= Chapter 25}}</ref> in 1990<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\">{{cite web|last= Child|first= Lee|title= Jack Reacher| website= leechild.com| url= http://www.leechild.com/jack-reacher.php |accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref> during his tenure in the military police. His commanding officer, Leon Garber, promoted Reacher twice in 18 months, making  him the youngest peacetime major anyone could remember.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee|title= Tripwire|publisher= Jove Books|year= 2000| isbn= 978-0515128635}}</ref> During his tenure, his achievements were recognised in the form of citations and awards including the [[Silver Star]], the [[Defense Superior Service Medal]], [[Legion of Merit]], [[Soldier's Medal]], [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= Night School|publisher= Delacorte Press| year= 2016| isbn= 978-0804178808 |page= 322}}</ref> [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]], and a second [[Silver Star]] and [[Purple Heart]] for wounds sustained in the bombing of the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings|US Marine Corps barracks]] in [[Beirut]] in 1983.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/><ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= 61 Hours | url= https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell| url-access= registration| year= 2010 |page= [https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell/page/22 22]|quote= Reacher had been an army liaison officer serving with the Marine Corps at the time of the barracks bombing. He had been badly wounded in the attack....The wound had healed fast and completely. It had left what the army called a disfiguring scar, which implied a real mess.}}</ref>\n\nWhile his Silver Star and Purple Heart are cited on his profile, all of the other [[Citations|medal citations]] involve official secrets and are therefore [[Sanitization (classified information)|redacted]]. The short story \"Deep Down\" hints that he possibly was awarded the Legion of Merit as a result of exposing a female liaison officer who was leaking confidential information to the Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= Deep Down|publisher= Delacorte Press|year=2012|isbn= 978-0-345-53710-2 |page= 86}}</ref>\n\nReacher served in the army's military police branch, resigning his commission and [[Mustering-out Payment Act|mustering out]] at the rank of major. His unit, the fictional 110th Special Investigations Unit,<ref name=DenOfGeek/> was formed to handle exceptionally tough cases. He left the armed forces in 1997, partly due to a reduction in the forces and partly because he verbally offended a lieutenant colonel during an investigation in Mississippi, who then singled him out for discharge.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Make Me|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2015|isbn = 9780804178785|location = |pages =| chapter= Chapter 23}}</ref>\n\nAmong his formal qualifications, Reacher is described as the only non-Marine to win the [[Wimbledon Cup]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first =Lee |title= [[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]}}</ref> a US Marine Corps 1000 Yard Invitational Rifle Competition; achieving a record score in 1988.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= [[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]]|publisher= Transworld Digital|year=2005|isbn= 0-385-33668-3| chapter= Chapter 12}}</ref> Anecdotally his fitness reports rated him well above average in the classroom, excellent in the field, fluently bilingual in English and French, passable in Spanish, outstanding on all man-portable weaponry, and beyond outstanding at hand-to-hand combat.<ref name=\"61H\">{{cite book | last= Child | first= Lee | title= 61 Hours | publisher= Delacorte Press | location= New York | year= 2010 | isbn= 9780440243694 | url= https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell }}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nAfter leaving the Army, Reacher became a [[vagabond (person)|drifter]], his only baggage a folding toothbrush,<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> although after the [[September 11 attacks]], with restrictions on [[wire transfer]]s in the light of [[Wire transfer fraud|fraud]] he is obliged to carry an [[ATM card]]<ref name=\"KevinNance2012\"/> and [[Photo identification|photo ID]] in the form of a (generally expired) American [[passport]].<ref name=\"SteveDrummond2011\">{{cite web|last= Drummond|first= Steve|title=Lee Child's 'The Affair': Sixteen Books In, Has Jack Reacher Still Got It?|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/monkeysee/2011/10/20/141548652/lee-childs-the-affair-sixteen-books-in-has-jack-reacher-still-got-it | website= NPR.org | publisher= [[National Public Radio]] | date= 20 October 2011 | accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nEmily Sargent, while conducting an interview with Lee Child, describes Reacher's post-military life as follows:\n\n<blockquote>You will never find Reacher going to the laundry or doing the ironing. When his clothes get dirty he simply goes to the local hardware store and buys a functional pair of chinos and a workman's shirt and stuffs the old ones in the bin. No mortgage, no wife, no ties, he is a perfectly free agent, unlimited and unbound, incapable of ever settling down.<ref name=\"EmilySargent2011\">{{cite web|last= Sargent|first= Emily|title=Killer instinct: Is Tom Cruise the right man to play Lee Child's savage anti-hero on screen?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/killer-instinct-is-tom-cruise-the-right-man-to-play-lee-childs-savage-anti-hero-on-screen-6252359.html |magazine=[[The Independent]] | accessdate=1 March 2016|date=30 October 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLee Child describes Reacher's obsession to wander about:\n\n<blockquote>He's an ex-military policeman, and he was demobilized in his middle thirties after having served all of his adult life in the [U.S.] Army and having grown up on Marine bases, because his father was a Marine. The idea was to have a character that was plausibly rootless. Most people who are wanderers do it for other reasons\u2014they are mentally ill, or something like that. Reacher is completely competent, but he's just habituated to this fragmented life in the military, so he can't settle into civilian society. The idea of staying anywhere for more than a few days is [[anathema]] to him.<ref name= \"RobertBidinotto2007\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Demeanor and personality==\nReacher himself expounds on a hypothesis about this vagrant life-style in ''[[Never Go Back (Lee Child novel)|Never Go Back]]''. He states that he has a genetic disposition towards roaming about, citing the [[British Empire]], the [[Vikings]], and the [[Polynesians]] as groups with a similar wanderlust. While he accepts that [[Human migration|there was an economical necessity]] behind their voyages, he maintains that \"some of them could not stop\". He feels that long ago when [[Prehistory|humans lived in small bands]], there was a risk of [[inbreeding]] as a result of which a [[gene]] developed over the course of [[evolution]] such that \"every generation and every small band had at least one person who had to wander\". This would lead to \"mixing up of [[gene pool]]s\" and would be \"healthier all around\". Reacher concludes:\n\n{{quote|I think ninety-nine of us grow up to love the campfire, and one grows up to hate it. Ninety-nine of us grow up to fear the howling wolf, and one grows up to envy it. And I'm that guy.\n\nCompelled to spread his [[DNA]] worldwide. Purely for the good of the species.<ref>{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location =London |chapter= Chapter 38}}</ref>}}\n\nReacher's large physique means his character is sometimes mistaken by other people. For example, in ''[[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]'', Reacher is wrongly suspected by the FBI of being involved in a kidnapping, which assesses him (solely on the basis of a few photos) as such: \"The big guy is different. Different clothes, different stance, different physically. He could be foreign, at least partly, or maybe second generation. Fair hair and blue eyes, but there's something in his face. Maybe he's European, perhaps a European mercenary or terrorist.\"<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Die Trying| url= https://archive.org/details/dietrying00chil| url-access= registration|year=|chapter= Chapter 22}}</ref> Reacher is aware of this perception. In ''[[Make Me (novel)|Make Me]]'' Reacher gets off a train in a remote town called Mother's Rest, simply because he likes the name of the town. When he sees a woman approaching him with a look of expectation, he immediately understands that the person she was waiting for must be very tall like him, as it is his standout feature when people first meet him.\n\nIn ''[[Echo Burning]]'', Reacher narrates how he first turned \"his fear into aggression\". He was about four when he watched a television show on space adventures. One episode depicted a [[Extraterrestrial life|space monster]] which then terrified the young Reacher. He was [[Insomnia|unable to sleep]] for days, thinking the monster was under his bed and would get him if he tried to sleep. According to Reacher, he then became angry: \"Not at myself for being afraid, because as far as I was concerned the thing was totally real and I should be afraid. I got mad at the thing for making me afraid. For threatening me\". Reacher then one night \"kind of exploded with fury\". In his words, Reacher \"raced down the monster\" and successfully changed his fear into fury. He also stated he has never been scared since.<ref>{{cite book| title = Echo Burning|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2001|isbn =0-515-13331-0 |location =London | chapter =Chapter 6| quote= One night I just kind of exploded with fury. I yelled O-K-, come out and try it! Just damn well try it! I'll beat the shit right out of you! I raced it down. I turned the fear into aggression.}}</ref>\n\nThis fact is later referenced in ''Never Go Back'', when an Army psychological study of fear in children is cited that shows Reacher to have abnormally fast reflexes and aggression levels at the age of six; Reacher believes that this abnormal level of aggression at that age is not due to genetics, as the Army report suggested, but because he got tired of being frightened, and trained himself \"to turn fear into aggression, automatically\".<ref>{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location = London | chapter= Chapters 30, 38}}</ref>\n\nReacher seldom shows remorse for the numerous felonies he perpetrates and has a primal sense of justice. In ''[[Personal (novel)|Personal]]'', after killing a thug, he defends his actions to his distraught accomplice, Casey Nice, by stating the man could have spent his life performing good deeds such as \"helping old ladies across the street\", \"raising funds for Africa\" or \"volunteering in the library\". Instead the man extorted money and hurt people and when he \"finally he opened the wrong door, what came out at him was his problem, not mine\".<ref name=\"alpha\">{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2014|isbn =9781473508774 |location = London |chapter= Chapter 28}}</ref>\n\nThis primitivity on part of Reacher is commented upon in ''Never Go Back'', in which Reacher is described by Susan Turner as being like \"something feral....It's like you've been sanded down to nothing but yes and no, and you and them, and black and white, and live or die. You're like a predator. Cold and hard.\" (p.&nbsp;176\u2013177) However, when she witnesses Reacher's outrage at the hurt inflicted upon an innocent waitress, she reconsiders and states that he is actually not feral as she had earlier presumed. Furthermore, she notes that Reacher had until then attempted to solve only her problems, neglecting the problems of his own:\n\n<blockquote> And you've done nothing but chip away at my problem. You're ignoring your own, with the Big Dog. Which is just as serious. Therefore, you still care for others. Which means you can't really be feral. I imagine caring for others is the first thing to go. And you still know right from wrong. Which all means you're OK.<ref name=\"bravo\">{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 35}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis underlying kindness perceived by Turner is visible in many of Reacher's actions: he stands up for the right of women in both ''[[Echo Burning]]'', whose central plot involves him aiding a woman's escape from her abusive husband, and in ''[[Worth Dying For (novel)|Worth Dying For]]'', in which he breaks the nose of an abusive husband for beating up his wife.<ref>{{cite book| title = Worth Dying For|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2010|isbn =9781407083131 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 6| quote= Reacher hit him, a straight right to the nose, a big vicious blow, his knuckles driving through cartilage and bone and crushing it all flat.}}</ref> He is also shown to be sympathetic to those in need, as seen in ''[[The Hard Way (novel)|The Hard Way]]'' where he bequeaths Edward Lane's fees paid to him for the medical treatment and living expenses of a man whom Lane had betrayed many years back.<ref>{{cite book|title = The Hard Way|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2006|isbn = 0-385-33669-1|location = London|chapter = Chapter 47|quote = I'm going to send Hobart down to Birmingham or Nashville and get him fixed up right. I'm going to buy him a lifetime's supply of spare parts and I'm going to rent him a place to live and I'm going to give him some walking-around money because my guess is he's not very employable right now. At least not in his old trade. And then if there's anything left, then sure, I'll buy myself a new shirt.|url = https://archive.org/details/hardwa00chil}}</ref>\n\nThis point is further elucidated in ''Personal'', when Reacher reminisces while standing at his mother's grave:\n\n<blockquote>She had said, 'You've got the strength of two normal boys. What are you going to do with it?' I hadn't replied. Our silence was part of the ritual. She answered for me. She said, 'You're going to do the right thing.' And I had tried, mostly, which had sometimes caused me trouble, and sometimes won me medals of my own.<ref name=\"foxtrot\">{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2014|isbn =9781473508774 |location = London | chapter= Chapter 18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Skills==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n\nReacher is described as proficient in hand-to-hand combat. He is quite fast for his height, and often fights opponents his size or larger. His skill is attributed to the fact that he grew up all over the world, due to being in a Marine Corps family. While he is not a master in any one form of combat, he tends to incorporate moves from various styles. His favorite moves are headbutts, elbow strikes, and kicks to the groin. As Child once put it, \"Reacher's fighting style is like a running chainsaw\". Reacher generally goes with the flow of the fight, caring about winning more than how he wins. However, he plans out how to strike first or react to the first strike, and how he'll make sure the other person never fights him again. As he puts it, \"The other guy cares how he wins, I care about pissing on the other guy's grave.\"\n\nReacher has an internal clock. He sets a time to wake up at and his body automatically awakens. He often sets a timer in fights to try and get a tactical edge. Reacher also has a fascination with numbers. In ''[[Bad Luck and Trouble]]'', Reacher uses this to deduce that the amount of money deposited without his knowledge into his bank account was an attempt by Neagley, his colleague from the Military Police Corps, to contact him.\n\nReacher has extremely acute deduction skills. He generally gains his information simply from talking to people or making minute observations. He will pick up on a simple pause and relate it back to what he is trying figure out. He is known as one of the best investigators the Military Police Corps had to offer, and he led a special unit tasked with difficult cases.\n\nReacher is also described as skilled [[marksman]], principally in ''[[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]]'', being the only non-[[United States Marine Corps|Marine]] to win the US Marine Corps [[Wimbledon Cup|1000 Yard Invitational rifle competition]].\n\n==Habits and beliefs==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2015}}\nReacher has a love for music, especially [[blues]].<ref name=\"Child 1997 p. 522\">Child (1997), ''Killing Floor'', p. 522.</ref> It was this affinity that inspires Reacher to get off the bus at the start of ''[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]]'', and in the same novel reveals that he has a music collection in his head, replaying tracks as he travels without needing the technology others seem to be obsessed with and burdened by. Reacher explains this to detectives investigating an early morning suicide on a near-deserted [[New York City Subway|New York subway]] near a visit to a [[blues]] club on [[Bleecker Street]].<ref>{{cite book| title = [[Gone Tomorrow]] |last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =| chapter= Chapter 7| page= | isbn= }}</ref>\n\nReacher espouses no personal religious beliefs but is scathing in his dismissal of town boss Thurman's [[fundamentalist Christianity|fundamentalist Christian]] position in the novel ''Nothing to Lose'': When asked if he is \"born again\" Reacher says, \"Once was enough for me\" and later rhetorically asks Thurman, \"I'm here to visit the sick and you want to have me beaten up? What kind of Christian are you?\"<ref>{{cite book| title = Nothing To Lose |last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =| chapter= Chapters 38, 44| page= | isbn= }}</ref> He also mentions at the opening of ''[[Bad Luck and Trouble]]'' that he avoids [[Alaska Airlines]] because \"they put a scripture card on the meal trays\".<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 4 |isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = 15}}</ref>\n\nReacher is also critical of the corruption of traditional spelling, such as the use of contractions like \"U\" for \"you\", \"lo\" for \"low\", disliking the absence of the apostrophe in ''DONT WALK'' pedestrian signage before they were replaced, then noting he also disapproved of replacing words with pictures.<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 20 |isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = }}</ref>\n\nWhile Reacher knows how to drive, in ''[[A Wanted Man]]'' he professes to be a bad driver, and in ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' he says he cannot rent a car because he does not have a driver's license.<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 22|isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = }}</ref> In ''Without Fail'' Agent Frolich trawls various databases for Reacher, only to discover he is effectively untraceable, because without a driver's license he has no photograph and no address.<ref>{{cite book|title = Without Fail|url = https://archive.org/details/withoutfail00chil|url-access = registration|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =  |year = |chapter= Chapter 1 |isbn = |location = |page = }}</ref>\n\nAmong his few indulgences are casual sex and coffee, which he drinks constantly.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref>{{cite book|title =The Enemy|url =https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780440245995|url-access =registration|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = |year = |chapter=  |isbn =  |location = |page = |quote= [Joe] was probably the only other human on the planet who liked coffee as much as I did. He started drinking it when he was six. I copied him immediately. I was four. Neither of us has stopped since. The Reacher brothers' need for caffeine makes [[heroin addiction]] look like an amusing little take-it-or-leave-it sideline.}}</ref><ref name=\"echo\">{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = The Enemy |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2004 |isbn = 0-553-81585-7 | chapter= Chapter 5}}</ref>\n\n==Physical appearance==\nBryan Curtis, in an interview with Lee Child, describes Reacher thus:\n\n<blockquote>His face looked like it had been chipped out of rock by a sculptor who had ability but not much time.<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/></blockquote>\n\nFrom ''A Wanted Man'': \"He was one of the largest men she had ever seen outside the NFL. He was extremely tall, and extremely broad, and long-armed, and long-legged. The lawn chair was regular size, but it looked tiny under him. It was bent and crushed out of shape. His knuckles were nearly touching the ground. His neck was thick and his hands were the size of dinner plates...A wild man. But not really. Underneath everything else seemed strangely civilized....His gaze was both wise and appealing, both friendly and bleak, both frank and utterly cynical.\"<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= A Wanted Man | url= https://archive.org/details/wantedmanreacher00chil| url-access= registration| year= 2012| page= [https://archive.org/details/wantedmanreacher00chil/page/169 169]}}</ref>\n\nReacher is described as being {{convert|6|ft|5|in}} tall, weighing {{convert|210|-|250|lb|kg}} and having a {{convert|50|in|cm|adj=on}} chest.<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\"/><ref name=\"DenOfGeek\">{{cite web|last= Stansfield |first= James |title= Who is Jack Reacher? |url=  https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/23502/who-is-jack-reacher |magazine= Den of Geek |date= 22 November 2012|accessdate= 7 March 2016}}</ref> In ''[[Never Go Back (Lee Child novel)|Never Go Back]]'', he is described as having \"a six-pack like a cobbled city street, a chest like a suit of NFL armor, biceps like basketballs, and subcutaneous fat like a Kleenex tissue.\"<ref name=\"bravo\"/> In his youth, his physical appearance likened to that of a 'bulked-up greyhound'.<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7 |page= 41}}</ref> He also reveals that his size is purely genetic; he states in ''[[Persuader]]''<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Persuader | year= 2003 |chapter= Chapter 3 |quote= I never work out.}}</ref> and ''Never Go Back'' that he is not much of an exercise enthusiast.<ref name= \"bravo\"/>\n\nHe has various scars, most notably a collection of roughly stitched scars on his abdomen caused by a bombing in Lebanon,<ref>{{cite book |title= Killing Floor| first= Lee| last= Child| year= 1999 |quote= He had served thirteen years in the Army, and the only time he was wounded it wasn't with a bullet. It was with a fragment of a Marine sergeant's jawbone.}}</ref> with ugly raised welts that are later instrumental in saving his life, a {{convert|3|to|4|in|cm|0|adj=mid|-wide}} white scar that intersects his [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] scar that he received during a knife fight in ''[[Gone Tomorrow]]''. Reacher attributes his survival to the rough [[Mobile Army Surgical Hospital|MASH]] stitch work.<ref>{{cite book |title= Killing Floor| first= Lee| last= Child| year= 1999 | chapter= Chapter 83}}</ref>\n\nHis various other scars include one from a chest shot with a [[.38 Special]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Never Go Back|url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780385344340|url-access= registration| first= Lee| last= Child| chapter= Chapter 35| quote= She traced around his ear, and his neck, and his chest. She put the tip of her pinkie in his bullet hole. It fit just right. 'A .38,' he said.}}</ref> and a [[powder burn]] from a near-miss at [[point blank range]], and one on his arm where his brother struck him with a chisel.<ref name=\"charlie\">{{cite book| title = The Enemy|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2004|isbn = 0-553-81585-7 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 6}}</ref>\n\nHe suffers his first ever broken nose in ''Worth Dying For'', at over 50 years of age.  He resets the bone with a thump from his palm and later puts on a plaster bandage made of [[duct tape]].\n\n==Family==\nReacher's maternal grandfather, Laurent Moutier, was a furniture restorer in [[Paris]], who, at age 30, volunteered for the [[French Army]] in 1914 at the outbreak of [[World War I]], fighting at [[Battle of Verdun|Verdun]] and [[The Somme]].<ref group=\"note\">The final days in the life of Reacher's grandfather, with [[flashback (continuity)|flashbacks]] to various earlier times in his life, appear in the story ''[[Second Son (Lee Child novel)|Second Son]]'', taking place when Reacher was 13 years old.</ref> Between 1919 and 1929 he was commissioned to produce wooden legs for wounded veterans. Josephine Moutier was his only child. He died in 1974 at age 90. Jack, as a boy, met him three times and is described as having liked him. In ''Second Son'' Reacher is impressed with his grandfather's stoic acceptance of approaching death and says that \"A man who survived [[Battle of Verdun|Verdun]] and [[The Somme]] as well as the WWII anti-Nazi Resistance has already beaten the odds\".\n\nReacher's mother, Josephine Moutier Reacher, born in France, was 30 years old when Reacher was born.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> She met Reacher's father in [[Korea]] and married him in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"charlie\"/> When she was only 13, she joined the [[French Resistance]] and under the alias \"Beatrice\" worked with ''Le Chemin de Fer Humain'' (the Human Railroad), saving 80 men. She [[garrote]]d a schoolmate, a boy who threatened to give her up to the [[Nazis]], and would later receive the ''[[M\u00e9daille de la R\u00e9sistance]]'' (the Resistance Medal) for further heroism.<ref name=TheEnemy>{{cite book|last1=Child|first1=Lee|title=The Enemy|date=April 2005|publisher=Dell Publishing Company|isbn=9780440241010| chapter= Chapter 19}}</ref> She was widowed in 1988,{{refn|group=note|It is mentioned in the novel ''Personal'' that Josephine Reacher died in 1990<ref name=\"foxtrot\"/> while according to Lee Child's official website, her husband died two years before her.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/> Thus simple arithmetic dictates her husband is bound to have died in 1988.}} and died in 1990 at the age of 60 of lung cancer.<ref name=\"foxtrot\"/> Reacher described his mother as \"[[French people|gallic]], feminine, obstinate,\" and \"[the] most stubborn woman possible.\" He also branded her a [[Fatalism|fatalist]] as she had concealed her cancer from her children and had refused treatment for a one-year period before her death.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> However Reacher compares her favourably to his father: \"My father hadn't killed the enemy at the age of thirteen. But my mother had. She had lived through desperate times and she had stepped up and done what was necessary.\"<ref name=TheEnemy/> Reacher also has great respect for his mother: at her funeral he buried his ''Silver Star'' medal with her,<ref name= \"foxtrot\"/> and on learning of her role in [[World War II]], states that he became the man he was because of her.<ref name=TheEnemy/> In ''[[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]'', when the FBI mistakenly assumes Reacher to be in league with the book's villains, the Bureau experts observing Reacher's demeanor on footage from a security camera consider him to be \"a foreigner, probably a European mercenary\".\n\nReacher's father, Stan Reacher, was a [[United States Marine Corps]] captain, who served in [[Korean War|Korea]] and [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. His military service kept his family continually moving all around the world to various military bases. At the time of the short story ''Second Son'', when Jack was 13, he was stationed in [[Okinawa]] and involved in preparing [[contingency plan]]s for an invasion of Mainland [[China]]. In the same short story, Stan Reacher is depicted as \"a child of the [[Great Depression|depression]],\" coming from a miserly [[New England]] family, and as a result was a proponent of the theories of \"Waste not, want not,\" \"Make do and mend,\" and \"Don't make an exhibition of oneself.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Second Son |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2011 |isbn = 9781446497111 | chapter = 13}}</ref>  Jack described his father as \"a plain [[New Hampshire]] [[Yankee]] with an implacable horror of anything fancy...he had no use for wealth and excess. Very compartmentalized guy. Gentle, shy, sweet, loving man, but a stone-cold killer. Next to him I look like [[Liberace]]\".<ref name=\"delta\">{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Without Fail |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2002 |isbn = 978-0-515-14431-4| chapter= Chapter 11}}</ref> Jack Reacher furthermore highlighted this dichotomy in his father's behaviour by stating that he would be engaging in violent actions such as \"how to angle a claymore mine so the little ball bearings explode outward at exactly the right angle to rip the enemy's spines out of their backs with maximum efficiency\" one day, and the next day would be doing something calmer, like \"watching birds,\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = The Enemy |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2004 |isbn = 0-553-81585-7 |chapter= Chapter 14}}</ref> After military service, \"there was no place left for people like him.\"<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref name=\"delta\"/> He died in 1988.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/> James Stanfield, in an article concludes that \"Reacher clearly looked up to and idolised his father, and though Reacher's reasons for leaving the service were very different to his dad's, they've ended up at the same point.\"<ref name=DenOfGeek/>\n\nReacher had only one sibling, brother Joe Reacher, who was two years older than Jack.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref name=\"echo\"/> Physically, Joe was one inch taller {{height|ft=6|in=6}} and a \"little slighter\" than his younger sibling, weighing {{convert|220|lb}}.<ref name=\"echo\"/><ref name= \"charlie\"/> Joe was born on a military base in the [[Philippines]], and Jack is described as helping Joe beat up the kids who gave him trouble in school, and vice versa.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Killing Floor |publisher = Penguin Group (USA) Inc. |location= 375 Hudson Street, New York, New York 10014, USA |year = 1997 |isbn = 1-4295-1117-6 |chapter= Chapter 10}}</ref> However Joe also had scuffles with his own brother, given the scar that Jack had put on his forehead during their childhood.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> Joe was also a [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] graduate, and spent five years in [[military intelligence]], where he never won any of the \"good medals\", only the \"junk awards.<ref name=echo/> \"Jack described his brother as being pedantic, and called him a perfectionist, \"a man horrified with anything less than the best.\"<ref name=\"echo\"/> Joe is described as joining the [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury Department]], and died at age 38 in the line of duty, having arranged a meeting with a potential investigation subject.<ref name=\"Child 1997 p. 522\"/> Because he was killed in the line of duty, his name can be found on the Treasury Department's Roll of Honor.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Critical reception and analysis==\nCritics have noted the strong theme of \"justice\" pervading the character as well as the book series. Claire E. White, characterises the titular protagonist as: \"wanderer, a hero who is a bit alienated from the establishment, but whose sense of justice is strong. He reminds (''me'') a bit of a character from the Old West: the strong, mysterious loner who never stays in town for long.\"<ref name=\"ClaireWhite2001\">{{cite web| last= White |first= Claire |title= A Conversation With Lee Child|url=  http://www.writerswrite.com/journal/aug01/a-conversation-with-lee-child-8012 |magazine= The Internet Writing Journal |accessdate= 1 March 2016|date=2001 }}</ref> Mike Ripley detected the influence of [[Jack Schaefer|Jack Schaefer's]] western novel ''[[Shane (novel)|Shane]]'' in the Reacher novel ''Echo Burning'' while Bob Cornwell calls the debut Jack Reacher novel '' Killing Floor'' \"a classic western\".<ref name=\"Bob Cornwell\">{{cite web |last= Cornwell |first= Bob |title= Lee Child Interview |url= http://www.twbooks.co.uk/crimescene/leechildinterview.htm |magazine= TwBooks |accessdate= 1 March 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150711233606/http://www.twbooks.co.uk/crimescene/leechildinterview.htm |archive-date= 11 July 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> [[Grantland]] columnist Bryan Curtis calls the character \"a protective figure, an avenging angel\" and quotes the author [[Michael Connelly]] describing the Reacher book series as: \"These are postmodern Westerns, they're ''Shane''. A stranger comes to town and sets things right. Then he leaves town.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> The critic Emily Sargent says of the fictional Reacher: \"just the kind of no-nonsense, ramrod hero an intelligent five-year old would dream up: a strapping, broad-shouldered, idealized father-figure, something akin to God in his wisdom and power, alternately benevolent and overwhelmingly cruel, fair but firm. Good at saving damsels in distress and sorting out bad guys.\"<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/>\n\nRick Gekoski, writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', takes a similar if darker interpretation of the character: \"Reacher is, of course, in a long line of American outcast heroes who abjure emotional ties, head out into the wilderness and take upon their own broad shoulders the primitive moral conscience of the tribe. Too immature to make a sexual commitment, obsessed with death and terror, this archetypal hero of American fiction was first described in [[Leslie Fiedler|Leslie Fiedler's]] classic ''Love and Death in the American Novel'' (1960).\"<ref name=\"RickGekoski2013\">{{cite web| last= Gekoski |first= Rick |title= Why I love Lee Child's Jack Reacher novels |url=  https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2013/aug/29/lee-child-jack-reacher |magazine= [[The Guardian]] |accessdate= 1 March 2016 |date= 29 August 2013 }}</ref> In the same article he also questions whether Fiedler would find that Reacher's [[hypermasculinity]] is a sign of the character's \"repressed [[homosexuality]]\".<ref name= \"RickGekoski2013\"/>\n\nMalcolm Gladwell, in an article for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', perceives a difference in the Reacher character and the traditional Western characters in terms of the symbolism they represent to the general public. In his opinion \"The traditional Western was a fantasy about lawfulness: it was based on a longing for order among those who had been living without it for too long. The heroes conduct themselves according to strict rules of chivalry. They act\u2014 insofar as it is possible \u2014with restraint. In the world we live in today, by contrast, we have too much order: we are, as we have been reminded so frequently lately, over-policed. Our contemporary fantasy is about lawlessness: about what would happen if the institutions of civility melted away and all we were left with was a hard-muscled, rangy guy who could do all the necessary calculations in his head to insure that the bad guy got what he had coming. That's why there are rarely any police in Reacher novels\u2014or judges or courts or lawyers or any discussion or consideration of the law. Nor is there any restraint on the part of the hero. He's not pointing toward a more civilized tomorrow. He's leading us back into the wilderness, with the reassurance that our psychopaths are bigger and stronger than the bad guys' psychopaths.\"<ref name=\"Malcolm Gladwell2015\">{{cite web| last= Gladwell |first= Malcolm |title= The Lawless Pleasures of Lee Child's Jack Reacher Novels |url=  http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-lawless-pleasures-of-lee-childs-jack-reacher-novels |magazine= [[The New Yorker]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 9 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nSargent also notes the dichotomy in Reacher's character, stating that he is intellectual and generous despite his exterior appearance of being \"unkempt, unshaven and out of uniform, a loner, avenger, perpetual outsider at odds with the army\". In Sargent's express opinion:\n\n{{quote|The thing about Reacher is that he is not just a thug, even if a well-meaning thug in the manner of, say, [[John Rambo|Rambo]] or [[Bruce Willis]]. He is also a thinker, an intellectual, capable of quoting [[Nietzsche]] or coming up with the etymology of \"vagrant\". And he speaks French....\n\n...He therefore brings a certain amount of liberal-leaning finesse and \u00e9lan to his encounters. He is sympathetic to deserters from the [[Iraq War]] and particularly severe on capitalist profiteers. You feel he would probably turn up at an [[Occupy Wall Street]] demo. There is something of the hippie in his rootless roaming around America, seeking out injustice and righting wrongs.<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/>}}\n\nCurtis concurs, remarking that \"Reacher isn't just a mindless vigilante. He can also be a liberal do-gooder. He has expressed sympathy for gays in the military and undocumented immigrants. In Child's latest book,'' A Wanted Man'', Reacher worries that the [[Patriot Act]] will lead to all sorts of 'national security bullshit.' Child has invented a kind of progressive vigilantism. The scumbag is killed, but usually for the right reasons.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\nMultiple critics have pointed out that the Jack Reacher character is characterized by his spells of silence,<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/><ref name= \"MichaelCavacini2014\"/> with Curtis claiming \"Reacher's classic line is silence.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\nOthers have been critical of the various implausibilities and contradictions present in the character and his behavior. Notes ''[[The Washington Post]]'' journalist Kevin Nance: \"The unlikelihoods and outright impossibilities stack up. Ever a frugal sort, Reacher travels mostly by hitchhiking (as he does at the beginning of \"A Wanted Man\" and 2001's \"Echo Burning,\" both set roughly in the time they were written), even though the practice is roughly as current as bellbottoms and even though his appearance is, as previously established, notably simian. (Not that this deters a series of smart, attractive young women, most of them officers of the law, from jumping into bed with him.) And although he's a loner who seems never so happy \u2014 rather like Agent Cooper in \"Twin Peaks\" \u2014 as when sitting quietly in a diner with a cup of black coffee and a piece of pie, he has an uncanny knack for stumbling into the worst kinds of trouble, almost none of it connected to himself.\"<ref name=\"KevinNance2012\">{{cite web| last= Nance |first= Kevin |title= Why is the character of Jack Reacher so popular? |url=  https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/why-is-the-character-of-jack-reacher-so-popular/2012/12/13/dcdfe816-3d7d-11e2-ae43-cf491b837f7b_story.html# |magazine= [[The Washington Post]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 14 December 2012 }}</ref> Michael Cavacini has concurred with this, stating that unlike traditional [[whodunit]]s, where a detective \"simply solves a problem because it's his job\", Reacher has no formal reason to be involved in anything and consequently \"seems to always wind up in a situation where something goes wrong and he must make right\".<ref name=\"MichaelCavacini2014\">{{cite web| last= Cavacini |first= Michael |title= An Interview With International Best-Selling Author Lee Child|url=  https://michaelcavacini.com/2014/09/04/an-interview-with-international-best-selling-author-lee-child/ |accessdate= 1 March 2016|date=2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Accomplices==\nLee Child has described Reacher's accomplices and their characterization and origin in the following terms: \" The whole cast for each book is new. It kind of depends on what the scenario is and what the set up is. Do I use people that I actually know? In a way yeah, because you met people and you regard them as meta-typical as one thing or another \u2013 so as a large extent, yes, they are based on people I've met but not specific individuals.\"<ref name=\"AmieFlanagan2014\">{{cite web|last=Flanagan |first= Amie|title=An Interview With Lee Child |url= http://www.keystothepage.com/interviews/interview-lee-child/|magazine= Keys To The Page |date= 9 September 2014|accessdate= 8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-military era===\n'''Jill Hemingway''', age 34 according to a police transmission, was a suspended [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent operating freelance in New York during 1977. She had been investigating the criminal activities of a New York mobster, Croselli but her investigation had been shut down and she had been suspended, pending review as part of a deal cut by Croselli with the FBI. She had since tried to unsuccessfully bring Croselli down by getting him to boast of his crimes on tape. She admitted that bringing down Croselli had become somewhat of an obsession for her, stating \"[Croselli] burns her up.\"<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7|location = |pages = 91}}</ref> Hemingway is described as a thin, pale, nervous, blonde woman and she teams up with a nearly seventeen year old Reacher in the [[novella]] ''High Heat'' to incriminate Croselli. She suffered from heart-related ailments and she dies near the end of the story due to a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] after having accomplished her goal. Reacher commented, \"She died young, but she had a smile on her face.\"<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child |first= Lee |publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7|location = |pages = 125}}</ref>\n\n===Military era===\n* '''Elizabeth Deveraux''', late 30s, is a former Marine serving as a [[county sheriff]] in [[Carter Crossing, Mississippi]] in 1997. She appears in ''The Affair'', where she tacitly condones Reacher's highly illegal ways of getting rid of some unsavory characters. She was a potential lover for Reacher, as they had sex several times, but ended up drifting apart.\n* '''Karla Dixon''', age unknown, possibly late 30s is a [[forensic accountant]]; formerly a Major in the Army and part of Reacher's 'Special Investigators Unit', which he formed and led in the 90s. They are reunited in ''Bad Luck & Trouble'' and secretly rekindle an affair, which they regret not starting back in the Army. She is described as 'dark, very pretty, comparatively small' and slim.  She is extremely good with numbers and shares Reacher's fascination with mathematics.\n* '''General Leon Garber''', retired, was Reacher's former commanding officer, mentor and close friend. His only child is Jodie. He risked his life to help Reacher in ''Die Trying'', and willed him his house, as his daughter is wealthy, didn't want it and already owns her own New York City home. He also appears in ''The Enemy'' and ''The Affair'', and (through his funeral) in ''Tripwire''.\n* '''Jodie Garber-Jacob''', 30, is the daughter of General Leon Garber. She met and fell in love with Reacher when she was 15 and was off-limits to him. In ''Tripwire'', she is divorced, using her married name, working as a corporate attorney and reunites romantically with him after her father's funeral. She and Reacher lived together in New York City and upstate New York in Leon's house which was left in his will to Reacher, his surrogate son. She is mentioned in ''Echo Burning'' as having moved to Europe. She appears in ''Tripwire'', and ''The Visitor'' (\"Running Blind\" in the United States).\n* '''Eileen Ann Hutton''', age unknown, is a Brigadier General in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Army's Judge Advocate General's Corps]]. She and Reacher had a relationship prior to, and featured in, ''One Shot''.\n* '''Dominique Kohl''', 29, was a Sergeant First Class on the way up and assigned to Reacher's unit when he was a captain in the Army. She appears in ''Persuader'', where Reacher remembers the events that led to her death ten years earlier.  Kohl is mentioned again in ''Personal'', when Reacher partners with a woman who reminds him of Kohl.\n* '''Stan Lowrey''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He is handsome, youthful, and full of energy. A kind of man that gets the job done. He appears in ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' and ''The Affair''.\n* '''Duncan Munro''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He appears in ''The Affair''.\n* '''Frances Neagley''', late 30s, is a partner with a successful private security firm, and former Army Master Sergeant and Military Policeman. She is of medium height, slim, and has dark hair and eyes. She spends large amounts of time in the gym and has a purely [[platonic relationship]] with Reacher. However, in ''Night School'' (2016), NSA senior Deputy Marian Sinclair notes Neagley's attraction to Reacher, and her refusal to sleep with him.<ref name=\"NightSchool187\">{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Night School | year= 2016 |location= London| publisher= Transworld Publishers, 2016 |page= 187}}</ref>  Reacher points out that Neagley has [[Haphephobia|haptephobia]], \"A fear of being touched.\"<ref name=\"NightSchool187\" /> When Sinclair asks if the condition is as a result of assault, Reacher responds, \"She says she was born with it.\"<ref name=\"NightSchool188\">{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Night School | year= 2016 |location= London| publisher= Transworld Publishers, 2016 |page= 188}}</ref> Her demeanor suggests that she could be considered a female counterpart to Reacher. Rarely impressed, Reacher describes her as sometimes scary. She appears in ''Without Fail'', ''The Affair'' and ''Bad Luck and Trouble'',  ''Night School'', and ''Small Wars'' and is mentioned in ''Never Go Back''. The first page of ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' includes a dedication \"For the real Frances L. Neagley\", who won a [[Bouchercon]] charity auction for the naming rights to a character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/features/arts/offthepage/blog/2007/09/characters_welcomed_and_you_can_be_one_too.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232851/http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/features/arts/offthepage/blog/2007/09/characters_welcomed_and_you_can_be_one_too.html |archivedate= 3 March 2016 |title=Characters welcomed! And you can be one, too |website=weblogs.sun-sentinel.com |publisher=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |first=Oline |last=Cogdill |date=13 September 2007 |access-date=29 March 2017 }}</ref>\n* '''Dave O'Donnell''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He appears in ''Bad Luck and Trouble''. He is \"tall, fair, handsome, like a stockbroker... carries an army blade in one pocket and a pair of ceramic [[brass-knuckles]] in the other.\" The ceramic knuckles are made from a composite stronger than steel, harder than brass and gets past any metal detector. He is meticulous, doesn't mind paperwork, and is usually underestimated because he looks like a white-collar office worker.\n* '''Lieutenant Summer''', 25, is an African-American Lieutenant in the Army Military Police. She is cute, petite and slender, and appears in ''The Enemy''. She is Reacher's accomplice throughout the novel and they have a brief relationship. She is promoted to Captain at the end of the novel.\n\n===Wandering era===\n* '''Alice Amanda Aaron''', an attorney, appears in ''Echo Burning''.\n* '''Michelle Chang''', an ex-FBI agent turned private investigator. Appears in ''Make Me''.\n* '''Susan Duffy''', appears in ''Persuader''.\n* '''M.E. (Mary Ellen) Froelich''', a Secret Service Agent, appears in ''Without Fail''.\n* '''Carmen Greer''', a woman with an abusive husband, appears in ''Echo Burning''.\n* '''Lisa Harper''', another FBI agent, appears in ''The Visitor'' (''Running Blind'' in the United States).\n* '''Holly Johnson''', an FBI agent, appears in ''Die Trying''.\n* '''Detective Theresa Lee''' an NYPD Detective, appears in ''Gone Tomorrow''.\n* '''Casey Nice''', 28, described as having \"blonde hair and green eyes and a heart shaped face\"<ref>{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Bantam Press|year = 2014|isbn = 9780593073827| chapter= Chapter 2}}</ref> is a CIA analyst lent out to the [[United States Department of State|State Department]]. She reminds Reacher of Dominique Kohl and he sees her as a \"young, fit woman in the peak of condition, lean, smooth, somehow flexible and fluent and elastic\".<ref name=\"alpha\" />  She is shown to take [[Anxiolytic|anti-anxiety medication]] and shares a platonic relationship with Reacher. Casey was born and raised in downstate [[Illinois]], is a graduate from [[Yale University]] and has a distinct American accent which is exploited by Reacher<ref>{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Bantam Press|year = 2014|isbn = 9780593073827| chapter= Chapter 30}}</ref> when she accompanies him to London in ''Personal''.\n* '''Lauren Pauling''', appears in ''The Hard Way''.\n* '''Helen Rodin''', only appears in ''One Shot'' and in the live action movie ''Jack Reacher'' based on the book.\n* '''Officer Elizabeth Roscoe''', 30, is a Margrave, Georgia police officer in ''Killing Floor''.\n* '''Julia Sorensen''', 47, teams up with Reacher in ''A Wanted Man''.\n* '''Susan Turner''', the Commanding Officer of Reacher's old unit, appears in ''61 Hours'' and ''Never Go Back''.\n* '''Vaughan''', exact age unknown, is a police officer in Hope, Colorado. She appears in ''Nothing to Lose''.\n\n== Adaptations ==\n===Film and television===\n{{main|Jack Reacher (film)|Jack Reacher: Never Go Back}}\n[[File:Jack Reacher poster.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Theatrical poster of 2012 film ''Jack Reacher'' depicting Tom Cruise]]\nThe 2012 [[action thriller]] film ''[[Jack Reacher (film)|Jack Reacher]]'' was adapted from the 2005 novel ''One Shot'' and starred [[Tom Cruise]] in the title role.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/07/tom-cruise-locked-to-play-jack-reacher-in-one-shot-for-paramount-and-skydance/ |title=Tom Cruise Locked To Play Jack Reacher In 'One Shot' For Paramount And Skydance |magazine=Deadline |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The film was directed by [[Christopher McQuarrie]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/why-hasnt-paramount-started-making-jack-reacher-movies |title=Why hasn't Paramount started making Jack Reacher movies? |work=HitFix |date=20 October 2010 |accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> Cruise reprised the role in the sequel, ''[[Jack Reacher: Never Go Back]]'', an adaptation of the 18th Jack Reacher book ''Never Go Back'', which was directed by [[Edward Zwick]], and released 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Ed Zwick In Talks To Direct 'Jack Reacher' Sequel|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/jack-reacher-sequel-ed-zwick-director-paramount-1201429671/|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=deadline.com|date=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nTom Cruise's casting was met with criticism from fans of the book series, primarily because the disparity in their heights, with Reacher portrayed as a blond, {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}} tall, 250-pound man in the novels, while Cruise is a {{convert|5|ft|7|in|abbr=on}} tall brunette<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\"/><ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/>) In 2012 Child commented on Cruise's casting by saying, \"Reacher\u2019s size in the books is a metaphor for an unstoppable force, which Cruise portrays in his own way.\" In 2018, Child expressed the opinion that the fans were right after the height of actor portraying the character.<ref name=\"DenOfGeek\" />\n\nOn November 14, 2018, Child announced that he made a deal with [[Skydance Television]] and [[Paramount Television]] to produce a ''Jack Reacher'' series based on Child's novels, during which feature films would no longer be produced. He also stated that [[Tom Cruise]] would not be returning to the role, and that another actor would be cast in the role, which he hoped would more properly represent the character than seen in the films. [[Paramount Television]] and [[Skydance Television]] are said to be produce the potential series. Child said of the recasting:\n\n<blockquote>\"I really enjoyed working with Cruise. He's a really, really nice guy. We had a lot of fun. But ultimately the readers are right. The size of Reacher is really, really important and it's a big component of who he is...So what I've decided to do is \u2013 there won't be any more movies with Tom Cruise. Instead we're going to take it to Netflix or something like that. Long-form streaming television, with a completely new actor. We're rebooting and starting over and we're going to try and find the perfect guy.<ref name=DeadlineHollywood>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/jack-reacher-tv-series-no-tom-cruise-lee-child-1202502218/|title='Jack Reacher' TV Series In The Works|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 14, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn July 15, 2019, Varity report that Amazon will develop the series for Amazon Prime with [[Nick Santora]] as the showrunner, writer and executive producer alongside with Child, Don Granger, Christopher McQuarrie, David Ellison, Dana Goldberg and Marcy Ross<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/amazon-jack-reacher-series-1203267743/|title=Amazon to Develop \u2018Jack Reacher\u2019 Series|last=Throne|first=Nick|magazine=Variety|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jack-reacher-tv-series-works-at-amazon-1224429|title='Jack Reacher' TV Series in the Works at Amazon|website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date= 2019-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n===In other authors' works===\n* Reacher is mentioned several times in the Stephen King novel ''[[Under the Dome (novel)|Under the Dome]]'', where he is described by the character Colonel Cox as \"the toughest goddam Army cop that ever served, in my humble opinion.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Stephen|title=Under the Dome: Part 2: A Novel|date=2014|publisher=Pocket Books|location=New York|isbn=9781476767284| page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476767284/page/180 180]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476767284|url-access=registration|accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|Chester's Mills' police officer Jackie Wettington is revealed to have previously served as a military policewoman in Germany, and she is recommended to Colonel Cox by Reacher.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} }} Lee Child's endorsement of ''Under the Dome'' appears on the cover of at least one edition of the book.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n* Reacher is referred to in the ''[[Hunt for Reacher]]'' series of novels and short stories by [[Diane Capri]], but is never explicitly seen. Capri has said in an interview that the series was inspired by her wondering \"What's [Reacher] doing between books?\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sharonkowensimplycreating.wordpress.com/2012/02/04/dont-know-jack-interview-with-diane-capri/ |title=Don't Know Jack: Interview With Diane Capri |website =SharonKowenSimplycreating.wordpress.com |date=}}</ref>\n* In the introduction to ''Good and Valuable Consideration'', it is mentioned that while creating his 'Nick Heller' series character, [[Joseph Finder]] borrowed many cues from Lee Child's Jack Reacher series.<ref>{{cite book |title=  Good And Valuable Consideration |publisher= Sphere |year= 2014 |pages= 1 |isbn= 978-0-7515-6349-8| quote= When Joseph Finder decided to try a series character, he took many cues from Lee Child's Jack Reacher}}</ref>\n* David Baldacci's character [[John Puller]] is a \"bloody ripoff of Jack Reacher\" according to Lee Child.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/lee-child-on-jack-reacher-how-the-best-selling-author-writes-his-mysteries-9959227.html|title=Lee Child on Jack Reacher | website=The Independent|date=Jan 15, 2015}}</ref> Child avenged himself by having Jack Reacher break all the fingers of a villain named David Baldacci in \"Never Go Back\".\n* [[Jude Hardin]] has written about Jack Reacher in the novels ''The Jack Reacher Files: Fugitive'' and ''The Jack Reacher Experiment: Dead Ringer''.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[Jack Reacher (book series)]]\n* [[Jack (hero)]]\n* [[Military brat]]\n* [[List of fictional military brats]]\n\n==References==\n'''Explanatory notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''[[Jack Reacher (book series)]]'''\n* {{cite book |last= Child| first= Lee |authorlink=Lee Child |title=[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]] |publisher=Putnam |location=New York |date=1997  |isbn=0515123447 |oclc=38994823 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]] |publisher= Jove |location= New York |year= 1999 |isbn= 0515125024 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Without Fail]] |publisher= Putnam |location= New York |year= 2002 |isbn= 0399148612 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Tripwire (novel)|Tripwire]] |publisher= Putnam |location= New York |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-0385336666 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Persuader (novel)|Persuader]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-0440245988 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[The Enemy (Child novel)|The Enemy]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2004 |isbn= 0385336675 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2004 |isbn= 978-0385336680 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[The Hard Way (novel)|The Hard Way]]|publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0385336697 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Bad Luck and Trouble]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0385340557 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Nothing to Lose (novel)|Nothing to Lose]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2008 |isbn= 978-0385340564 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Gone Tomorrow]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-0385340571 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[61 Hours]] | publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-0385340588 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Worth Dying For (novel)|Worth Dying For]] | publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-0385344319 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= [[The Affair (Child novel)|The Affair]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0440339359 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= [[A Wanted Man]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2012 |isbn= 978-044033936-6}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= High Heat |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-0345546647}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Personal|url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780804178747 |url-access= registration | publisher= Delacorte Press|location=New York|year= 2014|isbn = 978-0804178761}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Night School |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2016|isbn= 978-0804178808}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= The Midnight Line |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2017|isbn= 978-0399593482}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Past Tense |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2018|isbn= 978-0399593512}}\n\n''' Further reading '''\n* {{cite web|last=Curtis|first=Bryan|title=The Curious Case of Lee Child: Before Tom Cruise could become Jack Reacher, Jim Grant had to become Lee Child |url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8766396/lee-child-jim-grant-jack-reacher |magazine=[[Grantland]] | accessdate=5 September 2015 |date=20 December 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.leechild.com Lee Child's official website]\n\n{{Jack Reacher}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reacher, Jack}}\n[[Category:Jack Reacher books| ]]\n[[Category:Characters in British novels of the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Characters in British novels of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Characters in crime novel series]]\n[[Category:Fictional secret agents and spies]]\n[[Category:Fictional military brats]]\n[[Category:Fictional military police of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Army personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional majors]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional Krav Maga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional aikidoka]]\n[[Category:Fictional hoboes]]\n[[Category:Fictional private investigators]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1997]]\n[[Category:Fictional Silver Star recipients]]\n[[Category:Thriller film characters]]\n[[Category:Action film characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the character|the book series|Jack Reacher (book series)|the film|Jack Reacher (film)|}}\n{{short description|Fictional character}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour     = #DEDEE2\n| name       = Jack Reacher\n| image      = JackReacherAlt.jpg\n| caption    = Jack Reacher, as played by Tom Cruise, appearing in the theatrical poster of the 2012 film ''Jack Reacher''<!--This image is a scaled-down, lower-resolution image of the theatrical poster for ''[[Jack Reacher (film)]]''.-->\n| first      = ''[[Killing Floor (novel)]]'' (1997)<br>''[[Jack Reacher (film)]]'' (2012)\n| nickname   = Reacher\n| alias      = <!-- see article body, after it is described -->\n| gender     = Male\n| occupation = {{flatlist |\n* [[U.S. Army]] [[Military Police Corps (United States)|Military Police Corps]] [[Major]]\n* [[Private investigator]]\n* [[Vagrancy (people)|Drifter]]\n* [[Vigilante]]\n}}\n| family     = {{plainlist |\n* Laurent Moutier (maternal grandfather, deceased)\n* William \"Stan\" Reacher (father, deceased)\n* Josephine Moutier-Reacher (mother, deceased)\n* Joe Reacher (brother, deceased)\n}}\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| spouse     =\n| children   =\n| relatives  =\n| creator    = [[Lee Child]]\n| portrayer  = [[Tom Cruise]]\n}}\n\n'''Jack Reacher''' is a fictional character and the [[protagonist]] of a [[Jack Reacher (book series)|series of crime thriller]] novels by British author [[Lee Child]].<ref name=\"CurtisMarch2013\">{{cite web|last=Curtis|first=Bryan|title=The Curious Case of Lee Child: Before Tom Cruise could become Jack Reacher, Jim Grant had to become Lee Child|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8766396/lee-child-jim-grant-jack-reacher |magazine=[[Grantland]] | accessdate=5 September 2015|date=20 December 2012}}</ref> After leaving the [[US Army]] as a [[Major (military)|major]] in [[Military Police Corps (United States)|its military police]] at age 36, Reacher roams the United States taking [[Temporary work|odd jobs]] and investigating suspicious and frequently dangerous situations. {{as of|2019|10|29}}, 24 novels have been published, the most recent being ''Blue Moon''. The character has also appeared in short stories, and two of the novels have been adapted into successful [[action thriller]] [[Jack Reacher (film)|films]], starring [[Tom Cruise]] as Reacher.\n\n==Development and author's commentary==\n===Development===\nAt the time Lee Child sat down to write his first novel ''[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]]'', he was unemployed, having been fired from his position as a presentation director for [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]].<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/><ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/><ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/> According to Child, authorship was a purely pragmatic decision: \"I wasn't one of these people that felt compelled to write. It had to keep a roof over our heads, so it was totally, totally 110% commercially motivated.\"<ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/>\n\nCritics have perceived other influences in Jack Reacher's creation. Bob Cornwell quotes Lee Child's reply in another interview as having created Reacher \"as an antidote, to all the depressed and miserable alcoholics that increasingly peopled the genre\".<ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/><ref name= \"Bob Cornwell\"/> Similarly, editor [[Otto Penzler]] published an essay by Child explaining that Jack Reacher was created deliberately in contrast to the prevailing trends in crime fiction. His name is short and commonplace, as opposed to quirky or unusual; Reacher's  personal ethics and wandering lifestyle are reminiscent of the chivalrous [[knight errant]] of medieval lore as opposed to an [[anti-hero]] tormented by addiction and haunted by past misbehavior.<ref>Otto Penzler (editor) ''The lineup: the world's greatest crime writers tell the inside story of their greatest detectives''. Little, Brown (2009)</ref>\n\nThe character's name first came to Child in a supermarket when an old lady, noting the span of Child's arms, asked for his help in reaching out to a can of pears. On seeing this, Child's wife commented that if his writing career did not work out he could \"always get a job as a reacher in a supermarket\".<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/> Reacher's ex-military background was a specific and tactical choice on his behalf. Child has explained, \"I thought that I would do a book that's not the same as everybody else's. Everybody else had their guy working: a private guy in [[Boston]] or a police lieutenant in [[Los Angeles|L.A.]], or wherever. I thought, 'Well, he won't be working, and he won't live anywhere, and let's just take it from there.'\" Child also felt that this origin would lend itself to the character's personality and nomadic lifestyle: \"This idea of the rootless alienation has got to come from somewhere, and I noticed that the most alienated people are always ex-military, because it's like going from one solar system to the other, it's so different. So that was an easy choice: Make him ex-military. Then make him ex-military police because, broadly speaking, these would be crime novels, and he had to have some investigative experience, and he had to understand procedures and forensics and so on. So that part was all set in stone\".<ref name=\"RobertBidinotto2007\">{{cite web|last=Bidinotto |first= Robert |title=Thriller: Lee Child and the creation of Jack Reacher |url= http://atlassociety.org/commentary/commentary-blog/4508-thriller-lee-child-and-the-creation-of-jack-reacher |magazine= The Atlas Society |date= 17 March 2011 |accessdate= 8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Similarities between Reacher and Lee Child====\nNumerous critics have pointed out the various similarities between Lee Child and Jack Reacher. Bryan Curtis, writing for ''[[Grantland]]'', and Natasha Harding and Caroline Iggulden, in a separate article for ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', have brought out the various similarities between Child and Reacher: Child is {{convert|6|ft|4|in|abbr=on}} tall while his protagonist stands  {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}}; both writer and creation constantly consume coffee; Like Reacher, Child \"lives in cheap pairs of jeans and T-shirts and finds the idea of buying expensive clothes to be irrational\"; and that \"Jack Reacher's famous physical qualities are based on Child's playground memories as a child\".<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> Child tends to agree with such observations: \"I was huge as a kid and Reacher's stature is me translated as a kid. I enjoyed being bigger and fighting shamelessly. I've done a fair amount of [[headbutt]]ing. It's an awesome manoeuvre.\"{{refn|group=note|The headbutt is considered Reacher's \"signature move\".<ref name= \"AndyMartin2015\"/>}} Andy Martin notes that \"just as Reacher is half-[[Arthur Rimbaud|Rimbaud]], half-[[John Rambo|Rambo]], Child is both art-for-art's-sake [[Parnassianism|Parnassian]] and ruthless businessman.\"<ref name=\"AndyMartin2015\">{{cite web |last=Martin |first= Andy |title= Lee Child on Jack Reacher: How the best-selling author writes his mysteries |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/lee-child-on-jack-reacher-how-the-best-selling-author-writes-his-mysteries-9959227.html |magazine= [[The Independent]] |date= January 2015 |accessdate= 5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nCurtis, as well as Harding and Iggulden, have also considered the role Child's dismissal from Granada had on Reacher's development. Curtis also notes that \"Child created Reacher from the smoldering embers of his own rage. It might seem like a simplistic theory, but it's true. Like the author, Reacher was workplace surplus: He was a [[military police]]man in an era of Army [[Layoff|downsizing]]. The act of leaving his job turned Reacher into a protective figure, an avenging angel.\" He finds that Reacher's actions are a manifestation of Child's anger at his sacking and that his violent ways of dealing with villains is 'cathartic' to the author.<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\n===Author's commentary and interpretation===\n[[File:Lee Child, Bouchercon 2010.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lee Child|Jim Grant]], better known by his pen name Lee Child, at [[Bouchercon XLI]], 2010]]\n \nLee Child views Jack Reacher as a \"happy-go-lucky guy. He has quirks and problems, but the thing is, he doesn't know he's got them. Hence, no tedious self-pity. He's smart and strong, an [[introvert]], but any anguish he suffers is caused by others.\"<ref name= \"ClaireWhite2001\"/> When asked about the casting of [[Tom Cruise]] in the role of Jack Reacher (Tom Cruise's casting as Jack Reacher was met with severe criticism from fans of the book series, primarily because the disparity in their heights with Reacher portrayed as a blond, {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}} tall, 250-pound man in the novels, while Cruise is a {{convert|5|ft|7|in|abbr=on}} tall brunette<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\">{{cite web |last=Kellogg |first= Carolyn |title= Reader reactions to 'Jack Reacher': The fans are furious |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/21/entertainment/la-et-jc-tom-cruise-jack-reacher-fans-react-20121220 |magazine= [[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 21 December 2012}}</ref><ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/>), Child replied that \"Reacher's size in the books is a metaphor for an unstoppable force\".<ref name= DenOfGeek/> Physically and appearance wise, Child has  compared him to Rugby Player [[Lawrence Dallaglio]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Studio 10|title=Author Lee Child Talks 'Jack Reacher' TV Series {{!}} Studio 10|date=2018-11-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YK8rOM1skK4|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nHe has also referred to Reacher on multiple occasions as a '[[knight-errant]]'<ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/><ref name= \"AlexBerenson2014\"/> and in an interview for the ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine describes the character as: \" (He's) two things in one. On the surface, he is an ex-military cop who is suddenly dumped out into the civilian world. He doesn't fit in, and he spends his time wandering America, seeing the things that he's never had time to see before. He's trying to stay out of trouble, but masterfully once a year getting into trouble. He's also the descendant of a very ancient tradition: the noble loner, the knight errant, the mysterious stranger, who has shown up in stories forever\u2026 He is a truly universal character... I'm writing the modern iteration of a character who has existed for thousands of years.\"<ref name=\"AndreaSachs2012\">{{cite web |last=Sachs |first= Andrea |title= Lee Child on His New Thriller, Tom Cruise as Jack Reacher and Wandering Heroes |url= http://entertainment.time.com/2012/09/19/lee-child-on-his-new-thriller-tom-cruise-as-jack-reacher-and-wandering-heroes/ |magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=September 2012 |accessdate= 5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn another interview for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' magazine, Child further analyses the mythology of his character:\n\n<blockquote>The stories that I love are basically about the knight-errant, the mysterious stranger. And the reason why people think that's an essentially American paradigm is the Westerns. The Westerns were absolutely rock solid with that stuff. You know, the mysterious rider comes in off the range, sorts out the problem, and rides off into the sunset. It is just such a total paradigm, but not invented in America. That was imported from the medieval tales of Europe. The knight-errant: literally a knight, somehow banished and forced to wander the land doing good deeds. It's part of storytelling in every culture. Japan has it with the ronin myth; every culture has this Robin Hood idea. So really, that character was forced out of Europe as Europe became more densely populated and more civilized. That character no longer had stories in Europe; it had to migrate to where the frontier was still open and dangerous, which was America, essentially. So the character, I think, is actually universal and historic, most recently, normally represented in America. I think the Westerns saw it firmly adopted by America, so yeah, right now, we think of this as a completely American character, but really, it's more historic than that. But I'm very happy to have that reference made.<ref name=\"AlexBerenson2014\">{{cite web |last=Berenson |first= Alex |title= What Lee Child Has Learned from Writing the Jack Reacher Books |url= http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/books/a30736/jack-reacher-lee-child-interview/ |magazine= [[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate= 5 March 2016 |date=December 2014}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nChild also views Reacher as \"[[Postfeminism|post-feminist]]\" stating that he does not parlay in \"gender distinction...Reacher likes strong, realistic women, and he treats women with respect...he doesn't cut them any slack, but also he has no negative preconceptions. If you're a woman, he will be your friend; but if necessary, he will kill you.\"<ref name= \"RobertBidinotto2007\"/>\n\n==Fictional biography==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2015}}\nJack Reacher is described as being a former major in the United States Military Police Corps.\n\n===Childhood and formative years===\nJack Reacher was born on a [[military base]] in Berlin, on 29 October 1960. He has no middle name, and most people simply call him 'Reacher', even his family as a child. Regular references are made to the fact that Reacher's given name is Jack, which is not a nickname for John, and that he has no middle name.  His military record officially refers to him as Jack (none) Reacher.<ref name= DenOfGeek/> From the time he was a boy, his family, even his mother, simply called him \"Reacher\", an appellation that has stayed with him, but was never given to his brother.<ref name= \"LeeChildOfficial\"/>\n\nReacher's mother Josephine Moutier Reacher (n\u00e9e Moutier) was a French national, and Reacher was fluent in French from early childhood,<ref name=\"Enemy\">Child (2004). ''The Enemy''.</ref> but as he admits in ''The Affair'' (2011) he speaks the language ''Un peu, mais lentement'' (\"A little, but slowly\"). Reacher's maternal grandfather was at the Battle of Verdun in the First World War and in the French Resistance in the Second, and lived to a ripe old age, which in Reacher's view means that his grandfather had \"beaten the odds\".\n\n===Military years and profile===\n{{More citations needed section|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:USAMPC-COA.png|thumb|150px|left|Regimental Coat of Arms of the United States Military Police Corps]]\n\nAfter being shunted around the world, growing up on U.S. military bases where his father Stan was stationed, he gained an education in basic survival as well as an opportunity to enter the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point. After four years at West Point (1979 to 1983) Reacher achieved the ranks of [[Second lieutenant#United States|2nd lieutenant]], [[First lieutenant#United States|1st lieutenant]], [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], and [[Major (United States)#Army|major]],<ref>{{Cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|pages = 11}}</ref> including an intervening demotion from major to captain<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Enemy|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = TransworldDigital|year = 2004|isbn = 0-553-81585-7|chapter= Chapter 25}}</ref> in 1990<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\">{{cite web|last= Child|first= Lee|title= Jack Reacher| website= leechild.com| url= http://www.leechild.com/jack-reacher.php |accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref> during his tenure in the military police. His commanding officer, Leon Garber, promoted Reacher twice in 18 months, making  him the youngest peacetime major anyone could remember.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee|title= Tripwire|publisher= Jove Books|year= 2000| isbn= 978-0515128635}}</ref> During his tenure, his achievements were recognised in the form of citations and awards including the [[Silver Star]], the [[Defense Superior Service Medal]], [[Legion of Merit]], [[Soldier's Medal]], [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= Night School|publisher= Delacorte Press| year= 2016| isbn= 978-0804178808 |page= 322}}</ref> [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]], and a second [[Silver Star]] and [[Purple Heart]] for wounds sustained in the bombing of the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings|US Marine Corps barracks]] in [[Beirut]] in 1983.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/><ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= 61 Hours | url= https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell| url-access= registration| year= 2010 |page= [https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell/page/22 22]|quote= Reacher had been an army liaison officer serving with the Marine Corps at the time of the barracks bombing. He had been badly wounded in the attack....The wound had healed fast and completely. It had left what the army called a disfiguring scar, which implied a real mess.}}</ref>\n\nWhile his Silver Star and Purple Heart are cited on his profile, all of the other [[Citations|medal citations]] involve official secrets and are therefore [[Sanitization (classified information)|redacted]]. The short story \"Deep Down\" hints that he possibly was awarded the Legion of Merit as a result of exposing a female liaison officer who was leaking confidential information to the Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= Deep Down|publisher= Delacorte Press|year=2012|isbn= 978-0-345-53710-2 |page= 86}}</ref>\n\nReacher served in the army's military police branch, resigning his commission and [[Mustering-out Payment Act|mustering out]] at the rank of major. His unit, the fictional 110th Special Investigations Unit,<ref name=DenOfGeek/> was formed to handle exceptionally tough cases. He left the armed forces in 1997, partly due to a reduction in the forces and partly because he verbally offended a lieutenant colonel during an investigation in Mississippi, who then singled him out for discharge.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Make Me|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2015|isbn = 9780804178785|location = |pages =| chapter= Chapter 23}}</ref>\n\nAmong his formal qualifications, Reacher is described as the only non-Marine to win the [[Wimbledon Cup]],<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first =Lee |title= [[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]}}</ref> a US Marine Corps 1000 Yard Invitational Rifle Competition; achieving a record score in 1988.<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first=Lee|title= [[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]]|publisher= Transworld Digital|year=2005|isbn= 0-385-33668-3| chapter= Chapter 12}}</ref> Anecdotally his fitness reports rated him well above average in the classroom, excellent in the field, fluently bilingual in English and French, passable in Spanish, outstanding on all man-portable weaponry, and beyond outstanding at hand-to-hand combat.<ref name=\"61H\">{{cite book | last= Child | first= Lee | title= 61 Hours | publisher= Delacorte Press | location= New York | year= 2010 | isbn= 9780440243694 | url= https://archive.org/details/61hours00dell }}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nAfter leaving the Army, Reacher became a [[vagabond (person)|drifter]], his only baggage a folding toothbrush,<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> although after the [[September 11 attacks]], with restrictions on [[wire transfer]]s in the light of [[Wire transfer fraud|fraud]] he is obliged to carry an [[ATM card]]<ref name=\"KevinNance2012\"/> and [[Photo identification|photo ID]] in the form of a (generally expired) American [[passport]].<ref name=\"SteveDrummond2011\">{{cite web|last= Drummond|first= Steve|title=Lee Child's 'The Affair': Sixteen Books In, Has Jack Reacher Still Got It?|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/monkeysee/2011/10/20/141548652/lee-childs-the-affair-sixteen-books-in-has-jack-reacher-still-got-it | website= NPR.org | publisher= [[National Public Radio]] | date= 20 October 2011 | accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nEmily Sargent, while conducting an interview with Lee Child, describes Reacher's post-military life as follows:\n\n<blockquote>You will never find Reacher going to the laundry or doing the ironing. When his clothes get dirty he simply goes to the local hardware store and buys a functional pair of chinos and a workman's shirt and stuffs the old ones in the bin. No mortgage, no wife, no ties, he is a perfectly free agent, unlimited and unbound, incapable of ever settling down.<ref name=\"EmilySargent2011\">{{cite web|last= Sargent|first= Emily|title=Killer instinct: Is Tom Cruise the right man to play Lee Child's savage anti-hero on screen?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/killer-instinct-is-tom-cruise-the-right-man-to-play-lee-childs-savage-anti-hero-on-screen-6252359.html |magazine=[[The Independent]] | accessdate=1 March 2016|date=30 October 2011}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLee Child describes Reacher's obsession to wander about:\n\n<blockquote>He's an ex-military policeman, and he was demobilized in his middle thirties after having served all of his adult life in the [U.S.] Army and having grown up on Marine bases, because his father was a Marine. The idea was to have a character that was plausibly rootless. Most people who are wanderers do it for other reasons\u2014they are mentally ill, or something like that. Reacher is completely competent, but he's just habituated to this fragmented life in the military, so he can't settle into civilian society. The idea of staying anywhere for more than a few days is [[anathema]] to him.<ref name= \"RobertBidinotto2007\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Demeanor and personality==\nReacher himself expounds on a hypothesis about this vagrant life-style in ''[[Never Go Back (Lee Child novel)|Never Go Back]]''. He states that he has a genetic disposition towards roaming about, citing the [[British Empire]], the [[Vikings]], and the [[Polynesians]] as groups with a similar wanderlust. While he accepts that [[Human migration|there was an economical necessity]] behind their voyages, he maintains that \"some of them could not stop\". He feels that long ago when [[Prehistory|humans lived in small bands]], there was a risk of [[inbreeding]] as a result of which a [[gene]] developed over the course of [[evolution]] such that \"every generation and every small band had at least one person who had to wander\". This would lead to \"mixing up of [[gene pool]]s\" and would be \"healthier all around\". Reacher concludes:\n\n{{quote|I think ninety-nine of us grow up to love the campfire, and one grows up to hate it. Ninety-nine of us grow up to fear the howling wolf, and one grows up to envy it. And I'm that guy.\n\nCompelled to spread his [[DNA]] worldwide. Purely for the good of the species.<ref>{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location =London |chapter= Chapter 38}}</ref>}}\n\nReacher's large physique means his character is sometimes mistaken by other people. For example, in ''[[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]'', Reacher is wrongly suspected by the FBI of being involved in a kidnapping, which assesses him (solely on the basis of a few photos) as such: \"The big guy is different. Different clothes, different stance, different physically. He could be foreign, at least partly, or maybe second generation. Fair hair and blue eyes, but there's something in his face. Maybe he's European, perhaps a European mercenary or terrorist.\"<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Die Trying| url= https://archive.org/details/dietrying00chil| url-access= registration|year=|chapter= Chapter 22}}</ref> Reacher is aware of this perception. In ''[[Make Me (novel)|Make Me]]'' Reacher gets off a train in a remote town called Mother's Rest, simply because he likes the name of the town. When he sees a woman approaching him with a look of expectation, he immediately understands that the person she was waiting for must be very tall like him, as it is his standout feature when people first meet him.\n\nIn ''[[Echo Burning]]'', Reacher narrates how he first turned \"his fear into aggression\". He was about four when he watched a television show on space adventures. One episode depicted a [[Extraterrestrial life|space monster]] which then terrified the young Reacher. He was [[Insomnia|unable to sleep]] for days, thinking the monster was under his bed and would get him if he tried to sleep. According to Reacher, he then became angry: \"Not at myself for being afraid, because as far as I was concerned the thing was totally real and I should be afraid. I got mad at the thing for making me afraid. For threatening me\". Reacher then one night \"kind of exploded with fury\". In his words, Reacher \"raced down the monster\" and successfully changed his fear into fury. He also stated he has never been scared since.<ref>{{cite book| title = Echo Burning|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2001|isbn =0-515-13331-0 |location =London | chapter =Chapter 6| quote= One night I just kind of exploded with fury. I yelled O-K-, come out and try it! Just damn well try it! I'll beat the shit right out of you! I raced it down. I turned the fear into aggression.}}</ref>\n\nThis fact is later referenced in ''Never Go Back'', when an Army psychological study of fear in children is cited that shows Reacher to have abnormally fast reflexes and aggression levels at the age of six; Reacher believes that this abnormal level of aggression at that age is not due to genetics, as the Army report suggested, but because he got tired of being frightened, and trained himself \"to turn fear into aggression, automatically\".<ref>{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location = London | chapter= Chapters 30, 38}}</ref>\n\nReacher seldom shows remorse for the numerous felonies he perpetrates and has a primal sense of justice. In ''[[Personal (novel)|Personal]]'', after killing a thug, he defends his actions to his distraught accomplice, Casey Nice, by stating the man could have spent his life performing good deeds such as \"helping old ladies across the street\", \"raising funds for Africa\" or \"volunteering in the library\". Instead the man extorted money and hurt people and when he \"finally he opened the wrong door, what came out at him was his problem, not mine\".<ref name=\"alpha\">{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2014|isbn =9781473508774 |location = London |chapter= Chapter 28}}</ref>\n\nThis primitivity on part of Reacher is commented upon in ''Never Go Back'', in which Reacher is described by Susan Turner as being like \"something feral....It's like you've been sanded down to nothing but yes and no, and you and them, and black and white, and live or die. You're like a predator. Cold and hard.\" (p.&nbsp;176\u2013177) However, when she witnesses Reacher's outrage at the hurt inflicted upon an innocent waitress, she reconsiders and states that he is actually not feral as she had earlier presumed. Furthermore, she notes that Reacher had until then attempted to solve only her problems, neglecting the problems of his own:\n\n<blockquote> And you've done nothing but chip away at my problem. You're ignoring your own, with the Big Dog. Which is just as serious. Therefore, you still care for others. Which means you can't really be feral. I imagine caring for others is the first thing to go. And you still know right from wrong. Which all means you're OK.<ref name=\"bravo\">{{cite book| title = Never Go Back|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2013|isbn =9781409030805 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 35}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis underlying kindness perceived by Turner is visible in many of Reacher's actions: he stands up for the right of women in both ''[[Echo Burning]]'', whose central plot involves him aiding a woman's escape from her abusive husband, and in ''[[Worth Dying For (novel)|Worth Dying For]]'', in which he breaks the nose of an abusive husband for beating up his wife.<ref>{{cite book| title = Worth Dying For|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2010|isbn =9781407083131 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 6| quote= Reacher hit him, a straight right to the nose, a big vicious blow, his knuckles driving through cartilage and bone and crushing it all flat.}}</ref> He is also shown to be sympathetic to those in need, as seen in ''[[The Hard Way (novel)|The Hard Way]]'' where he bequeaths Edward Lane's fees paid to him for the medical treatment and living expenses of a man whom Lane had betrayed many years back.<ref>{{cite book|title = The Hard Way|last = Child|first = Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2006|isbn = 0-385-33669-1|location = London|chapter = Chapter 47|quote = I'm going to send Hobart down to Birmingham or Nashville and get him fixed up right. I'm going to buy him a lifetime's supply of spare parts and I'm going to rent him a place to live and I'm going to give him some walking-around money because my guess is he's not very employable right now. At least not in his old trade. And then if there's anything left, then sure, I'll buy myself a new shirt.|url = https://archive.org/details/hardwa00chil}}</ref>\n\nThis point is further elucidated in ''Personal'', when Reacher reminisces while standing at his mother's grave:\n\n<blockquote>She had said, 'You've got the strength of two normal boys. What are you going to do with it?' I hadn't replied. Our silence was part of the ritual. She answered for me. She said, 'You're going to do the right thing.' And I had tried, mostly, which had sometimes caused me trouble, and sometimes won me medals of my own.<ref name=\"foxtrot\">{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2014|isbn =9781473508774 |location = London | chapter= Chapter 18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Skills==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n\nReacher is described as proficient in hand-to-hand combat. He is quite fast for his height, and often fights opponents his size or larger. His skill is attributed to the fact that he grew up all over the world, due to being in a Marine Corps family. While he is not a master in any one form of combat, he tends to incorporate moves from various styles. His favorite moves are headbutts, elbow strikes, and kicks to the groin. As Child once put it, \"Reacher's fighting style is like a running chainsaw\". Reacher generally goes with the flow of the fight, caring about winning more than how he wins. However, he plans out how to strike first or react to the first strike, and how he'll make sure the other person never fights him again. As he puts it, \"The other guy cares how he wins, I care about pissing on the other guy's grave.\"\n\nReacher has an internal clock. He sets a time to wake up at and his body automatically awakens. He often sets a timer in fights to try and get a tactical edge. Reacher also has a fascination with numbers. In ''[[Bad Luck and Trouble]]'', Reacher uses this to deduce that the amount of money deposited without his knowledge into his bank account was an attempt by Neagley, his colleague from the Military Police Corps, to contact him.\n\nReacher has extremely acute deduction skills. He generally gains his information simply from talking to people or making minute observations. He will pick up on a simple pause and relate it back to what he is trying figure out. He is known as one of the best investigators the Military Police Corps had to offer, and he led a special unit tasked with difficult cases.\n\nReacher is also described as skilled [[marksman]], principally in ''[[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]]'', being the only non-[[United States Marine Corps|Marine]] to win the US Marine Corps [[Wimbledon Cup|1000 Yard Invitational rifle competition]].\n\n==Habits and beliefs==\n{{More citations needed section|date=September 2015}}\nReacher has a love for music, especially [[blues]].<ref name=\"Child 1997 p. 522\">Child (1997), ''Killing Floor'', p. 522.</ref> It was this affinity that inspires Reacher to get off the bus at the start of ''[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]]'', and in the same novel reveals that he has a music collection in his head, replaying tracks as he travels without needing the technology others seem to be obsessed with and burdened by. Reacher explains this to detectives investigating an early morning suicide on a near-deserted [[New York City Subway|New York subway]] near a visit to a [[blues]] club on [[Bleecker Street]].<ref>{{cite book| title = [[Gone Tomorrow]] |last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =| chapter= Chapter 7| page= | isbn= }}</ref>\n\nReacher espouses no personal religious beliefs but is scathing in his dismissal of town boss Thurman's [[fundamentalist Christianity|fundamentalist Christian]] position in the novel ''Nothing to Lose'': When asked if he is \"born again\" Reacher says, \"Once was enough for me\" and later rhetorically asks Thurman, \"I'm here to visit the sick and you want to have me beaten up? What kind of Christian are you?\"<ref>{{cite book| title = Nothing To Lose |last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =| chapter= Chapters 38, 44| page= | isbn= }}</ref> He also mentions at the opening of ''[[Bad Luck and Trouble]]'' that he avoids [[Alaska Airlines]] because \"they put a scripture card on the meal trays\".<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 4 |isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = 15}}</ref>\n\nReacher is also critical of the corruption of traditional spelling, such as the use of contractions like \"U\" for \"you\", \"lo\" for \"low\", disliking the absence of the apostrophe in ''DONT WALK'' pedestrian signage before they were replaced, then noting he also disapproved of replacing words with pictures.<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 20 |isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = }}</ref>\n\nWhile Reacher knows how to drive, in ''[[A Wanted Man]]'' he professes to be a bad driver, and in ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' he says he cannot rent a car because he does not have a driver's license.<ref>{{cite book|title = Bad Luck and Trouble|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = Random House |year = 2007|chapter= Chapter 22|isbn = 9780440336853 |location = |page = }}</ref> In ''Without Fail'' Agent Frolich trawls various databases for Reacher, only to discover he is effectively untraceable, because without a driver's license he has no photograph and no address.<ref>{{cite book|title = Without Fail|url = https://archive.org/details/withoutfail00chil|url-access = registration|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher =  |year = |chapter= Chapter 1 |isbn = |location = |page = }}</ref>\n\nAmong his few indulgences are casual sex and coffee, which he drinks constantly.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref>{{cite book|title =The Enemy|url =https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780440245995|url-access =registration|last = Child |first = Lee |publisher = |year = |chapter=  |isbn =  |location = |page = |quote= [Joe] was probably the only other human on the planet who liked coffee as much as I did. He started drinking it when he was six. I copied him immediately. I was four. Neither of us has stopped since. The Reacher brothers' need for caffeine makes [[heroin addiction]] look like an amusing little take-it-or-leave-it sideline.}}</ref><ref name=\"echo\">{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = The Enemy |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2004 |isbn = 0-553-81585-7 | chapter= Chapter 5}}</ref>\n\n==Physical appearance==\nBryan Curtis, in an interview with Lee Child, describes Reacher thus:\n\n<blockquote>His face looked like it had been chipped out of rock by a sculptor who had ability but not much time.<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/></blockquote>\n\nFrom ''A Wanted Man'': \"He was one of the largest men she had ever seen outside the NFL. He was extremely tall, and extremely broad, and long-armed, and long-legged. The lawn chair was regular size, but it looked tiny under him. It was bent and crushed out of shape. His knuckles were nearly touching the ground. His neck was thick and his hands were the size of dinner plates...A wild man. But not really. Underneath everything else seemed strangely civilized....His gaze was both wise and appealing, both friendly and bleak, both frank and utterly cynical.\"<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= A Wanted Man | url= https://archive.org/details/wantedmanreacher00chil| url-access= registration| year= 2012| page= [https://archive.org/details/wantedmanreacher00chil/page/169 169]}}</ref>\n\nReacher is described as being {{convert|6|ft|5|in}} tall, weighing {{convert|210|-|250|lb|kg}} and having a {{convert|50|in|cm|adj=on}} chest.<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\"/><ref name=\"DenOfGeek\">{{cite web|last= Stansfield |first= James |title= Who is Jack Reacher? |url=  https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/23502/who-is-jack-reacher |magazine= Den of Geek |date= 22 November 2012|accessdate= 7 March 2016}}</ref> In ''[[Never Go Back (Lee Child novel)|Never Go Back]]'', he is described as having \"a six-pack like a cobbled city street, a chest like a suit of NFL armor, biceps like basketballs, and subcutaneous fat like a Kleenex tissue.\"<ref name=\"bravo\"/> In his youth, his physical appearance likened to that of a 'bulked-up greyhound'.<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7 |page= 41}}</ref> He also reveals that his size is purely genetic; he states in ''[[Persuader]]''<ref>{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Persuader | year= 2003 |chapter= Chapter 3 |quote= I never work out.}}</ref> and ''Never Go Back'' that he is not much of an exercise enthusiast.<ref name= \"bravo\"/>\n\nHe has various scars, most notably a collection of roughly stitched scars on his abdomen caused by a bombing in Lebanon,<ref>{{cite book |title= Killing Floor| first= Lee| last= Child| year= 1999 |quote= He had served thirteen years in the Army, and the only time he was wounded it wasn't with a bullet. It was with a fragment of a Marine sergeant's jawbone.}}</ref> with ugly raised welts that are later instrumental in saving his life, a {{convert|3|to|4|in|cm|0|adj=mid|-wide}} white scar that intersects his [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] scar that he received during a knife fight in ''[[Gone Tomorrow]]''. Reacher attributes his survival to the rough [[Mobile Army Surgical Hospital|MASH]] stitch work.<ref>{{cite book |title= Killing Floor| first= Lee| last= Child| year= 1999 | chapter= Chapter 83}}</ref>\n\nHis various other scars include one from a chest shot with a [[.38 Special]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Never Go Back|url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780385344340|url-access= registration| first= Lee| last= Child| chapter= Chapter 35| quote= She traced around his ear, and his neck, and his chest. She put the tip of her pinkie in his bullet hole. It fit just right. 'A .38,' he said.}}</ref> and a [[powder burn]] from a near-miss at [[point blank range]], and one on his arm where his brother struck him with a chisel.<ref name=\"charlie\">{{cite book| title = The Enemy|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Transworld Publishers|year = 2004|isbn = 0-553-81585-7 |location =London| chapter= Chapter 6}}</ref>\n\nHe suffers his first ever broken nose in ''Worth Dying For'', at over 50 years of age.  He resets the bone with a thump from his palm and later puts on a plaster bandage made of [[duct tape]].\n\n==Family==\nReacher's maternal grandfather, Laurent Moutier, was a furniture restorer in [[Paris]], who, at age 30, volunteered for the [[French Army]] in 1914 at the outbreak of [[World War I]], fighting at [[Battle of Verdun|Verdun]] and [[The Somme]].<ref group=\"note\">The final days in the life of Reacher's grandfather, with [[flashback (continuity)|flashbacks]] to various earlier times in his life, appear in the story ''[[Second Son (Lee Child novel)|Second Son]]'', taking place when Reacher was 13 years old.</ref> Between 1919 and 1929 he was commissioned to produce wooden legs for wounded veterans. Josephine Moutier was his only child. He died in 1974 at age 90. Jack, as a boy, met him three times and is described as having liked him. In ''Second Son'' Reacher is impressed with his grandfather's stoic acceptance of approaching death and says that \"A man who survived [[Battle of Verdun|Verdun]] and [[The Somme]] as well as the WWII anti-Nazi Resistance has already beaten the odds\".\n\nReacher's mother, Josephine Moutier Reacher, born in France, was 30 years old when Reacher was born.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> She met Reacher's father in [[Korea]] and married him in the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"charlie\"/> When she was only 13, she joined the [[French Resistance]] and under the alias \"Beatrice\" worked with ''Le Chemin de Fer Humain'' (the Human Railroad), saving 80 men. She [[garrote]]d a schoolmate, a boy who threatened to give her up to the [[Nazis]], and would later receive the ''[[M\u00e9daille de la R\u00e9sistance]]'' (the Resistance Medal) for further heroism.<ref name=TheEnemy>{{cite book|last1=Child|first1=Lee|title=The Enemy|date=April 2005|publisher=Dell Publishing Company|isbn=9780440241010| chapter= Chapter 19}}</ref> She was widowed in 1988,{{refn|group=note|It is mentioned in the novel ''Personal'' that Josephine Reacher died in 1990<ref name=\"foxtrot\"/> while according to Lee Child's official website, her husband died two years before her.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/> Thus simple arithmetic dictates her husband is bound to have died in 1988.}} and died in 1990 at the age of 60 of lung cancer.<ref name=\"foxtrot\"/> Reacher described his mother as \"[[French people|gallic]], feminine, obstinate,\" and \"[the] most stubborn woman possible.\" He also branded her a [[Fatalism|fatalist]] as she had concealed her cancer from her children and had refused treatment for a one-year period before her death.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> However Reacher compares her favourably to his father: \"My father hadn't killed the enemy at the age of thirteen. But my mother had. She had lived through desperate times and she had stepped up and done what was necessary.\"<ref name=TheEnemy/> Reacher also has great respect for his mother: at her funeral he buried his ''Silver Star'' medal with her,<ref name= \"foxtrot\"/> and on learning of her role in [[World War II]], states that he became the man he was because of her.<ref name=TheEnemy/> In ''[[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]]'', when the FBI mistakenly assumes Reacher to be in league with the book's villains, the Bureau experts observing Reacher's demeanor on footage from a security camera consider him to be \"a foreigner, probably a European mercenary\".\n\nReacher's father, Stan Reacher, was a [[United States Marine Corps]] captain, who served in [[Korean War|Korea]] and [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. His military service kept his family continually moving all around the world to various military bases. At the time of the short story ''Second Son'', when Jack was 13, he was stationed in [[Okinawa]] and involved in preparing [[contingency plan]]s for an invasion of Mainland [[China]]. In the same short story, Stan Reacher is depicted as \"a child of the [[Great Depression|depression]],\" coming from a miserly [[New England]] family, and as a result was a proponent of the theories of \"Waste not, want not,\" \"Make do and mend,\" and \"Don't make an exhibition of oneself.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Second Son |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2011 |isbn = 9781446497111 | chapter = 13}}</ref>  Jack described his father as \"a plain [[New Hampshire]] [[Yankee]] with an implacable horror of anything fancy...he had no use for wealth and excess. Very compartmentalized guy. Gentle, shy, sweet, loving man, but a stone-cold killer. Next to him I look like [[Liberace]]\".<ref name=\"delta\">{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Without Fail |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2002 |isbn = 978-0-515-14431-4| chapter= Chapter 11}}</ref> Jack Reacher furthermore highlighted this dichotomy in his father's behaviour by stating that he would be engaging in violent actions such as \"how to angle a claymore mine so the little ball bearings explode outward at exactly the right angle to rip the enemy's spines out of their backs with maximum efficiency\" one day, and the next day would be doing something calmer, like \"watching birds,\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = The Enemy |publisher = Transworld Publishers |year = 2004 |isbn = 0-553-81585-7 |chapter= Chapter 14}}</ref> After military service, \"there was no place left for people like him.\"<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref name=\"delta\"/> He died in 1988.<ref name=\"LeeChildOfficial\"/> James Stanfield, in an article concludes that \"Reacher clearly looked up to and idolised his father, and though Reacher's reasons for leaving the service were very different to his dad's, they've ended up at the same point.\"<ref name=DenOfGeek/>\n\nReacher had only one sibling, brother Joe Reacher, who was two years older than Jack.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref name=\"echo\"/> Physically, Joe was one inch taller {{height|ft=6|in=6}} and a \"little slighter\" than his younger sibling, weighing {{convert|220|lb}}.<ref name=\"echo\"/><ref name= \"charlie\"/> Joe was born on a military base in the [[Philippines]], and Jack is described as helping Joe beat up the kids who gave him trouble in school, and vice versa.<ref name=DenOfGeek/><ref>{{cite book |last= Child |first= Lee |title = Killing Floor |publisher = Penguin Group (USA) Inc. |location= 375 Hudson Street, New York, New York 10014, USA |year = 1997 |isbn = 1-4295-1117-6 |chapter= Chapter 10}}</ref> However Joe also had scuffles with his own brother, given the scar that Jack had put on his forehead during their childhood.<ref name=\"charlie\"/> Joe was also a [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] graduate, and spent five years in [[military intelligence]], where he never won any of the \"good medals\", only the \"junk awards.<ref name=echo/> \"Jack described his brother as being pedantic, and called him a perfectionist, \"a man horrified with anything less than the best.\"<ref name=\"echo\"/> Joe is described as joining the [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury Department]], and died at age 38 in the line of duty, having arranged a meeting with a potential investigation subject.<ref name=\"Child 1997 p. 522\"/> Because he was killed in the line of duty, his name can be found on the Treasury Department's Roll of Honor.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Critical reception and analysis==\nCritics have noted the strong theme of \"justice\" pervading the character as well as the book series. Claire E. White, characterises the titular protagonist as: \"wanderer, a hero who is a bit alienated from the establishment, but whose sense of justice is strong. He reminds (''me'') a bit of a character from the Old West: the strong, mysterious loner who never stays in town for long.\"<ref name=\"ClaireWhite2001\">{{cite web| last= White |first= Claire |title= A Conversation With Lee Child|url=  http://www.writerswrite.com/journal/aug01/a-conversation-with-lee-child-8012 |magazine= The Internet Writing Journal |accessdate= 1 March 2016|date=2001 }}</ref> Mike Ripley detected the influence of [[Jack Schaefer|Jack Schaefer's]] western novel ''[[Shane (novel)|Shane]]'' in the Reacher novel ''Echo Burning'' while Bob Cornwell calls the debut Jack Reacher novel '' Killing Floor'' \"a classic western\".<ref name=\"Bob Cornwell\">{{cite web |last= Cornwell |first= Bob |title= Lee Child Interview |url= http://www.twbooks.co.uk/crimescene/leechildinterview.htm |magazine= TwBooks |accessdate= 1 March 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150711233606/http://www.twbooks.co.uk/crimescene/leechildinterview.htm |archive-date= 11 July 2015 |url-status= dead }}</ref> [[Grantland]] columnist Bryan Curtis calls the character \"a protective figure, an avenging angel\" and quotes the author [[Michael Connelly]] describing the Reacher book series as: \"These are postmodern Westerns, they're ''Shane''. A stranger comes to town and sets things right. Then he leaves town.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/> The critic Emily Sargent says of the fictional Reacher: \"just the kind of no-nonsense, ramrod hero an intelligent five-year old would dream up: a strapping, broad-shouldered, idealized father-figure, something akin to God in his wisdom and power, alternately benevolent and overwhelmingly cruel, fair but firm. Good at saving damsels in distress and sorting out bad guys.\"<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/>\n\nRick Gekoski, writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', takes a similar if darker interpretation of the character: \"Reacher is, of course, in a long line of American outcast heroes who abjure emotional ties, head out into the wilderness and take upon their own broad shoulders the primitive moral conscience of the tribe. Too immature to make a sexual commitment, obsessed with death and terror, this archetypal hero of American fiction was first described in [[Leslie Fiedler|Leslie Fiedler's]] classic ''Love and Death in the American Novel'' (1960).\"<ref name=\"RickGekoski2013\">{{cite web| last= Gekoski |first= Rick |title= Why I love Lee Child's Jack Reacher novels |url=  https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2013/aug/29/lee-child-jack-reacher |magazine= [[The Guardian]] |accessdate= 1 March 2016 |date= 29 August 2013 }}</ref> In the same article he also questions whether Fiedler would find that Reacher's [[hypermasculinity]] is a sign of the character's \"repressed [[homosexuality]]\".<ref name= \"RickGekoski2013\"/>\n\nMalcolm Gladwell, in an article for ''[[The New Yorker]]'', perceives a difference in the Reacher character and the traditional Western characters in terms of the symbolism they represent to the general public. In his opinion \"The traditional Western was a fantasy about lawfulness: it was based on a longing for order among those who had been living without it for too long. The heroes conduct themselves according to strict rules of chivalry. They act\u2014 insofar as it is possible \u2014with restraint. In the world we live in today, by contrast, we have too much order: we are, as we have been reminded so frequently lately, over-policed. Our contemporary fantasy is about lawlessness: about what would happen if the institutions of civility melted away and all we were left with was a hard-muscled, rangy guy who could do all the necessary calculations in his head to insure that the bad guy got what he had coming. That's why there are rarely any police in Reacher novels\u2014or judges or courts or lawyers or any discussion or consideration of the law. Nor is there any restraint on the part of the hero. He's not pointing toward a more civilized tomorrow. He's leading us back into the wilderness, with the reassurance that our psychopaths are bigger and stronger than the bad guys' psychopaths.\"<ref name=\"Malcolm Gladwell2015\">{{cite web| last= Gladwell |first= Malcolm |title= The Lawless Pleasures of Lee Child's Jack Reacher Novels |url=  http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-lawless-pleasures-of-lee-childs-jack-reacher-novels |magazine= [[The New Yorker]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 9 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nSargent also notes the dichotomy in Reacher's character, stating that he is intellectual and generous despite his exterior appearance of being \"unkempt, unshaven and out of uniform, a loner, avenger, perpetual outsider at odds with the army\". In Sargent's express opinion:\n\n{{quote|The thing about Reacher is that he is not just a thug, even if a well-meaning thug in the manner of, say, [[John Rambo|Rambo]] or [[Bruce Willis]]. He is also a thinker, an intellectual, capable of quoting [[Nietzsche]] or coming up with the etymology of \"vagrant\". And he speaks French....\n\n...He therefore brings a certain amount of liberal-leaning finesse and \u00e9lan to his encounters. He is sympathetic to deserters from the [[Iraq War]] and particularly severe on capitalist profiteers. You feel he would probably turn up at an [[Occupy Wall Street]] demo. There is something of the hippie in his rootless roaming around America, seeking out injustice and righting wrongs.<ref name= \"EmilySargent2011\"/>}}\n\nCurtis concurs, remarking that \"Reacher isn't just a mindless vigilante. He can also be a liberal do-gooder. He has expressed sympathy for gays in the military and undocumented immigrants. In Child's latest book,'' A Wanted Man'', Reacher worries that the [[Patriot Act]] will lead to all sorts of 'national security bullshit.' Child has invented a kind of progressive vigilantism. The scumbag is killed, but usually for the right reasons.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\nMultiple critics have pointed out that the Jack Reacher character is characterized by his spells of silence,<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/><ref name= \"MichaelCavacini2014\"/> with Curtis claiming \"Reacher's classic line is silence.\"<ref name=CurtisMarch2013/>\n\nOthers have been critical of the various implausibilities and contradictions present in the character and his behavior. Notes ''[[The Washington Post]]'' journalist Kevin Nance: \"The unlikelihoods and outright impossibilities stack up. Ever a frugal sort, Reacher travels mostly by hitchhiking (as he does at the beginning of \"A Wanted Man\" and 2001's \"Echo Burning,\" both set roughly in the time they were written), even though the practice is roughly as current as bellbottoms and even though his appearance is, as previously established, notably simian. (Not that this deters a series of smart, attractive young women, most of them officers of the law, from jumping into bed with him.) And although he's a loner who seems never so happy \u2014 rather like Agent Cooper in \"Twin Peaks\" \u2014 as when sitting quietly in a diner with a cup of black coffee and a piece of pie, he has an uncanny knack for stumbling into the worst kinds of trouble, almost none of it connected to himself.\"<ref name=\"KevinNance2012\">{{cite web| last= Nance |first= Kevin |title= Why is the character of Jack Reacher so popular? |url=  https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/why-is-the-character-of-jack-reacher-so-popular/2012/12/13/dcdfe816-3d7d-11e2-ae43-cf491b837f7b_story.html# |magazine= [[The Washington Post]] |accessdate= 7 March 2016 |date= 14 December 2012 }}</ref> Michael Cavacini has concurred with this, stating that unlike traditional [[whodunit]]s, where a detective \"simply solves a problem because it's his job\", Reacher has no formal reason to be involved in anything and consequently \"seems to always wind up in a situation where something goes wrong and he must make right\".<ref name=\"MichaelCavacini2014\">{{cite web| last= Cavacini |first= Michael |title= An Interview With International Best-Selling Author Lee Child|url=  https://michaelcavacini.com/2014/09/04/an-interview-with-international-best-selling-author-lee-child/ |accessdate= 1 March 2016|date=2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Accomplices==\nLee Child has described Reacher's accomplices and their characterization and origin in the following terms: \" The whole cast for each book is new. It kind of depends on what the scenario is and what the set up is. Do I use people that I actually know? In a way yeah, because you met people and you regard them as meta-typical as one thing or another \u2013 so as a large extent, yes, they are based on people I've met but not specific individuals.\"<ref name=\"AmieFlanagan2014\">{{cite web|last=Flanagan |first= Amie|title=An Interview With Lee Child |url= http://www.keystothepage.com/interviews/interview-lee-child/|magazine= Keys To The Page |date= 9 September 2014|accessdate= 8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-military era===\n'''Jill Hemingway''', age 34 according to a police transmission, was a suspended [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent operating freelance in New York during 1977. She had been investigating the criminal activities of a New York mobster, Croselli but her investigation had been shut down and she had been suspended, pending review as part of a deal cut by Croselli with the FBI. She had since tried to unsuccessfully bring Croselli down by getting him to boast of his crimes on tape. She admitted that bringing down Croselli had become somewhat of an obsession for her, stating \"[Croselli] burns her up.\"<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7|location = |pages = 91}}</ref> Hemingway is described as a thin, pale, nervous, blonde woman and she teams up with a nearly seventeen year old Reacher in the [[novella]] ''High Heat'' to incriminate Croselli. She suffered from heart-related ailments and she dies near the end of the story due to a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] after having accomplished her goal. Reacher commented, \"She died young, but she had a smile on her face.\"<ref>{{cite book| title = High Heat|last = Child |first= Lee |publisher = Delacorte Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-0-345-54664-7|location = |pages = 125}}</ref>\n\n===Military era===\n* '''Elizabeth Deveraux''', late 30s, is a former Marine serving as a [[county sheriff]] in [[Carter Crossing, Mississippi]] in 1997. She appears in ''The Affair'', where she tacitly condones Reacher's highly illegal ways of getting rid of some unsavory characters. She was a potential lover for Reacher, as they had sex several times, but ended up drifting apart.\n* '''Karla Dixon''', age unknown, possibly late 30s is a [[forensic accountant]]; formerly a Major in the Army and part of Reacher's 'Special Investigators Unit', which he formed and led in the 90s. They are reunited in ''Bad Luck & Trouble'' and secretly rekindle an affair, which they regret not starting back in the Army. She is described as 'dark, very pretty, comparatively small' and slim.  She is extremely good with numbers and shares Reacher's fascination with mathematics.\n* '''General Leon Garber''', retired, was Reacher's former commanding officer, mentor and close friend. His only child is Jodie. He risked his life to help Reacher in ''Die Trying'', and willed him his house, as his daughter is wealthy, didn't want it and already owns her own New York City home. He also appears in ''The Enemy'' and ''The Affair'', and (through his funeral) in ''Tripwire''.\n* '''Jodie Garber-Jacob''', 30, is the daughter of General Leon Garber. She met and fell in love with Reacher when she was 15 and was off-limits to him. In ''Tripwire'', she is divorced, using her married name, working as a corporate attorney and reunites romantically with him after her father's funeral. She and Reacher lived together in New York City and upstate New York in Leon's house which was left in his will to Reacher, his surrogate son. She is mentioned in ''Echo Burning'' as having moved to Europe. She appears in ''Tripwire'', and ''The Visitor'' (\"Running Blind\" in the United States).\n* '''Eileen Ann Hutton''', age unknown, is a Brigadier General in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Army's Judge Advocate General's Corps]]. She and Reacher had a relationship prior to, and featured in, ''One Shot''.\n* '''Dominique Kohl''', 29, was a Sergeant First Class on the way up and assigned to Reacher's unit when he was a captain in the Army. She appears in ''Persuader'', where Reacher remembers the events that led to her death ten years earlier.  Kohl is mentioned again in ''Personal'', when Reacher partners with a woman who reminds him of Kohl.\n* '''Stan Lowrey''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He is handsome, youthful, and full of energy. A kind of man that gets the job done. He appears in ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' and ''The Affair''.\n* '''Duncan Munro''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He appears in ''The Affair''.\n* '''Frances Neagley''', late 30s, is a partner with a successful private security firm, and former Army Master Sergeant and Military Policeman. She is of medium height, slim, and has dark hair and eyes. She spends large amounts of time in the gym and has a purely [[platonic relationship]] with Reacher. However, in ''Night School'' (2016), NSA senior Deputy Marian Sinclair notes Neagley's attraction to Reacher, and her refusal to sleep with him.<ref name=\"NightSchool187\">{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Night School | year= 2016 |location= London| publisher= Transworld Publishers, 2016 |page= 187}}</ref>  Reacher points out that Neagley has [[Haphephobia|haptephobia]], \"A fear of being touched.\"<ref name=\"NightSchool187\" /> When Sinclair asks if the condition is as a result of assault, Reacher responds, \"She says she was born with it.\"<ref name=\"NightSchool188\">{{cite book| first= Lee| last= Child |title= Night School | year= 2016 |location= London| publisher= Transworld Publishers, 2016 |page= 188}}</ref> Her demeanor suggests that she could be considered a female counterpart to Reacher. Rarely impressed, Reacher describes her as sometimes scary. She appears in ''Without Fail'', ''The Affair'' and ''Bad Luck and Trouble'',  ''Night School'', and ''Small Wars'' and is mentioned in ''Never Go Back''. The first page of ''Bad Luck and Trouble'' includes a dedication \"For the real Frances L. Neagley\", who won a [[Bouchercon]] charity auction for the naming rights to a character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/features/arts/offthepage/blog/2007/09/characters_welcomed_and_you_can_be_one_too.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232851/http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/features/arts/offthepage/blog/2007/09/characters_welcomed_and_you_can_be_one_too.html |archivedate= 3 March 2016 |title=Characters welcomed! And you can be one, too |website=weblogs.sun-sentinel.com |publisher=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |first=Oline |last=Cogdill |date=13 September 2007 |access-date=29 March 2017 }}</ref>\n* '''Dave O'Donnell''', late 30s, is a member of Reacher's old 110th MP unit. He appears in ''Bad Luck and Trouble''. He is \"tall, fair, handsome, like a stockbroker... carries an army blade in one pocket and a pair of ceramic [[brass-knuckles]] in the other.\" The ceramic knuckles are made from a composite stronger than steel, harder than brass and gets past any metal detector. He is meticulous, doesn't mind paperwork, and is usually underestimated because he looks like a white-collar office worker.\n* '''Lieutenant Summer''', 25, is an African-American Lieutenant in the Army Military Police. She is cute, petite and slender, and appears in ''The Enemy''. She is Reacher's accomplice throughout the novel and they have a brief relationship. She is promoted to Captain at the end of the novel.\n\n===Wandering era===\n* '''Alice Amanda Aaron''', an attorney, appears in ''Echo Burning''.\n* '''Michelle Chang''', an ex-FBI agent turned private investigator. Appears in ''Make Me''.\n* '''Susan Duffy''', appears in ''Persuader''.\n* '''M.E. (Mary Ellen) Froelich''', a Secret Service Agent, appears in ''Without Fail''.\n* '''Carmen Greer''', a woman with an abusive husband, appears in ''Echo Burning''.\n* '''Lisa Harper''', another FBI agent, appears in ''The Visitor'' (''Running Blind'' in the United States).\n* '''Holly Johnson''', an FBI agent, appears in ''Die Trying''.\n* '''Detective Theresa Lee''' an NYPD Detective, appears in ''Gone Tomorrow''.\n* '''Casey Nice''', 28, described as having \"blonde hair and green eyes and a heart shaped face\"<ref>{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Bantam Press|year = 2014|isbn = 9780593073827| chapter= Chapter 2}}</ref> is a CIA analyst lent out to the [[United States Department of State|State Department]]. She reminds Reacher of Dominique Kohl and he sees her as a \"young, fit woman in the peak of condition, lean, smooth, somehow flexible and fluent and elastic\".<ref name=\"alpha\" />  She is shown to take [[Anxiolytic|anti-anxiety medication]] and shares a platonic relationship with Reacher. Casey was born and raised in downstate [[Illinois]], is a graduate from [[Yale University]] and has a distinct American accent which is exploited by Reacher<ref>{{cite book| title = Personal|last = Child|first= Lee|publisher = Bantam Press|year = 2014|isbn = 9780593073827| chapter= Chapter 30}}</ref> when she accompanies him to London in ''Personal''.\n* '''Lauren Pauling''', appears in ''The Hard Way''.\n* '''Helen Rodin''', only appears in ''One Shot'' and in the live action movie ''Jack Reacher'' based on the book.\n* '''Officer Elizabeth Roscoe''', 30, is a Margrave, Georgia police officer in ''Killing Floor''.\n* '''Julia Sorensen''', 47, teams up with Reacher in ''A Wanted Man''.\n* '''Susan Turner''', the Commanding Officer of Reacher's old unit, appears in ''61 Hours'' and ''Never Go Back''.\n* '''Vaughan''', exact age unknown, is a police officer in Hope, Colorado. She appears in ''Nothing to Lose''.\n\n== Adaptations ==\n===Film and television===\n{{main|Jack Reacher (film)|Jack Reacher: Never Go Back}}\n[[File:Jack Reacher poster.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Theatrical poster of 2012 film ''Jack Reacher'' depicting Tom Cruise]]\nThe 2012 [[action thriller]] film ''[[Jack Reacher (film)|Jack Reacher]]'' was adapted from the 2005 novel ''One Shot'' and starred [[Tom Cruise]] in the title role.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Fleming |first=Mike |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/07/tom-cruise-locked-to-play-jack-reacher-in-one-shot-for-paramount-and-skydance/ |title=Tom Cruise Locked To Play Jack Reacher In 'One Shot' For Paramount And Skydance |magazine=Deadline |date=15 July 2011 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The film was directed by [[Christopher McQuarrie]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/why-hasnt-paramount-started-making-jack-reacher-movies |title=Why hasn't Paramount started making Jack Reacher movies? |work=HitFix |date=20 October 2010 |accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> Cruise reprised the role in the sequel, ''[[Jack Reacher: Never Go Back]]'', an adaptation of the 18th Jack Reacher book ''Never Go Back'', which was directed by [[Edward Zwick]], and released 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Ed Zwick In Talks To Direct 'Jack Reacher' Sequel|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/jack-reacher-sequel-ed-zwick-director-paramount-1201429671/|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=deadline.com|date=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nTom Cruise's casting was met with criticism from fans of the book series, primarily because the disparity in their heights, with Reacher portrayed as a blond, {{convert|6|ft|5|in|abbr=on}} tall, 250-pound man in the novels, while Cruise is a {{convert|5|ft|7|in|abbr=on}} tall brunette<ref name=\"CarolynKellogg2012\"/><ref name= \"AndreaSachs2012\"/>) In 2012 Child commented on Cruise's casting by saying, \"Reacher\u2019s size in the books is a metaphor for an unstoppable force, which Cruise portrays in his own way.\" In 2018, Child expressed the opinion that the fans were right after the height of actor portraying the character.<ref name=\"DenOfGeek\" />\n\nOn November 14, 2018, Child announced that he made a deal with [[Skydance Television]] and [[Paramount Television]] to produce a ''Jack Reacher'' series based on Child's novels, during which feature films would no longer be produced. He also stated that [[Tom Cruise]] would not be returning to the role, and that another actor would be cast in the role, which he hoped would more properly represent the character than seen in the films. [[Paramount Television]] and [[Skydance Television]] are said to be produce the potential series. Child said of the recasting:\n\n<blockquote>\"I really enjoyed working with Cruise. He's a really, really nice guy. We had a lot of fun. But ultimately the readers are right. The size of Reacher is really, really important and it's a big component of who he is...So what I've decided to do is \u2013 there won't be any more movies with Tom Cruise. Instead we're going to take it to Netflix or something like that. Long-form streaming television, with a completely new actor. We're rebooting and starting over and we're going to try and find the perfect guy.<ref name=DeadlineHollywood>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/jack-reacher-tv-series-no-tom-cruise-lee-child-1202502218/|title='Jack Reacher' TV Series In The Works|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 14, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn July 15, 2019, Varity report that Amazon will develop the series for Amazon Prime with [[Nick Santora]] as the showrunner, writer and executive producer alongside with Child, Don Granger, Christopher McQuarrie, David Ellison, Dana Goldberg and Marcy Ross<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/amazon-jack-reacher-series-1203267743/|title=Amazon to Develop \u2018Jack Reacher\u2019 Series|last=Throne|first=Nick|magazine=Variety|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jack-reacher-tv-series-works-at-amazon-1224429|title='Jack Reacher' TV Series in the Works at Amazon|website=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date= 2019-07-17 }}</ref>\n\n===In other authors' works===\n* Reacher is mentioned several times in the Stephen King novel ''[[Under the Dome (novel)|Under the Dome]]'', where he is described by the character Colonel Cox as \"the toughest goddam Army cop that ever served, in my humble opinion.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Stephen|title=Under the Dome: Part 2: A Novel|date=2014|publisher=Pocket Books|location=New York|isbn=9781476767284| page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476767284/page/180 180]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781476767284|url-access=registration|accessdate=2 February 2017}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|Chester's Mills' police officer Jackie Wettington is revealed to have previously served as a military policewoman in Germany, and she is recommended to Colonel Cox by Reacher.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} }} Lee Child's endorsement of ''Under the Dome'' appears on the cover of at least one edition of the book.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n* Reacher is referred to in the ''[[Hunt for Reacher]]'' series of novels and short stories by [[Diane Capri]], but is never explicitly seen. Capri has said in an interview that the series was inspired by her wondering \"What's [Reacher] doing between books?\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sharonkowensimplycreating.wordpress.com/2012/02/04/dont-know-jack-interview-with-diane-capri/ |title=Don't Know Jack: Interview With Diane Capri |website =SharonKowenSimplycreating.wordpress.com |date=}}</ref>\n* In the introduction to ''Good and Valuable Consideration'', it is mentioned that while creating his 'Nick Heller' series character, [[Joseph Finder]] borrowed many cues from Lee Child's Jack Reacher series.<ref>{{cite book |title=  Good And Valuable Consideration |publisher= Sphere |year= 2014 |pages= 1 |isbn= 978-0-7515-6349-8| quote= When Joseph Finder decided to try a series character, he took many cues from Lee Child's Jack Reacher}}</ref>\n* David Baldacci's character [[John Puller]] is a \"bloody ripoff of Jack Reacher\" according to Lee Child.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/lee-child-on-jack-reacher-how-the-best-selling-author-writes-his-mysteries-9959227.html|title=Lee Child on Jack Reacher | website=The Independent|date=Jan 15, 2015}}</ref> Child avenged himself by having Jack Reacher break all the fingers of a villain named David Baldacci in \"Never Go Back\".\n* [[Jude Hardin]] has written about Jack Reacher in the novels ''The Jack Reacher Files: Fugitive'' and ''The Jack Reacher Experiment: Dead Ringer''.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Novels}}\n* [[Jack Reacher (book series)]]\n* [[Jack (hero)]]\n* [[Military brat]]\n* [[List of fictional military brats]]\n\n==References==\n'''Explanatory notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''[[Jack Reacher (book series)]]'''\n* {{cite book |last= Child| first= Lee |authorlink=Lee Child |title=[[Killing Floor (novel)|Killing Floor]] |publisher=Putnam |location=New York |date=1997  |isbn=0515123447 |oclc=38994823 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Die Trying (novel)|Die Trying]] |publisher= Jove |location= New York |year= 1999 |isbn= 0515125024 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Without Fail]] |publisher= Putnam |location= New York |year= 2002 |isbn= 0399148612 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Tripwire (novel)|Tripwire]] |publisher= Putnam |location= New York |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-0385336666 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Persuader (novel)|Persuader]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-0440245988 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[The Enemy (Child novel)|The Enemy]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2004 |isbn= 0385336675 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[One Shot (novel)|One Shot]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2004 |isbn= 978-0385336680 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[The Hard Way (novel)|The Hard Way]]|publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0385336697 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Bad Luck and Trouble]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0385340557 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Nothing to Lose (novel)|Nothing to Lose]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2008 |isbn= 978-0385340564 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Gone Tomorrow]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-0385340571 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[61 Hours]] | publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-0385340588 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee | title= [[Worth Dying For (novel)|Worth Dying For]] | publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-0385344319 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= [[The Affair (Child novel)|The Affair]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0440339359 }}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= [[A Wanted Man]] |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2012 |isbn= 978-044033936-6}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= High Heat |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-0345546647}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Personal|url= https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780804178747 |url-access= registration | publisher= Delacorte Press|location=New York|year= 2014|isbn = 978-0804178761}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Night School |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2016|isbn= 978-0804178808}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= The Midnight Line |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2017|isbn= 978-0399593482}}\n* {{cite book |author= Child, Lee |title= Past Tense |publisher= Delacorte Press |location= New York |year= 2018|isbn= 978-0399593512}}\n\n''' Further reading '''\n* {{cite web|last=Curtis|first=Bryan|title=The Curious Case of Lee Child: Before Tom Cruise could become Jack Reacher, Jim Grant had to become Lee Child |url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8766396/lee-child-jim-grant-jack-reacher |magazine=[[Grantland]] | accessdate=5 September 2015 |date=20 December 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.leechild.com Lee Child's official website]\n\n{{Jack Reacher}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reacher, Jack}}\n[[Category:Jack Reacher books| ]]\n[[Category:Characters in British novels of the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Characters in British novels of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Characters in crime novel series]]\n[[Category:Fictional secret agents and spies]]\n[[Category:Fictional military brats]]\n[[Category:Fictional military police of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Army personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional majors]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional Krav Maga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional aikidoka]]\n[[Category:Fictional hoboes]]\n[[Category:Fictional private investigators]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1997]]\n[[Category:Fictional Silver Star recipients]]\n[[Category:Thriller film characters]]\n[[Category:Action film characters]]\n", "name_user": "Abejschwartz", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Reacher"}
{"title_page": "Psilocybe yungensis", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Psilocybe.yungensis.Jalisco.jpg\n| image_width = 234px\n| image_caption = Found in [[Jalisco, Mexico]]\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Agaricales]]\n| familia = [[Strophariaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Psilocybe]]''\n| species = '''''P. yungensis'''''\n| binomial = ''Psilocybe yungensis''\n| binomial_authority = [[Rolf Singer|Singer]] & [[Alexander H. Smith|A.H.Sm.]] (1958)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=Guzman1978b/><ref name=Guzman2000/><ref name=\"Ramirez-Cruz2013\"/>\n| synonyms = ''Psilocybe yungensis'' var. ''diconica'' <small>A.H.Smith (1958)</small><br/>\n''Psilocybe acutissima'' <small>[[Roger Heim|Heim]] (1959)</small><br/>\n''Psilocybe chiapanensis'' <small>Guzman (1995)</small><br/>\n''Psilocybe isauri'' <small>Singer (1959)</small><br/>\n''Psilocybe subyungensis'' <small>Guzman (1978)</small>\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox\n| name=''Psilocybe yungensis''\n| whichGills=adnate\n| whichGills2=adnexed\n| capShape=conical\n| capShape2=campanulate\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter=bare\n| ecologicalType=saprotrophic\n| sporePrintColor=purple-brown\n| howEdible=psychoactive\n}}\n\n'''''Psilocybe yungensis''''' is a species of [[psychedelic mushroom]] in the family [[Strophariaceae]]. In North America, it is found in northeast, central and southeastern Mexico. In South America, it has been recorded from Bolivia, Colombia, and Ecuador. It is also known from the Caribbean island [[Martinique]], and China. The mushroom grows in clusters or groups on rotting wood. The [[basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] have conical to bell-shaped reddish- to orangish-brown [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] that are up to {{convert|2.5|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in diameter, set atop slender [[stipe (mycology)|stems]] {{convert|3|to|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. The mushrooms stain blue when bruised, indicative of the presence of the compound [[psilocybin]]. ''Psilocybe yungensis'' is used by [[Mazatec people|Mazatec Indians]] in the Mexican State of [[Oaxaca]] for [[entheogen]]ic purposes.\n\n==Taxonomy and classification==\nThe species was described as new to science by American mycologists [[Rolf Singer]] and [[Alexander H. Smith]], based on specimens collected in [[Nor Yungas Province]], [[Bolivia]], on the road to [[La Paz]] to [[Coroico]].<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/> They published a short description in [[Latin]] in a 1958 ''[[Mycologia]]'' publication,<ref name=Singer1958/> followed by a more detailed description in English later that year.<ref name=Singer1958b/> According to ''[[Psilocybe]]'' specialist [[Gast\u00f3n Guzm\u00e1n]], the species ''Psilocybe acutissima'' (described by [[Roger Heim]] in 1958<ref name=Heim1958/>), and ''Psilocybe isauri'' (described by Singer in 1959<ref name=Singer1959/>) are [[synonym (biology)|synonyms]], as both the macroscopic and microscopic features are the same in the [[type (biology)|type]] material of all three.<ref name=Guzman2000/> Singer considered ''P.&nbsp;isauri'' a species distinct from ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' because of differences in the hairiness of the stem surface. Smith named the [[variety (botany)|variety]] ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' var. ''diconica'' for specimens he found with conical, rather than obconical (the form of an inverted cone) [[umbo (mycology)|papilla]]. Similarly, the main distinguishing feature that Heim ascribed to ''P.&nbsp;acutissima'' was a [[papillate]] cap (somewhat resembling the shape of a female human breast). Later studies showed that these [[morphology (biology)|morphological]] variations did not warrant individual recognition, because of the variable nature of these characteristics, and the existence of intermediate forms.<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/>\n\nGuzm\u00e1n places ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' in the [[section (biology)|section]] ''Cordisporae'', a grouping of ''Psilocybe'' species characterized primarily by having [[rhomboid]] spores less than 8&nbsp;[[micrometer]]s long.<ref>Guzm\u00e1n (1983), p. 106.</ref> The [[specific name (botany)|specific epithet]] ''yungensis'' refers to the name of the [[type locality (biology)|type locality]].<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/> The natives of [[Huautla de Jim\u00e9nez]] and [[Mixe]] natives call ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' a ''hongo adivinador'' (\"divinatory mushroom\"), ''hong que adormece'' (\"soporific mushroom\"), or ''hongo genio'' (\"genius mushroom\").<ref name=Stamets1996/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Psilocybe yungensis 163986.jpg|thumb|left|Caps range in shape from conical to bell-shaped, and have a prominent umbo. Stems are densely covered with whitish fibrils pressed flat against the surface.]]\nThe ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' [[Basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] have [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] that are conical to bell-shaped in maturity, and reach a diameter of up to {{convert|2.5|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}. The cap surface is smooth and sticky, and, in moist specimens, has faint radial striations (grooves) that extend almost to the margin. The color of fresh caps ranges from dark reddish-brown to rusty brown to orangish-brown. Additionally, the cap is [[hygrophanous]], meaning it will change color depending on its state of hydration; a dry cap fades to become dull yellowish-brown or the color of \"dingy straw\". The cap frequently has a prominent [[umbo (mycology)|umbo]].<ref name=Stamets1996/>\n\nThe [[lamella (mycology)|gill]] attachment ranges from adnate (broadly attached to the stem) to adnexed (narrowly attached). The spacing of the narrow gills is close to crowded, and the gill color is initially dull gray before maturing spores cause the color to change to purplish-brown. The [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is {{convert|3|to|5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1.5|to|2.5|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} thick, and more or less equal in width throughout its length or slightly larger near the base. The hollow, brittle, stem is pale brown on the upper part, and reddish-brown near the bottom. The stem is densely covered with whitish fibrils that are pressed flat against the surface; the fibrils slough off in maturity to leave a smooth surface.<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/> The mushroom has a cortinate [[partial veil]] (resembling the webby cortina produced by species of ''[[Cortinarius]]'') but it does not last for long; it occasionally leaves behind sparse remnants of tissue hanging on the cap margin and the upper part of the stem. No [[annulus (mycology)|ring]] remains on the stem after the veil disappears. All parts of the mushroom will stain blue when injured; these stains will blacken as the mushroom dries.<ref name=Stamets1996/>\n{{multiple image | align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header =\n| width = 200\n| image1 = Psilocybe yungensis 171324.jpg\n| caption1 = Spores and translucent cheilocystidia\n| image2 = Psilocybe yungensis 171250.jpg\n| caption2 = [[Cap cuticle]], cap tissue, and gill tissue at 100x magnification\n}}\nThe [[spore print]] is dark purplish-brown. [[Spore]]s range in shape from roughly [[rhombus|rhomboid]] to roughly elliptical, and typically have dimensions of 5\u20136 by 4\u20136&nbsp;[[micrometre|\u03bcm]].<ref name=Stamets1996/> They are thick-walled and have a large [[germ pore]]. The [[basidia]] (spore-bearing cells) are club-shaped to swollen, hyaline, usually four-spored (although rarely two- or three-spored forms are present), and measure 13\u201319 by 4.4\u20136.6&nbsp;\u03bcm.<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\">Guzm\u00e1n (1983), pp. 150\u20132.</ref> The pleurocystidia ([[cystidia]] on the gill face) are ventricose (swollen) near the base and often mucronate (ending abruptly in a short sharp point) at the apex, and measure 14\u201325 by 4.4\u201310.5&nbsp;\u03bcm. The cheilocystidia (cystidia on the gill edge) are variable in shape, and measure 14\u201340 by 4.4\u20137.7&nbsp;\u03bcm.<ref name=Stamets1996/> Pleurocystidia are relatively sparse, while cheilocystidia are abundant. [[Clamp connection]]s are present in the [[hypha]]e. The application of a drop of [[potassium hydroxide]] solution turns both the cap and the stem from brown to blackish.<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/>\n\n===Similar species===\nThe species ''[[Psilocybe subyungensis]]'', known only from [[Venezuela]], is roughly similar in form, although somewhat smaller, with a cap width of up to {{convert|1|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} in diameter and stem lengths of up to {{convert|3.5|cm|in|abbr=on}}. In addition to differences in distribution, it can be clearly distinguished from ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' by the larger cystidia: the pleurocystidia measure 8.8\u201311 by 3.8\u20135.5&nbsp;\u03bcm, and the cheilocystidia 16.5\u201325 by 7.7\u201312&nbsp;\u03bcm.<ref name=Guzman1978/> Stamets notes that \"Few species resemble ''P.&nbsp;yungensis''\", while Michael Beug considers the orangish-brown cap color unusual for a ''Psilocybe'', and compares it to ''[[Conocybe]]''.<ref name=Beug2011/>\n\n==Habitat and distribution==\n''Psilocybe yungensis'' is a [[saprobic]] species, and contributes to the degradation of organic matter deposited in soils and [[nutrient cycling]] in forests where it grows.<ref>Guzm\u00e1n (1983), p. 22.</ref> It typically grows in clusters or groups on rotting wood (rarely on [[humus]]); it is less frequently found growing solitarily. It is often reported from coffee plantations, [[tropical moist forests|subtropical]], or [[cloud forest]]s, especially those occurring at elevations between {{convert|1000|and|2000|m|abbr=on}}. The species occurs in northeast, central and southeastern Mexico, and has been recorded from several locations in the states of [[Oaxaca]], [[Puebla]], [[Tamaulipas]] and [[Veracruz]].<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/><ref name=Guzman1988/> It is also known from [[Bolivia]], [[Colombia]], and [[Ecuador]],<ref name=Stamets1996/> as well as the Caribbean island [[Martinique]].<ref name=Guzman2000/> In 2009, it was reported from China.<ref name=Bau2009/> In Mexico and Colombia, the fungus usually fruits between June and July; in Bolivia, it was recorded appearing during January.<ref name=\"Guzman1983pp.150-2\"/>\n\n==Uses==\nThe fruit bodies of ''Psilocybe yungensis'' are used for [[entheogen]]ic, or spiritual, ritualistic purposes by the [[Mazatec people|Mazatec Indians]] in the Mexican State of [[Oaxaca]].<ref name=Guzman2008/> Some authorities have suggested that ''P.&nbsp;yungensis'' is the \"tree fungus\" reported by [[Jesuit missionaries]] of the 17th and 18th centuries, a reddish mushroom that was apparently the source of an intoxicating beverage used by the [[Yurimagua]] Indians of [[Peruvian Amazon|Amazonian Peru]]. There is, however, no established record of hallucinogenic mushroom use in that area,<ref name=Schultes1966/><ref name=Schultes1969/> and it is possible that the mushroom could instead be a psychedelic species of the wood-dwelling genus ''[[Gymnopilus]]''.<ref name=Gartz1996/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Fungi}}\n*[[Legal status of psilocybin mushrooms]]\n*[[List of Psilocybin mushrooms]]\n*[[List of Psilocybe species|List of ''Psilocybe'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=Bau2009>{{cite journal |author=Bau T. |title=Strophariaceae of China. (IV). ''Psilocybe'' |journal=Journal of Fungal Research |year=2009 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=14\u201336 |issn=1672-3538  |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Beug2011>{{cite journal |author=Beug M. |title=The genus ''Psilocybe'' in North America |journal=Fungi Magazine |year=2011 |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=6\u201317 |url=http://www.fungimag.com/summer-2011-articles/FungiSUM_GenusPsilocybeNA_LR.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331105044/http://www.fungimag.com/summer-2011-articles/FungiSUM_GenusPsilocybeNA_LR.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-31 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Gartz1996>{{cite book |author=Gartz J. |year=1996 |title=Magic Mushrooms Around the World. A Scientific Journey Across Cultures and Time |publisher=LIS P