University Press of Kansas. {{ISBN|0-700-61444-3}}. {{OCLC|62593627}} \n* {{cite book|first1=Assaf |last1=Moghadam|first2=William Lee|last2= Eubank|title=The Roots of Terrorism|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=DQdgnRgXeiUC}}|year=2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-7910-8307-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Brent L. |last=Smith|title=Terrorism in America: Pipe Bombs and Pipe Dreams|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=-3CuViIjqj8C}}|date=25 January 1994|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-1760-7|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [https://www.sv.uio.no/c-rex/english/rtv/index.html Right-wing terrorism and violence in Western Europe: the RTV dataset. C-REX - Center for Research on Extremism.]\n* {{cite news|publisher=BBC News|series=Reality Check|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47626859|title=How prevalent is far-right extremism?|first1=Ben|last1=Butcher|first2=Micah|last2=Luxen|date=19 March 2019}}\n* Florian Hartleb: Lone wolves. The New Terrorism of Right-Wing Single Actors, Heidelberg et al. 2020, Springer, {{ISBN|978-3-030-36152-5}}.\n\n{{white nationalism}}\n\n[[Category:Far-right terrorism| ]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics|Terrorism]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist terrorism]]\n[[Category:Terrorism by form]]\n[[Category:Political violence]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics|Terrorism]]\n[[Category:Hate crime]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "unsuccesfully->unsuccessfully -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-wing_terrorism"}
{"title_page": "Zabir Saeed", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2012}}\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Zabir Saeed<br>{{Nastaliq|\u0632\u0627\u0628\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u06cc\u062f }}\n| image              = Zabir Saeed.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Zabir Saeed\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|05|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Islamic Republic of Pakistan]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = Masters in Mass Communication from University of Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan.\n| occupation         = Journalist/Author\n| alias              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = \n| domestic_partner   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| ethnicity          = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| credits            = \n| agent              = \n| website            = [http://www.Zabirsaeed.com/ www.zabirsaeed.com]\n[http://www.Zabirsaeedbadar.com/ www.zabirsaeedbadar.com]\n}}\n\n'''Zabir Saeed'''{{Nastaliq|\u0632\u0627\u0628\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u06cc\u062f }} (born May 22, 1972) is a [[Pakistan]]i journalist and editor, known for his columns in Urdu and English newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/283453-briefs...|title=briefs...|publisher=}}</ref> He is also a writer and public relations practitioner.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090824024721/http://www.ue.edu.pk/admin/newsletter/newletter4.pdf ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/oct2011-weekly/nos-23-10-2011/pol1.htm#2|title=Pol Eco, NOS, The News International|website=jang.com.pk}}</ref> He has written more than Fifty books about the subjects of mass communication and journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-5-235879-Book-published|title=The News International: Latest News Breaking, Pakistan News|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref><ref name=\"Journalist awarded\">{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/24-May-2019/journalist-awarded|title=Journalist awarded|date=2019-05-24|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\nSaeed received his early education from Saint Joseph School in [[Lahore]], and matriculated from government pilot secondary school, one of the best educational institutions of the time. He completed his F. Sc & B. Sc from Islamia College in Lahore, and then earned his master's degree in mass communication from the department of mass communication of the University of the Punjab in 1996 with distinction. He earned an M.A. in history from the same university.\n\n=== Career ===\n\nSaeed was inspired by his father Saeed Badar, who is also a poet, journalist and writer. His grandfather Hakeem Muhammad Yaqub Munir Azeemi Qadri was another source of guidance and inspiration for him. He has written a book on his life and works. He has contributed articles to several newspapers of Pakistan, such as the dailies Jang, Imroze, and the Pakistan Times. He started his journalistic career as sub-editor for the Lahore daily Nawa-e-waqt. Subsequently, he joined Pakistan\u2019s Jang media group in 2002. He also rendered his services as a public relations practitioner to the water and sanitation agency(WASA) and the University of Education in Lahore as well as other public relations organizations.\n\n=== Achievements ===\nZabir Saeed is renowned as media strategist, public relations practitioner, communication educationist, research scholar and a writer of dozen of books in the fields of Journalism, Mass Communication, Public Relations, History and Current Affairs .\nHe is also known for his articles, columns, features, children stories and won many awards as best feature writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/writers/zabir-saeed-badar/|title=Zabir Saeed Badar Archives - TNS - The News on Sunday|website=tns.thenews.com.pk}}</ref>\n\nHe actively participated in various literary activities and he is the president of South Asian Literary Forum (SALF).Now -a-days he is associated with the largest Media group of Pakistan the JANG GROUP. He is also delivering lectures in Institute of Communication Studies, University of the Punjab, and many other leading universities as a senior visiting professor. He has been awarded the best Media Educationist for the year 2015 by (SALF)<ref name=\"pakobserver.net\">[http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=288145 ]{{dead link|date=May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nation.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/lahore/06-Feb-2016/journalist-awarded|title=Journalist awarded|date=6 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and Recently Zabir Saeed Badar has been given the Lifetime Achievement Award by Pakistan Writers Guild and Qalam Foundation International<ref name=\"Journalist awarded\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epaper.dawn.com/DetailImage.php?StoryImage=23_05_2019_177_007|title=Journalist honoured {{!}} ePaper {{!}} DAWN.COM|website=epaper.dawn.com|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nHe organized the first Perween Shakir literary award in Pakistan in 1995.\nHe is a pioneer of publishing community newspapers of Pakistan in Lahore, founding Makhzan-e-Iqbal, which was the first of its kind.\nHe is a council member of the Lahore Press club and the Pakistan Federal Union of Journalists.\n\n=== Books and publications ===\n\nHe has written more than fifty books in the subjects of mass communication, journalism, history, literature, and social psychology.<ref name=\"nation.com.pk\"/><ref name=\"pakobserver.net\"/>\nHe has also written about 1,000 articles, features, columns, and editorials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prntstyl.asp?strid=618&strdesc=Journalism+/+Sahafat&mnstrdesc=Urdu+Books|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online bookstore ::|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n\n===Partial bibliography===\n* Ablagh Aama Aur Development Sport Communication\n* Ablagh Aama Aur Badalti Dunya\n* Zaban Aur Ablagh\n* Idarat Aur Us Key Jadeed Rujhanaat\n* Khabar Aur Khabriyat\n* Pakistan Aur Global World\n* Sahafat Say Ablaghiat Tak<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/314987-briefs...|title=Briefs...|publisher=}}</ref>\n* The Voyage of Mass Communication<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/lahore/28-May-2015/book-published|title=Book published|date=28 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Pakistan Aur Global World<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=78320|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Mass Communication Advanced Studies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=99766|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Media Research<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115365|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Media History laws And Ethics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115367|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Magazine Journalism<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115368|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Language Skills And Communicative Abilities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115372|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Pakistan Aur Foj\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saeed, Zabir}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{mi|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2012}}\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Zabir Saeed<br>{{Nastaliq|\u0632\u0627\u0628\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u06cc\u062f }}\n| image              = Zabir Saeed.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Zabir Saeed\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|05|22}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Islamic Republic of Pakistan]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = Masters in Mass Communication from University of Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan.\n| occupation         = Journalist/Author\n| alias              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = \n| domestic_partner   = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| ethnicity          = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| credits            = \n| agent              = \n| website            = [http://www.Zabirsaeed.com/ www.zabirsaeed.com]\n[http://www.Zabirsaeedbadar.com/ www.zabirsaeedbadar.com]\n}}\n\n'''Zabir Saeed'''{{Nastaliq|\u0632\u0627\u0628\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u06cc\u062f }} (born May 22, 1972) is a [[Pakistan]]i journalist and editor, known for his columns in Urdu and English newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/283453-briefs...|title=briefs...|publisher=}}</ref> He is also a writer and public relations practitioner.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090824024721/http://www.ue.edu.pk/admin/newsletter/newletter4.pdf ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/oct2011-weekly/nos-23-10-2011/pol1.htm#2|title=Pol Eco, NOS, The News International|website=jang.com.pk}}</ref> He has written more than Fifty books about the subjects of mass communication and journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-5-235879-Book-published|title=The News International: Latest News Breaking, Pakistan News|website=www.thenews.com.pk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/24-May-2019/journalist-awarded|title=Journalist awarded|date=2019-05-24|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\nSaeed received his early education from Saint Joseph School in [[Lahore]], and matriculated from government pilot secondary school, one of the best educational institutions of the time. He completed his F. Sc & B. Sc from Islamia College in Lahore, and then earned his master's degree in mass communication from the department of mass communication of the University of the Punjab in 1996 with distinction. He earned an M.A. in history from the same university.\n\n=== Career ===\n\nSaeed was inspired by his father Saeed Badar, who is also a poet, journalist and writer. His grandfather Hakeem Muhammad Yaqub Munir Azeemi Qadri was another source of guidance and inspiration for him. He has written a book on his life and works. He has contributed articles to several newspapers of Pakistan, such as the dailies Jang, Imroze, and the Pakistan Times. He started his journalistic career as sub-editor for the Lahore daily Nawa-e-waqt. Subsequently, he joined Pakistan\u2019s Jang media group in 2002. He also rendered his services as a public relations practitioner to the water and sanitation agency(WASA) and the University of Education in Lahore as well as other public relations organizations.\n\n=== Achievements ===\nZabir Saeed is renowned as media strategist, public relations practitioner, communication educationist, research scholar and a writer of dozen of books in the fields of Journalism, Mass Communication, Public Relations, History and Current Affairs .\nHe is also known for his articles, columns, features, children stories and won many awards as best feature writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tns.thenews.com.pk/writers/zabir-saeed-badar/|title=Zabir Saeed Badar Archives - TNS - The News on Sunday|website=tns.thenews.com.pk}}</ref>\n\nHe actively participated in various literary activities and he is the president of South Asian Literary Forum (SALF).Now -a-days he is associated with the largest Media group of Pakistan the JANG GROUP. He is also delivering lectures in Institute of Communication Studies, University of the Punjab, and many other leading universities as a senior visiting professor. He has been awarded the best Media Educationist for the year 2015 by (SALF)<ref name=\"pakobserver.net\">[http://pakobserver.net/detailnews.asp?id=288145 ]{{dead link|date=May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nation.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/lahore/06-Feb-2016/journalist-awarded|title=Journalist awarded|date=6 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and Recently Zabir Saeed Badar has been given the Lifetime Achievement Award by Pakistan Writers Guild and Qalam Foundation International<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/24-May-2019/journalist-awarded|title=Journalist awarded|date=2019-05-24|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://epaper.dawn.com/DetailImage.php?StoryImage=23_05_2019_177_007|title=Journalist honoured {{!}} ePaper {{!}} DAWN.COM|website=epaper.dawn.com|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\nHe organized the first Perween Shakir literary award in Pakistan in 1995.\nHe is a pioneer of publishing community newspapers of Pakistan in Lahore, founding Makhzan-e-Iqbal, which was the first of its kind.\nHe is a council member of the Lahore Press club and the Pakistan Federal Union of Journalists.\n\n=== Books and publications ===\n\nHe has written more than fifty books in the subjects of mass communication, journalism, history, literature, and social psychology.<ref name=\"nation.com.pk\"/><ref name=\"pakobserver.net\"/>\nHe has also written about 1,000 articles, features, columns, and editorials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prntstyl.asp?strid=618&strdesc=Journalism+/+Sahafat&mnstrdesc=Urdu+Books|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online bookstore ::|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n\n===Partial bibliography===\n* Ablagh Aama Aur Development Sport Communication\n* Ablagh Aama Aur Badalti Dunya\n* Zaban Aur Ablagh\n* Idarat Aur Us Key Jadeed Rujhanaat\n* Khabar Aur Khabriyat\n* Pakistan Aur Global World\n* Sahafat Say Ablaghiat Tak<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/314987-briefs...|title=Briefs...|publisher=}}</ref>\n* The Voyage of Mass Communication<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/lahore/28-May-2015/book-published|title=Book published|date=28 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Pakistan Aur Global World<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=78320|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Mass Communication Advanced Studies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=99766|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Media Research<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115365|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Media History laws And Ethics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115367|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Magazine Journalism<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115368|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Language Skills And Communicative Abilities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saeedbookbank.com/prod.asp?bstslrid=115372|title=Welcome to SAEED BOOK BANK :: One of the largest online book store ::|first=Saeed Book|last=Bank|website=www.saeedbookbank.com}}</ref>\n* Pakistan Aur Foj\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saeed, Zabir}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani male journalists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zabir_Saeed"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Winship", "text_new": "{{use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Tommy Winship\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Thomas Winship<ref name=Joyce/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1890|7|14|df=y}}<ref name=Joyce/>\n|birth_place = [[Byker]], England\n|death_date  = 1976<ref name=Joyce/>\n|death_place = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=Arse>{{cite web |url=http://www.blog.woolwicharsenal.co.uk/archives/8919 |title=Tommy Winship played in the first game at Highbury |website=woolwicharsenal.co.uk |publisher= |date=26 December 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n|position    = [[Outside left]]\n|youthyears1 = \u2013         |youthclubs1 = \n|years1      = \u2013         |clubs1 = Sleekburn Villa\n|years2      = \u2013         |clubs2 = [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]]\n|years3      = 1910\u20131913 |caps3 = 28  |goals3 = 3  |clubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]]        \n|years4      = 1913      |caps4 = 2   |goals4 = 0  |clubs4 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]                   \n|years5      = 1913\u20131915 |caps5 = 27  |goals5 = 4  |clubs5 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal / Arsenal]]        \n|years6      = 1919      |caps6 = 8   |goals6 = 2  |clubs6 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepools United]]{{efn|Appearances and goals in the Northern Victory League.<ref name=ITMC/>}} \n|years7      = 1919\u20131926 |caps7 = 146 |goals7 = 17 |clubs7 = [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]]{{efn|Appearances and goals in [[the Football League]] only.<!-- if anyone has a reliable source for his NEL stats, please add them (with a reference) -->}}\n|years8      = 1926\u20131927 |caps8 = 19  |goals8 = 1  |clubs8 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] \n|years9      = 1927\u201319?? |clubs9 = [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Winship''' (14 July 1890&nbsp;\u2013 1976), generally known as '''Tom''' or '''Tommy Winship''', but also referred to as '''Wee Winship''' because of his small stature,<ref name=Arse/><ref name=ITMC/> was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as an [[outside left]]. He scored 25 goals from 222 appearances in [[the Football League]] playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]] and [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] before the First World War and for [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] and [[Crewe Alexandra]] after it.<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData |location=Nottingham |page=285 |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref>\n\nWinship began his football career in the area local to his native [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] for clubs including [[North-Eastern League]] club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]], from where he joined [[Football League First Division]] club Woolwich Arsenal in late 1910. He made nearly 30 first-team appearances in a little over two years, then spent the last few weeks of the 1912\u201313 season with Fulham before returning to Arsenal, by then a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] team. In the two seasons before the Football League was suspended for the duration of the First World War, he took his appearance total to 56 matches, then returned to the north-east where he worked in shipbuilding and then served in the [[Royal Engineers]].\n\nAfter the war, he played for [[Hartlepools United]] in the Northern Victory League, then helped Darlington reach runners-up spot in the 1919\u201320 North-Eastern League and win the title the following year. Darlington were elected to the newly formed [[Football League Third Division North|Northern Section of the Third Division]] in 1921, and Winship contributed to their second-place finish in their first season and their Northern Section title in 1924\u201325. Before Winship could represent Darlington in Second Division football, they had to pay \u00a3100 to Arsenal to transfer his registration, which that club had retained. He was not a regular at the higher level, but still took his total of league appearances for Darlington to nearly 150 over five seasons. He then spent one last season in the Football League with Third Division Crewe Alexandra before winding down his career back with Wallsend.\n\n==Early life and career==\nWinship was born in the [[Byker]] area of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], which was then part of [[Northumberland]],<ref name=Joyce/> the third child of John Winship, a brickmaker, and his wife Mary.<ref name=1891Census>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=gbc/1891/0028928017 |title=1891 England, Wales & Scotland Census Transcription Wilfred Street, Byker, Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England |via=[[Findmypast]] |url-access=subscription |at=Census reference: RG12 4214 38 24 |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> He began his football career in the local area, and it was playing for [[North-Eastern League]] club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]] that he earned himself a reputation as \"one of the best junior players in the North\".<ref name=BestJunior/> He attracted attention from clubs at a higher level, and in late 1910, he signed for [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]] of the [[Football League First Division]].<ref name=BestJunior>{{cite news |title=World of Sport |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=2 December 1910 |page=18}}</ref>\n\n==Woolwich Arsenal==\nWinship made his Woolwich Arsenal debut on [[Boxing Day]] 1910 against league leaders [[Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]]; United won 5\u20130.<ref name=AFCprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/history/profiles/741/tommy-winship |title=Tommy Winship |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=AK>{{cite web |url=http://www.thearsenalhistory.com/stat/aftlu.htm |title=Arsenal first team line-ups |website=The Arsenal History |publisher=Andy Kelly |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> A fortnight later, the ''[[Sheffield Daily Telegraph]]'' described the team as having \"a couple of capable, enterprising wingers, though Winship was a bit late waking up\" in a 3\u20132 defeat to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000250/19110109/050 |title=Best of five. United win a unexpectedly close match |last='Athleo' |newspaper=Sheffield Daily Telegraph |date=9 January 1911 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> He had a run of seven league matches, counting the visit of [[Aston Villa]] abandoned because of bad light, before losing his place to the established first-choice winger [[David Greenaway]].<ref name=AK/>\n\nHe came into the team for the Christmas 1911 fixtures against London rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur]]: a heavy defeat at Tottenham preceded a 3\u20131 win in muddy conditions at the [[Manor Ground (Plumstead)|Manor Ground]], in which Winship&nbsp;\u2013 described by the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' as having the ideal build for work in mud&nbsp;\u2013 played a major role. He crossed the ball to give [[Charles Lewis (footballer)|Charles Lewis]] an opening goal from close range, Arsenal's second goal followed the free kick awarded when he was fouled, and he scored \"an exceptionally clever\" third himself.<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal avenged. 'Spurs defeated on a morass at Plumstead |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=27 December 1911 |page=6}}</ref> It was his first competitive goal for Arsenal, and his second came a few days later in a 2\u20132 draw with Aston Villa.<ref name=AK/> In mid-March, he was carried off the field with what the ''[[Daily Express]]'' called a nasty leg injury in a match against [[West Bromwich Albion]] and played no further part in the first team that season.<ref name=AK/><ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal checked. Albion demonstrate marked superiority |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=18 March 1912 |page=8}}</ref> Winship married Rose Kilpatrick in Newcastle later that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://durhamlightinfantry.webs.com/thosewhoproudlyserved.htm |title=Those Who Proudly Served: 4449147 Pte Anthony Corkhill 2 DLI |website=Durham Light Infantry 1920\u20131946 |accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd/m/1912/3/az/001157/049 |url-access=subscription |via=Findmypast |title=England & Wales marriages 1837\u20132008 Transcription |at=Thomas Winship. Marriage quarter: 3. Marriage year: 1912. Spouse's last name: Kilpatrick. District: Newcastle upon Tyne. County: Northumberland. Volume: 10B. Page: 206 |accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912\u201313, he played 14 league matches, scoring once,<ref name=AK/> before signing for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] just ahead of the March transfer deadline.<ref>{{cite news |title=Important transfer |last=Mancunian |newspaper=Manchester Courier |date=14 March 1913 |page=2 |via=Findmypast }}</ref> Arsenal were [[relegated]] to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] at the end of that season, and promptly re-signed Winship, who had played just twice for Fulham. Questions were asked as to the probity of the transfer&nbsp;\u2013 Sir [[Henry Norris (businessman)|Henry Norris]] had been and remained a director of Fulham before becoming major shareholder in and chairman of Arsenal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blog.woolwicharsenal.co.uk/archives/10239 |title=When Arsenal died one man stepped up and rescued the club. The story of May 1910 |first1=Tony |last1=Attwood |first2=Andy |last2=Kelly |first3=Mark |last3=Andrews |website=The History of Arsenal |publisher=AISA Arsenal History Society |date=13 May 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 but [[the Football League]]'s management committee ratified his return.<ref>{{cite news |title=English Football League settle transfers and players' claims |newspaper=Dundee Courier |date=14 June 1913 |page=7 |quote=An explanation as to the transfer of Winship from Fulham to Woolwich, about which there had been some doubt, was accepted. |via=Findmypast }}</ref> Woolwich Arsenal began the 1913\u201314 season in their new stadium with the visit of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 6 September. The visitors took a one-goal lead, and [[George Jobey]] scored the equaliser&nbsp;\u2013 Arsenal's first goal at what would become generally known as [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]]&nbsp;\u2013 with a header from Winship's corner; Arsenal won 2\u20131.<ref name=Highbury>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Smith |title=Highbury: The Story of Arsenal Stadium |chapterurl=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1WkMvY5vYL8C&pg=PT91&lpg=PT91 |chapter=Fifteen: Landmark Games |publisher=Mainstream |location=Edinburgh |date=2005 |isbn=1 84596 104 8}}</ref>\n\nLater that season, the club dropped the \"Woolwich\" from its name and began to call itself The Arsenal. Winship scored the first goal for the club under that new name to equalise against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]: Jobey sent a free kick across goal \"and Winship, running in, crashed the ball into the net with a magnificent first-time drive\".<ref>{{cite news |title=City's creditable draw |newspaper=Western Daily Press |location=Bristol |date=6 April 1914 |page=9 |via=Findmypast }}</ref> He also appeared to score a winner, but the \"goal\" was disallowed; the game was temporarily halted while the police dealt with displeasure among the home support.<ref name=Highbury/> Winship never established himself as a first-team regular; his Arsenal career ended when the Football League was suspended for the duration of the First World War, at which point he had played 56 first-team matches.<ref name=AFCprofile/>\n\n==First World War==\nWinship returned to [[Tyneside]] to work in shipbuilding,<ref name=AFCprofile/> but kept up his footballing skills when he could. In October 1915, together with a number of other former professional players, he took part in a [[benefit match]] for the family of a local footballer killed on active service.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000569/19151009/068 |title=Charity match in Newcastle |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Journal |date=9 October 1915 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The following year he guested for [[Ashington A.F.C.|Ashington]] in Easter fixtures against [[Blyth Spartans]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000569/19160322/088 |title=Association football |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Journal |date=22 March 1916 |page=9 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and was expected to appear for [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]] at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in the Midland Section of the wartime league competition, but did not.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19160909/281 |title=Football. Notes on to-day's matches |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=9 September 1916 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19160911/210 |title=Football. Association |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=11 September 1916 |page=10 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> By November 1917, listed as [[Sapper#Commonwealth of Nations|Sapper]] Winship, he was guesting for Grimsby for their visit to [[Leicester Fosse]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19171124/275 |title=Football. Notes on to-day's matches |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 November 1917 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and in September 1918, he was a member of the [[Royal Engineers]] Reserve Battalion team that won a [[five-a-side]] tournament in aid of the Football National War Fund.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000400/19180907/190 |title=Sports and pastimes |newspaper=Grantham Journal |date=7 September 1918 |page=7 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In December 1918, after the war ended but before his demobilisation, [[Lance-Corporal]] Winship played for the 1st Royal Engineers stationed at [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]], [[Nottinghamshire]], against a [[Derby]]-based eleven featuring the former [[England national football team|England international]] [[Steve Bloomer]], who was making his first footballing appearance since his return from a German prisoner-of-war camp.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19181207/017 |title=Steve Bloomer's re-appearance |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=7 December 1918 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nBy February 1919, Winship was back in the north-east and playing for [[Hartlepools United]] in the Northern Victory League. He appeared in eight matches and scored twice.<ref name=ITMC>{{cite web |url=http://www.inthemadcrowd.co.uk/ui/Person.aspx?oid=1140 |title=Wee Winship |website=In The Mad Crowd |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> When league football resumed in the 1919\u201320 season, he did not return to Arsenal, but became one of a number of former Football League players to sign for the re-formed [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] club, playing in the North-Eastern League.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000289/19190827/073 |title=North-Eastern League. Prospects of the competition |last=The Ranger |newspaper=Sunderland Daily Echo |date=27 August 1919 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Darlington==\n\n===North-Eastern League===\nIn his first season, he helped Darlington reach the second round proper (last 32) of the [[1919\u201320 FA Cup]], with a goal in the 5\u20130 elimination of [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=English Cup and League surprises |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |last=J.W.H. |date=22 December 1919 |page=11}}</ref> was \"ever dangerous\" in the goalless draw at home to First Division [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]] in the first round,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000276/19200114/153 |title=Wednesday's tie. Goalless draw wth Darlington at Feethams |last='Free Lance' |newspaper=Yorkshire Telegraph & Star |date=14 January 1920 |page=8 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and took the corner from which [[George Stevens]] opened the scoring in the [[replay (sports)|replay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000276/19200119/098 |title=Cup replay. Wednesday forwards' missed chances |last='Free Lance' |newspaper=Yorkshire Telegraph & Star |date=19 January 1920 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington faced Second Division [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] in the second round without centre forward [[Dick Healey (footballer)|Dick Healey]], and according to the ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'''s reporter, in his absence \"there were long spells in the game when Winship, who is very clever when he gets an opening, was left without the slightest chance of gaining distinction.\"<ref name=Bham>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19200202/124 |title=Birmingham v. Darlington. Darlington easily defeated |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=2 February 1920 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship missed a penalty, Birmingham won 4\u20130, and \"it must have been exasperating to the supporters of Darlington to see Winship having such an idle time on the far wing.\"<ref name=Bham/>\n\nThe club began the North-Eastern League season well. By mid-October, when Winship contributed two goals to a 5\u20133 defeat of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] Reserves, they were top of the table,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19191013/209 |title=North-Eastern League |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=13 October 1919 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but were unable to hold on to their lead, and finished two points behind [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] Reserves.<ref name=RSSSFNEL/> He was a key player in 1920\u201321:<ref name=LgeDebut/> his contributions included the only goal of the away match against Hartlepools United<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19201228/089 |title=North-Eastern League. Hartlepools United v. Darlington |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=28 January 1921 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and a penalty in the 3\u20132 win away to Middlesbrough Reserves,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19210104/253 |title=North-Eastern League |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=4 January 1921 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> as Darlington finished one point ahead of the latter to win the title.<ref name=RSSSFNEL/> They were one of four North-Eastern League teams to be elected to the newly formed [[Football League Third Division North|Northern Section of the Third Division]].<ref name=RSSSFNEL>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engnortheasthist.html |title=England \u2013 North Eastern League |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=6 December 2006 |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Football League===\n\nWithin the first minute of Darlington's first Football League match, at home to [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] on 27 August 1921, Winship made a run down the left wing and crossed towards [[Bill Hooper (English footballer)|Bill Hooper]], whose \"driving shot\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19210829/085 |title=Darlington v. Halifax Town |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=29 August 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> was \"in all probability\" the first goal scored in the new division.<ref name=LgeDebut>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:MNEB1&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FE0A3B36F0DF103&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=The day Feethams started life as a football ground |first=Chris |last=Lloyd |newspaper=The Northern Echo |location=Darlington |date=16 August 2003 |page=10 |via=Newsbank}}</ref> According to the ''Northern Echo'', Winship was the best player on the field: \"time and again he got away down the wing and sent across some lovely centres\".<ref name=LgeDebut/> He provided numerous [[assist (football)|assists]] over the season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19211119/073 |title=Lincoln's ill-luck |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=19 November 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19220103/176 |title=Darlington v. Walsall |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=3 January 1922 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> including one cross that confused [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] defenders into giving away an [[own goal]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19211017/117 |title=Darlington v. Wrexham |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=17 October 1921 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and scored goals as well, including two in a 7\u20133 defeat of [[Durham City A.F.C.|Durham City]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19211024/165 |title=Durham City v. Darlington: heavy scoring |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 October 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> as Darlington finished in second place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fchd.info/DARLINGT.HTM |title=Darlington |website=Football Club History Database |publisher=Richard Rundle |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Darlington performed rather less well in 1922\u201323, Winship remained in the thick of the action. Against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], he scored his side's only goal, struck the crossbar from distance, and was fouled for a penalty, but [[George Malcolm (footballer)|George Malcolm]]'s kick was saved.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19230103/257 |title=Drawn game at Darlington |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=3 January 1923 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The following week, he was again fouled for a penalty, and this time [[Hughie Dickson]]'s kick produced the only goal of the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19230108/101 |title=Darlington v. Stalybridge Celtic |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=8 January 1923 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In March 1923, after he scored twice against [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford]], the ''[[Derby Daily Telegraph]]'' described him as \"quite the most consistent forward in Darlington's weak attack\" whom \"no inducement has yet proved sufficient\" to persuade to leave.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19230303/026 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=3 March 1923 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Arsenal had retained his registration, and listed him for transfer at a fee of \u00a3300, a not inconsiderable sum for a man of nearly 33.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000321/19230312/035 |title=The Football League. Benefit matches and transfers sanctioned |newspaper=Nottingham Evening Post |date=12 March 1923 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the next season, Winship was awarded a benefit, in recognition of his five years' service as \"one of the most popular players ever connected with the [[River Skerne|Skerneside]] club\";<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000541/19240126/230 |title=Sports items |newspaper=Derbyshire Times |date=26 January 1924 |page=9 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> he could not play in the match, against a Middlesbrough eleven, because of injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000541/19240126/230 |title=''Untitled'' |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 April 1924 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nHe began the 1924\u201325 season in the reserves, [[Walter Creasor]] being preferred at outside left,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19240828/129 |title=World of Sport. Darlington's selections |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=28 August 1924 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but soon returned to first-team duties. In September, he \"played a great game\" in a losing cause at [[Tranmere Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19240915/125 |title=Darlington's first defeat |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=15 September 1924 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and scored with a \"swinging shot which curled into the net\" to open the scoring at home to Bradford.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19240929/133 |title=Darlington's remarkable home record |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=29 September 1924 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington soon established a lead at the top of the division which they were to hold for the rest of the season, despite their team containing numerous \"real old stagers\", players who were well known before the war.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19241227/040 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=27 December 1924 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship himself was still \"nippy\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000563/19250422/098 |title=In the world of sport. \"The Quakers'\" famous men |newspaper=Evening Telegraph |location=Dundee |date=22 April 1925 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> despite his veteran status, though not as quick as the outside-right [[Mark Hooper]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000283/19250408/127 |title=The duel with Darlington |last='Athleticus' |newspaper=Burnley Express |date=8 April 1925 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIf Darlington wanted to retain his services for their Second Division campaign, Arsenal required payment; a fee of \u00a3100 was agreed, and Winship became Darlington's player. Similarly, they had to pay \u00a3150 to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] for the transfer of full-back [[Tommy Greaves]], who had been with the club a similar length of time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19250516/117 |title=World of Sport. Another \"Quaker\" re-engaged |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=16 May 1925 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription |quote=His transfer is nominally held by The Arsenal, and is necessary before he can play in Second League Football, but negotiations have so far proceeded as to justify the directors re-engaging him.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19250520/063 |title=Close season chatter. Coaches not popular in England; Darlington happy |last=An Outside Right |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=20 May 1925 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> By October, the team were struggling at the higher level, and Winship and other of the older men were dropped in favour of \"younger and speedier players\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19251010/021 |title=Promotion points |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=10 October 1925 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington retained their Second Division status, and Winship brought his career statistics to 17 goals from 146 Football League matches with the club.<ref name=Joyce/>\n\n==Later life and career==\n\nWinship, [[David Brown (footballer, born 1887)|Davie Brown]] and [[George Stevens (Scottish footballer)|George Stevens]] were among the players not offered terms for 1926\u201327. All three were given [[free transfer (association football)|free transfers]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Signings-on |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=20 May 1926 |page=12}}</ref> and all three returned to the Third Division North with [[Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19260917/065 |title=Tomorrow's football. Crewe Alexandra v. Lincoln City |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=17 September 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship scored what was to prove his only goal for Crewe in a 3\u20133 draw with [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] in September,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19260920/086 |title=Crewe Alexandra v. Lincoln City. Lincoln's smart recovery |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=20 September 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but after the game conceded \"without hesitation\" that the goal should have been disallowed because a teammate was clearly in an [[offside (association football)|offside]] position.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19260920/050 |title=Lincoln's fight at Crewe. Offside goal saves Railwaymen |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=20 September 1926 |page=2 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The ''Derby Daily Telegraph'' wrote in December that he had been one of Crewe's most consistent players of the season thus far, that his experience counted for much, and despite his advancing years, he was still capable of being a \"very powerful and dangerous raider\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19261218/026 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=18 December 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> He scored once from 19 League matches with Crewe, and his Football League career ended at the end of that season.<ref name=Joyce/>\n\nIn December 1927, Winship returned to the North-Eastern League with his former club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19271203/100 |title=World of Sport. Winship for Wallsend |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=3 December 1927 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nHe died in Newcastle in late 1976 at the age of 86.<ref name=deathcert>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd/d/1976/4/az/001269/050 |url-access=subscription |via=Findmypast |title=England & Wales deaths 1837\u20132007 Transcription |at=Thomas Winship. Birth date: 14 Jul 1890. Death quarter: 4. Death year: 1976. District: Newcastle upon Tyne. County: Northumberland. Volume: 2. Page: 0757 |accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winship, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Darlington F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers soldiers]]\n[[Category:Hartlepool United F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Tommy Winship\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Thomas Winship<ref name=Joyce/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1890|7|14|df=y}}<ref name=Joyce/>\n|birth_place = [[Byker]], England\n|death_date  = 1976<ref name=Joyce/>\n|death_place = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=4}}<ref name=Arse>{{cite web |url=http://www.blog.woolwicharsenal.co.uk/archives/8919 |title=Tommy Winship played in the first game at Highbury |website=woolwicharsenal.co.uk |publisher= |date=26 December 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref>\n|position    = [[Outside left]]\n|youthyears1 = \u2013         |youthclubs1 = \n|years1      = \u2013         |clubs1 = Sleekburn Villa\n|years2      = \u2013         |clubs2 = [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]]\n|years3      = 1910\u20131913 |caps3 = 28  |goals3 = 3  |clubs3 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]]        \n|years4      = 1913      |caps4 = 2   |goals4 = 0  |clubs4 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]                   \n|years5      = 1913\u20131915 |caps5 = 27  |goals5 = 4  |clubs5 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal / Arsenal]]        \n|years6      = 1919      |caps6 = 8   |goals6 = 2  |clubs6 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepools United]]{{efn|Appearances and goals in the Northern Victory League.<ref name=ITMC/>}} \n|years7      = 1919\u20131926 |caps7 = 146 |goals7 = 17 |clubs7 = [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]]{{efn|Appearances and goals in [[the Football League]] only.<!-- if anyone has a reliable source for his NEL stats, please add them (with a reference) -->}}\n|years8      = 1926\u20131927 |caps8 = 19  |goals8 = 1  |clubs8 = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] \n|years9      = 1927\u201319?? |clubs9 = [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Winship''' (14 July 1890&nbsp;\u2013 1976), generally known as '''Tom''' or '''Tommy Winship''', but also referred to as '''Wee Winship''' because of his small stature,<ref name=Arse/><ref name=ITMC/> was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as an [[outside left]]. He scored 25 goals from 222 appearances in [[the Football League]] playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]] and [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] before the First World War and for [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] and [[Crewe Alexandra]] after it.<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData |location=Nottingham |page=285 |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref>\n\nWinship began his football career in the area local to his native [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] for clubs including [[North-Eastern League]] club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]], from where he joined [[Football League First Division]] club Woolwich Arsenal in late 1910. He made nearly 30 first-team appearances in a little over two years, then spent the last few weeks of the 1912\u201313 season with Fulham before returning to Arsenal, by then a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] team. In the two seasons before the Football League was suspended for the duration of the First World War, he took his appearance total to 56 matches, then returned to the north-east where he worked in shipbuilding and then served in the [[Royal Engineers]].\n\nAfter the war, he played for [[Hartlepools United]] in the Northern Victory League, then helped Darlington reach runners-up spot in the 1919\u201320 North-Eastern League and win the title the following year. Darlington were elected to the newly formed [[Football League Third Division North|Northern Section of the Third Division]] in 1921, and Winship contributed to their second-place finish in their first season and their Northern Section title in 1924\u201325. Before Winship could represent Darlington in Second Division football, they had to pay \u00a3100 to Arsenal to transfer his registration, which that club had retained. He was not a regular at the higher level, but still took his total of league appearances for Darlington to nearly 150 over five seasons. He then spent one last season in the Football League with Third Division Crewe Alexandra before winding down his career back with Wallsend.\n\n==Early life and career==\nWinship was born in the [[Byker]] area of [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], which was then part of [[Northumberland]],<ref name=Joyce/> the third child of John Winship, a brickmaker, and his wife Mary.<ref name=1891Census>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=gbc/1891/0028928017 |title=1891 England, Wales & Scotland Census Transcription Wilfred Street, Byker, Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England |via=[[Findmypast]] |url-access=subscription |at=Census reference: RG12 4214 38 24 |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> He began his football career in the local area, and it was playing for [[North-Eastern League]] club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend Park Villa]] that he earned himself a reputation as \"one of the best junior players in the North\".<ref name=BestJunior/> He attracted attention from clubs at a higher level, and in late 1910, he signed for [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]] of the [[Football League First Division]].<ref name=BestJunior>{{cite news |title=World of Sport |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=2 December 1910 |page=18}}</ref>\n\n==Woolwich Arsenal==\nWinship made his Woolwich Arsenal debut on [[Boxing Day]] 1910 against league leaders [[Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]]; United won 5\u20130.<ref name=AFCprofile>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/history/profiles/741/tommy-winship |title=Tommy Winship |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=AK>{{cite web |url=http://www.thearsenalhistory.com/stat/aftlu.htm |title=Arsenal first team line-ups |website=The Arsenal History |publisher=Andy Kelly |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> A fortnight later, the ''[[Sheffield Daily Telegraph]]'' described the team as having \"a couple of capable, enterprising wingers, though Winship was a bit late waking up\" in a 3\u20132 defeat to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000250/19110109/050 |title=Best of five. United win a unexpectedly close match |last='Athleo' |newspaper=Sheffield Daily Telegraph |date=9 January 1911 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> He had a run of seven league matches, counting the visit of [[Aston Villa]] abandoned because of bad light, before losing his place to the established first-choice winger [[David Greenaway]].<ref name=AK/>\n\nHe came into the team for the Christmas 1911 fixtures against London rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur]]: a heavy defeat at Tottenham preceded a 3\u20131 win in muddy conditions at the [[Manor Ground (Plumstead)|Manor Ground]], in which Winship&nbsp;\u2013 described by the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' as having the ideal build for work in mud&nbsp;\u2013 played a major role. He crossed the ball to give [[Charles Lewis (footballer)|Charles Lewis]] an opening goal from close range, Arsenal's second goal followed the free kick awarded when he was fouled, and he scored \"an exceptionally clever\" third himself.<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal avenged. 'Spurs defeated on a morass at Plumstead |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=27 December 1911 |page=6}}</ref> It was his first competitive goal for Arsenal, and his second came a few days later in a 2\u20132 draw with Aston Villa.<ref name=AK/> In mid-March, he was carried off the field with what the ''[[Daily Express]]'' called a nasty leg injury in a match against [[West Bromwich Albion]] and played no further part in the first team that season.<ref name=AK/><ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal checked. Albion demonstrate marked superiority |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=18 March 1912 |page=8}}</ref> Winship married Rose Kilpatrick in Newcastle later that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://durhamlightinfantry.webs.com/thosewhoproudlyserved.htm |title=Those Who Proudly Served: 4449147 Pte Anthony Corkhill 2 DLI |website=Durham Light Infantry 1920\u20131946 |accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd/m/1912/3/az/001157/049 |url-access=subscription |via=Findmypast |title=England & Wales marriages 1837\u20132008 Transcription |at=Thomas Winship. Marriage quarter: 3. Marriage year: 1912. Spouse's last name: Kilpatrick. District: Newcastle upon Tyne. County: Northumberland. Volume: 10B. Page: 206 |accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1912\u201313, he played 14 league matches, scoring once,<ref name=AK/> before signing for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] just ahead of the March transfer deadline.<ref>{{cite news |title=Important transfer |last=Mancunian |newspaper=Manchester Courier |date=14 March 1913 |page=2 |via=Findmypast }}</ref> Arsenal were [[relegated]] to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] at the end of that season, and promptly re-signed Winship, who had played just twice for Fulham. Questions were asked as to the probity of the transfer&nbsp;\u2013 Sir [[Henry Norris (businessman)|Henry Norris]] had been and remained a director of Fulham before becoming major shareholder in and chairman of Arsenal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blog.woolwicharsenal.co.uk/archives/10239 |title=When Arsenal died one man stepped up and rescued the club. The story of May 1910 |first1=Tony |last1=Attwood |first2=Andy |last2=Kelly |first3=Mark |last3=Andrews |website=The History of Arsenal |publisher=AISA Arsenal History Society |date=13 May 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2015 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 but [[the Football League]]'s management committee ratified his return.<ref>{{cite news |title=English Football League settle transfers and players' claims |newspaper=Dundee Courier |date=14 June 1913 |page=7 |quote=An explanation as to the transfer of Winship from Fulham to Woolwich, about which there had been some doubt, was accepted. |via=Findmypast }}</ref> Woolwich Arsenal began the 1913\u201314 season in their new stadium with the visit of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 6 September. The visitors took a one-goal lead, and [[George Jobey]] scored the equaliser&nbsp;\u2013 Arsenal's first goal at what would become generally known as [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]]&nbsp;\u2013 with a header from Winship's corner; Arsenal won 2\u20131.<ref name=Highbury>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Smith |title=Highbury: The Story of Arsenal Stadium |chapterurl=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1WkMvY5vYL8C&pg=PT91&lpg=PT91 |chapter=Fifteen: Landmark Games |publisher=Mainstream |location=Edinburgh |date=2005 |isbn=1 84596 104 8}}</ref>\n\nLater that season, the club dropped the \"Woolwich\" from its name and began to call itself The Arsenal. Winship scored the first goal for the club under that new name to equalise against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]: Jobey sent a free kick across goal \"and Winship, running in, crashed the ball into the net with a magnificent first-time drive\".<ref>{{cite news |title=City's creditable draw |newspaper=Western Daily Press |location=Bristol |date=6 April 1914 |page=9 |via=Findmypast }}</ref> He also appeared to score a winner, but the \"goal\" was disallowed; the game was temporarily halted while the police dealt with displeasure among the home support.<ref name=Highbury/> Winship never established himself as a first-team regular; his Arsenal career ended when the Football League was suspended for the duration of the First World War, at which point he had played 56 first-team matches.<ref name=AFCprofile/>\n\n==First World War==\nWinship returned to [[Tyneside]] to work in shipbuilding,<ref name=AFCprofile/> but kept up his footballing skills when he could. In October 1915, together with a number of other former professional players, he took part in a [[benefit match]] for the family of a local footballer killed on active service.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000569/19151009/068 |title=Charity match in Newcastle |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Journal |date=9 October 1915 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The following year he guested for [[Ashington A.F.C.|Ashington]] in Easter fixtures against [[Blyth Spartans]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000569/19160322/088 |title=Association football |newspaper=Newcastle Daily Journal |date=22 March 1916 |page=9 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and was expected to appear for [[Leeds City F.C.|Leeds City]] at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in the Midland Section of the wartime league competition, but did not.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19160909/281 |title=Football. Notes on to-day's matches |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=9 September 1916 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19160911/210 |title=Football. Association |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=11 September 1916 |page=10 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> By November 1917, listed as [[Sapper#Commonwealth of Nations|Sapper]] Winship, he was guesting for Grimsby for their visit to [[Leicester Fosse]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19171124/275 |title=Football. Notes on to-day's matches |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 November 1917 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and in September 1918, he was a member of the [[Royal Engineers]] Reserve Battalion team that won a [[five-a-side]] tournament in aid of the Football National War Fund.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000400/19180907/190 |title=Sports and pastimes |newspaper=Grantham Journal |date=7 September 1918 |page=7 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In December 1918, after the war ended but before his demobilisation, [[Lance-Corporal]] Winship played for the 1st Royal Engineers stationed at [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]], [[Nottinghamshire]], against a [[Derby]]-based eleven featuring the former [[England national football team|England international]] [[Steve Bloomer]], who was making his first footballing appearance since his return from a German prisoner-of-war camp.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19181207/017 |title=Steve Bloomer's re-appearance |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=7 December 1918 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nBy February 1919, Winship was back in the north-east and playing for [[Hartlepools United]] in the Northern Victory League. He appeared in eight matches and scored twice.<ref name=ITMC>{{cite web |url=http://www.inthemadcrowd.co.uk/ui/Person.aspx?oid=1140 |title=Wee Winship |website=In The Mad Crowd |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> When league football resumed in the 1919\u201320 season, he did not return to Arsenal, but became one of a number of former Football League players to sign for the re-formed [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] club, playing in the North-Eastern League.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000289/19190827/073 |title=North-Eastern League. Prospects of the competition |last=The Ranger |newspaper=Sunderland Daily Echo |date=27 August 1919 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Darlington==\n\n===North-Eastern League===\nIn his first season, he helped Darlington reach the second round proper (last 32) of the [[1919\u201320 FA Cup]], with a goal in the 5\u20130 elimination of [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=English Cup and League surprises |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |last=J.W.H. |date=22 December 1919 |page=11}}</ref> was \"ever dangerous\" in the goalless draw at home to First Division [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]] in the first round,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000276/19200114/153 |title=Wednesday's tie. Goalless draw wth Darlington at Feethams |last='Free Lance' |newspaper=Yorkshire Telegraph & Star |date=14 January 1920 |page=8 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and took the corner from which [[George Stevens]] opened the scoring in the [[replay (sports)|replay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000276/19200119/098 |title=Cup replay. Wednesday forwards' missed chances |last='Free Lance' |newspaper=Yorkshire Telegraph & Star |date=19 January 1920 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington faced Second Division [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham]] in the second round without centre forward [[Dick Healey (footballer)|Dick Healey]], and according to the ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'''s reporter, in his absence \"there were long spells in the game when Winship, who is very clever when he gets an opening, was left without the slightest chance of gaining distinction.\"<ref name=Bham>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19200202/124 |title=Birmingham v. Darlington. Darlington easily defeated |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=2 February 1920 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship missed a penalty, Birmingham won 4\u20130, and \"it must have been exasperating to the supporters of Darlington to see Winship having such an idle time on the far wing.\"<ref name=Bham/>\n\nThe club began the North-Eastern League season well. By mid-October, when Winship contributed two goals to a 5\u20133 defeat of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] Reserves, they were top of the table,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19191013/209 |title=North-Eastern League |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=13 October 1919 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but were unable to hold on to their lead, and finished two points behind [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] Reserves.<ref name=RSSSFNEL/> He was a key player in 1920\u201321:<ref name=LgeDebut/> his contributions included the only goal of the away match against Hartlepools United<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19201228/089 |title=North-Eastern League. Hartlepools United v. Darlington |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=28 January 1921 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and a penalty in the 3\u20132 win away to Middlesbrough Reserves,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19210104/253 |title=North-Eastern League |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=4 January 1921 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> as Darlington finished one point ahead of the latter to win the title.<ref name=RSSSFNEL/> They were one of four North-Eastern League teams to be elected to the newly formed [[Football League Third Division North|Northern Section of the Third Division]].<ref name=RSSSFNEL>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engnortheasthist.html |title=England \u2013 North Eastern League |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=6 December 2006 |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Football League===\n\nWithin the first minute of Darlington's first Football League match, at home to [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]] on 27 August 1921, Winship made a run down the left wing and crossed towards [[Bill Hooper (English footballer)|Bill Hooper]], whose \"driving shot\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19210829/085 |title=Darlington v. Halifax Town |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=29 August 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> was \"in all probability\" the first goal scored in the new division.<ref name=LgeDebut>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:MNEB1&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FE0A3B36F0DF103&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815|title=The day Feethams started life as a football ground |first=Chris |last=Lloyd |newspaper=The Northern Echo |location=Darlington |date=16 August 2003 |page=10 |via=Newsbank}}</ref> According to the ''Northern Echo'', Winship was the best player on the field: \"time and again he got away down the wing and sent across some lovely centres\".<ref name=LgeDebut/> He provided numerous [[assist (football)|assists]] over the season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19211119/073 |title=Lincoln's ill-luck |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=19 November 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19220103/176 |title=Darlington v. Walsall |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=3 January 1922 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> including one cross that confused [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] defenders into giving away an [[own goal]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19211017/117 |title=Darlington v. Wrexham |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=17 October 1921 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and scored goals as well, including two in a 7\u20133 defeat of [[Durham City A.F.C.|Durham City]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19211024/165 |title=Durham City v. Darlington: heavy scoring |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 October 1921 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> as Darlington finished in second place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fchd.info/DARLINGT.HTM |title=Darlington |website=Football Club History Database |publisher=Richard Rundle |accessdate=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Darlington performed rather less well in 1922\u201323, Winship remained in the thick of the action. Against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], he scored his side's only goal, struck the crossbar from distance, and was fouled for a penalty, but [[George Malcolm (footballer)|George Malcolm]]'s kick was saved.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19230103/257 |title=Drawn game at Darlington |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=3 January 1923 |page=12 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The following week, he was again fouled for a penalty, and this time [[Hughie Dickson]]'s kick produced the only goal of the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19230108/101 |title=Darlington v. Stalybridge Celtic |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=8 January 1923 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In March 1923, after he scored twice against [[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford]], the ''[[Derby Daily Telegraph]]'' described him as \"quite the most consistent forward in Darlington's weak attack\" whom \"no inducement has yet proved sufficient\" to persuade to leave.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19230303/026 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=3 March 1923 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Arsenal had retained his registration, and listed him for transfer at a fee of \u00a3300, a not inconsiderable sum for a man of nearly 33.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000321/19230312/035 |title=The Football League. Benefit matches and transfers sanctioned |newspaper=Nottingham Evening Post |date=12 March 1923 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the next season, Winship was awarded a benefit, in recognition of his five years' service as \"one of the most popular players ever connected with the [[River Skerne|Skerneside]] club\";<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000541/19240126/230 |title=Sports items |newspaper=Derbyshire Times |date=26 January 1924 |page=9 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> he could not play in the match, against a Middlesbrough eleven, because of injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000541/19240126/230 |title=''Untitled'' |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=24 April 1924 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nHe began the 1924\u201325 season in the reserves, [[Walter Creasor]] being preferred at outside left,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19240828/129 |title=World of Sport. Darlington's selections |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=28 August 1924 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but soon returned to first-team duties. In September, he \"played a great game\" in a losing cause at [[Tranmere Rovers]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19240915/125 |title=Darlington's first defeat |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=15 September 1924 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> and scored with a \"swinging shot which curled into the net\" to open the scoring at home to Bradford.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19240929/133 |title=Darlington's remarkable home record |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=29 September 1924 |page=3 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington soon established a lead at the top of the division which they were to hold for the rest of the season, despite their team containing numerous \"real old stagers\", players who were well known before the war.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19241227/040 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=27 December 1924 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship himself was still \"nippy\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000563/19250422/098 |title=In the world of sport. \"The Quakers'\" famous men |newspaper=Evening Telegraph |location=Dundee |date=22 April 1925 |page=11 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> despite his veteran status, though not as quick as the outside-right [[Mark Hooper]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000283/19250408/127 |title=The duel with Darlington |last='Athleticus' |newspaper=Burnley Express |date=8 April 1925 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIf Darlington wanted to retain his services for their Second Division campaign, Arsenal required payment; a fee of \u00a3100 was agreed, and Winship became Darlington's player. Similarly, they had to pay \u00a3150 to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] for the transfer of full-back [[Tommy Greaves]], who had been with the club a similar length of time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19250516/117 |title=World of Sport. Another \"Quaker\" re-engaged |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=16 May 1925 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription |quote=His transfer is nominally held by The Arsenal, and is necessary before he can play in Second League Football, but negotiations have so far proceeded as to justify the directors re-engaging him.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19250520/063 |title=Close season chatter. Coaches not popular in England; Darlington happy |last=An Outside Right |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=20 May 1925 |page=6 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> By October, the team were struggling at the higher level, and Winship and other of the older men were dropped in favour of \"younger and speedier players\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19251010/021 |title=Promotion points |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=10 October 1925 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Darlington retained their Second Division status, and Winship brought his career statistics to 17 goals from 146 Football League matches with the club.<ref name=Joyce/>\n\n==Later life and career==\n\nWinship, [[David Brown (footballer, born 1887)|Davie Brown]] and [[George Stevens (Scottish footballer)|George Stevens]] were among the players not offered terms for 1926\u201327. All three were given [[free transfer (association football)|free transfers]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Signings-on |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=20 May 1926 |page=12}}</ref> and all three returned to the Third Division North with [[Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19260917/065 |title=Tomorrow's football. Crewe Alexandra v. Lincoln City |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=17 September 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Winship scored what was to prove his only goal for Crewe in a 3\u20133 draw with [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] in September,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000687/19260920/086 |title=Crewe Alexandra v. Lincoln City. Lincoln's smart recovery |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=20 September 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> but after the game conceded \"without hesitation\" that the goal should have been disallowed because a teammate was clearly in an [[offside (association football)|offside]] position.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000332/19260920/050 |title=Lincoln's fight at Crewe. Offside goal saves Railwaymen |newspaper=Lincolnshire Echo |date=20 September 1926 |page=2 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> The ''Derby Daily Telegraph'' wrote in December that he had been one of Crewe's most consistent players of the season thus far, that his experience counted for much, and despite his advancing years, he was still capable of being a \"very powerful and dangerous raider\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000327/19261218/026 |title=North and South |newspaper=Derby Daily Telegraph |date=18 December 1926 |page=4 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref> He scored once from 19 League matches with Crewe, and his Football League career ended at the end of that season.<ref name=Joyce/>\n\nIn December 1927, Winship returned to the North-Eastern League with his former club [[Wallsend F.C.|Wallsend]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/bna/viewarticle?id=bl/0000378/19271203/100 |title=World of Sport. Winship for Wallsend |newspaper=Northern Daily Mail |location=West Hartlepool |date=3 December 1927 |page=5 |via=Findmypast |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nHe died in Newcastle in late 1976 at the age of 86.<ref name=deathcert>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/record?id=bmd/d/1976/4/az/001269/050 |url-access=subscription |via=Findmypast |title=England & Wales deaths 1837\u20132007 Transcription |at=Thomas Winship. Birth date: 14 Jul 1890. Death quarter: 4. Death year: 1976. District: Newcastle upon Tyne. County: Northumberland. Volume: 2. Page: 0757 |accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winship, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Darlington F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers soldiers]]\n[[Category:Hartlepool United F.C. players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Winship"}
{"title_page": "Hongshanornis", "text_new": "{{italic title}}{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], {{fossilrange|124.6|122}}\n| image = Fossil specimen (DNHM D2945 6) of Hongshanornis longicresta.jpg\n| image_caption = Fossil specimen\n| display_parents = 3\n| genus = Hongshanornis \n| species = longicresta\n| parent_authority = Zhou & Zhang, 2005\n| authority = Zhou & Zhang, 2005\n}}\n\n'''''Hongshanornis''''' is a [[genus]] of [[Ornithuromorpha|ornithuromorph]] birds known from early [[Cretaceous]] lake deposits of the [[Yixian Formation]], [[Inner Mongolia]], [[China]]. The holotype specimen, recovered in 2005, is currently held by the Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology in Beijing. It was found in the Jianshangou fossil beds, dated to 124.6 million years ago.<ref name=\"zhou2006\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/gj.1045 | last1 = Zhou | first1 = Z. | year = 2006 | title = Evolutionary radiation of the Jehol Biota: chronological and ecological perspectives | url = | journal = Geological Journal | volume = 41 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 377\u2013393 }}</ref> Three additional specimens have been reported, though only one of those has been definitively identified as belonging to ''Hongshanornis''.<ref name=hongshan2014>{{Cite journal | last1 = Chiappe | first1 = L. M. | last2 = Zhao | first2 = B. | last3 = o\u2019Connor | first3 = J. K. | last4 = Chunling | first4 = G. | last5 = Wang | first5 = X. | last6 = Habib | first6 = M. | last7 = Marugan-Lobon | first7 = J. | last8 = Meng | first8 = Q. | last9 = Cheng | first9 = X. | title = A new specimen of the Early Cretaceous bird ''Hongshanornis longicresta'': Insights into the aerodynamics and diet of a basal ornithuromorph | doi = 10.7717/peerj.234 | journal = PeerJ | volume = 2 | page = e234 | year = 2014 | pmid =  24482756| pmc = 3898307}}</ref> This latter specimen was found in the Dawangzhangzi fossil beds, which are about 122 million years old.<ref name=\"zhou2006\"/>\n\n''Hongshanornis'' is a member of the group [[Hongshanornithidae]], to which it lent its name. It is closely related to ''[[Longicrusavis]]'', which existed alongside ''Hongshanornis'' in the Dawangzhangzi ecosystem, and is very similar to the later ''[[Parahongshanornis]]'' from the [[Jiufotang Formation]].<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n==Description==\n''Hongshanornis longicresta'' was a small species, especially compared to other early ornithuromorphs (birds with a modern tail anatomy), about the size of a [[Turdus|thrush]], and adult specimens are estimated to have weighed about {{convert|50|g|oz}} in life, with a wingspan of about {{convert|320|mm|ft}}.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n[[File:DNHM D2945 6 interpretive.png|thumb|left|upright|Interpretive drawing of specimen DNHM D2946, showing location of gizzard stones]]\nThe skull in all known specimens is poorly preserved, but in general appears to have had a narrow snout compared to the closely related ''[[Longicrusavis]]''.<ref name=hongshan2014/> The teeth were very small and are poorly preserved in all known specimens. At first, this led scientists to conclude that the teeth were absent in both the upper and lower jaws, probably replaced with a beak. However, later study of the type specimen showed that tooth sockets were present in the preserved parts of the jaw, and comparison with related forms showed that it did have teeth.<ref name=OGC10>{{cite journal |last=O'Connor |first=J.K. |author2=Gao, K.-Q. |author3= Chiappe, L.M.  |year=2010 |title=A new ornithuromorph (Aves: Ornithothoraces) bird from the Jehol Group indicative of higher-level diversity |journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=311\u2013321 |doi=10.1080/02724631003617498 |url=http://pdfserve.informaworld.com/462280__920289337.pdf}}</ref> The discovery of a more well preserved specimen confirmed the presence of teeth in at least the [[maxilla]] (middle of the upper jaw) and [[dentary]] (lower jaw). The snout appears to have lacked feathers, though whether it was only covered in skin or some parts bore a [[beak]] is currently unknown. The describers of ''Hongshanornis'' noted a unique bone in the end of the lower jaw which they equated with the beak-bearing \"[[predentary]] bone\" similar to the one found in [[ornithischia]]n dinosaurs. Such bones have also been found in more advanced birds like ''[[Hesperornis]]''.<ref name=\"Zhou & Zhang 2005\">{{cite journal | pmid = 16344487 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0507106102 | volume=102 | title=Discovery of an ornithurine bird and its implication for Early Cretaceous avian radiation | pmc=1323170 | date=December 2005 | journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. | pages=18998\u20139002 | last1 = Zhou | first1 = Z | last2 = Zhang | first2 = F}}  [http://www.pnas.org/content/102/52/18998/suppl/DC1 Supporting Information]</ref> However, other scientists have pointed out that the \"predentary\" (or, technically, ''mandibular symphysial ossification'') of ''Hongshanornis'' lacks the characteristic pits and grooves associated with the beak in early beaked birds like ''[[Archaeorhynchus]]'', and that the presence or absence of any beak is unclear.<ref name=OGC10/><ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\nThe original describers of ''Hongshanornis'' noted the apparent presence of a large feathered crest on the head,<ref name=\"Zhou & Zhang 2005\"/> though the feather traces are extremely poor quality and it may be an artifact of preservation.<ref name=OGC10/> A second specimen from different fossil beds did not have long feathers on the head, but rather showed feathers which became shorter closer to the snout.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\nThe wings were long and broad, but tapered and pointed at the tips. The first few primary flight feathers were much shorter than the rest. The total wing area was 0.016 square meters. The wing digits bore small claws, with the claw on the first finger (the alular digit) much larger than that of the second finger (major digit).<ref name=hongshan2014/> ''Hongshanornis'' is characterized by very long legs, with the lower leg (''tibiotarsus'') more than one and a half times longer than the upper leg (''femur''). The toes were long and thin, with small claws. The first toe (''hallux'') was very small, and the second toe was much shorter than the fourth. The third toe was longest.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n[[File:Hongshanornis.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Restoration]]\nThe bones of the tail have not been preserved in any known specimen, but comparison with related species suggest it was short with a small, [[plowshare]]-shaped [[pygostyle]] bone, to which the tail feathers anchored. A mass of muscles, called the rectorial bulb, probably was present to control the fanning of the trail feathers. The tail feathers were long, with symmetrical vanes. There were at least 10 tail feathers (''rectrices''), more than in other primitive fan-tailed birds. The overall shape of the tail was rounded and wedge-shaped when viewed from above; due to the symmetrical feathers, the sides of the tail were probably not held fully fanned into the wind but swept back, forming a partially fanned wedge, as in some modern birds like [[accipiter]]s, [[tyrant flycatcher]]s and [[sunbittern]]s.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n==Biology==\n===Diet and ecology===\n[[File:DNHM D2945 6 skull.png|thumb|right|Skull of specimen DNHM D2945, highlighting teeth]]\nDue to the assumption of toothlessness, hongshanornithids were originally interpreted as having a very specialized diet and ecology, perhaps as waders or shorebirds due to their slim snouts and long legs. However, the confirmation that they did in fact have teeth in both jaws has led to a re-interpretation of their ecological niche. Though still considered probably wading birds, they probably had a more generalized diet than previously assumed, with the different snout shapes present in different members of the group indicating niche portioning within a general wading ecology (''Hongshanornis'' lived alongside the closely related ''Longicrusavis'', and both were very similar to each other except for the shape of the snout).<ref name=hongshan2014/> One specimen of ''Hongshanornis'' preserved several gizzard stones ([[gastrolith]]s) of various sizes, which is usually an indication of an herbivorous diet.<ref name=hongshan2014/> Another specimen originally assigned to the genus ''Hongshanornis'' preserved fossilized seeds in the [[Crop (anatomy)|crop]];<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Xiaoting Zheng |author2=Larry D. Martin |author3=Zhonghe Zhou |author4=David A. Burnham |author5=Fucheng Zhang |author6=Desui Miao |year=2011 |title=Fossil evidence of avian crops from the Early Cretaceous of China |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=108 |issue=38 |pages=15904\u201315907 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1112694108 |pmc=3179114 |pmid=21896733}}</ref><ref name=hongshan2014/> however, this specimen was subsequently transferred to a distinct taxon ''[[Eogranivora]] edentulata''.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Xiaoting Zheng |author2=Jingmai K. O'Connor |author3=Xiaoli Wang |author4=Yan Wang |author5=Zhonghe Zhou |year=2018 |title=Reinterpretation of a previously described Jehol bird clarifies early trophic evolution in the Ornithuromorpha |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volume=285 |issue=1871 |pages=20172494 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2017.2494 |pmc=5805944 |pmid=29386367}}</ref>\n\n===Flight===\n[[File:Hongshanornis wingspan.png|thumb|left|Diagram of the wing and tail profile]]\nThe wings of ''H. longicresta'' were broad and tapered, with an average wing area and wing loading compared to modern birds in the same size range.<ref name=hongshan2014/> The presence or absence of slotting at the wing tips cannot be determined with known specimens, but modern birds with similar size and wing shape tend to lack wing slotting. The absence of wing slotting would suggest that ''Hongshanornis'' tended to fly mainly at relatively high speeds. Given the overall wing shape and comparison to modern birds, ''Hongshanornis'' probably flapped continuously when flying at lower speeds, and switched to bounding flight (rapid flapping alternating with periods of ballistic forward motion with the wings partly folded) at higher speeds. Overall, the wing and tail anatomy, and therefore probably flight style, of ''Hongshanornis'' was similar to many medium-sized [[passerine]] birds.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n{{clearboth}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palaeocritti.com/by-group/aves/ornithuromorpha/hongshanornis Information and photograph of the type specimen, Palaeocritti]\n\n{{portal|Paleontology}}\n{{Paraves|B.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3029892}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous birds of Asia]]\n[[Category:Yixian fauna]]\n[[Category:Basal Ornithurae]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2005]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], {{fossilrange|124.6|122}}\n| image = Fossil specimen (DNHM D2945 6) of Hongshanornis longicresta.jpg\n| image_caption = Fossil specimen\n| display_parents = 3\n| genus = Hongshanornis \n| species = longicresta\n| parent_authority = Zhou & Zhang, 2005\n| authority = Zhou & Zhang, 2005\n}}\n\n'''''Hongshanornis''''' is a [[genus]] of [[Ornithuromorpha|ornithuromorph]] birds known from early [[Cretaceous]] lake deposits of the [[Yixian Formation]], [[Inner Mongolia]], [[China]]. The holotype specimen, recovered in 2005, is currently held by the Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology in Beijing. It was found in the Jianshangou fossil beds, dated to 124.6 million years ago.<ref name=\"zhou2006\">{{cite journal | doi = 10.1002/gj.1045 | last1 = Zhou | first1 = Z. | year = 2006 | title = Evolutionary radiation of the Jehol Biota: chronological and ecological perspectives | url = | journal = Geological Journal | volume = 41 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 377\u2013393 }}</ref> Three additional specimens have been reported, though only one of those has been definitively identified as belonging to ''Hongshanornis''.<ref name=hongshan2014>{{Cite journal | last1 = Chiappe | first1 = L. M. | last2 = Zhao | first2 = B. | last3 = o\u2019Connor | first3 = J. K. | last4 = Chunling | first4 = G. | last5 = Wang | first5 = X. | last6 = Habib | first6 = M. | last7 = Marugan-Lobon | first7 = J. | last8 = Meng | first8 = Q. | last9 = Cheng | first9 = X. | title = A new specimen of the Early Cretaceous bird ''Hongshanornis longicresta'': Insights into the aerodynamics and diet of a basal ornithuromorph | doi = 10.7717/peerj.234 | journal = PeerJ | volume = 2 | page = e234 | year = 2014 | pmid =  24482756| pmc = 3898307}}</ref> This latter specimen was found in the Dawangzhangzi fossil beds, which are about 122 million years old.<ref name=\"zhou2006\"/>\n\n''Hongshanornis'' is a member of the group [[Hongshanornithidae]], to which it lent its name. It is closely related to ''[[Longicrusavis]]'', which existed alongside ''Hongshanornis'' in the Dawangzhangzi ecosystem, and is very similar to the later ''[[Parahongshanornis]]'' from the [[Jiufotang Formation]].<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n==Description==\n''Hongshanornis longicresta'' was a small species, especially compared to other early ornithuromorphs (birds with a modern tail anatomy), about the size of a [[Turdus|thrush]], and adult specimens are estimated to have weighed about {{convert|50|g|oz}} in life, with a wingspan of about {{convert|320|mm|ft}}.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n[[File:DNHM D2945 6 interpretive.png|thumb|left|upright|Interpretive drawing of specimen DNHM D2946, showing location of gizzard stones]]\nThe skull in all known specimens is poorly preserved, but in general appears to have had a narrow snout compared to the closely related ''[[Longicrusavis]]''.<ref name=hongshan2014/> The teeth were very small and are poorly preserved in all known specimens. At first, this led scientists to conclude that the teeth were absent in both the upper and lower jaws, probably replaced with a beak. However, later study of the type specimen showed that tooth sockets were present in the preserved parts of the jaw, and comparison with related forms showed that it did have teeth.<ref name=OGC10>{{cite journal |last=O'Connor |first=J.K. |author2=Gao, K.-Q. |author3= Chiappe, L.M.  |year=2010 |title=A new ornithuromorph (Aves: Ornithothoraces) bird from the Jehol Group indicative of higher-level diversity |journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology |volume=30 |issue=2 |pages=311\u2013321 |doi=10.1080/02724631003617498 |url=http://pdfserve.informaworld.com/462280__920289337.pdf}}</ref> The discovery of a more well preserved specimen confirmed the presence of teeth in at least the [[maxilla]] (middle of the upper jaw) and [[dentary]] (lower jaw). The snout appears to have lacked feathers, though whether it was only covered in skin or some parts bore a [[beak]] is currently unknown. The describers of ''Hongshanornis'' noted a unique bone in the end of the lower jaw which they equated with the beak-bearing \"[[predentary]] bone\" similar to the one found in [[ornithischia]]n dinosaurs. Such bones have also been found in more advanced birds like ''[[Hesperornis]]''.<ref name=\"Zhou & Zhang 2005\">{{aut|Zhou, Z. & Zhang, F.}} (2005): Discovery of an ornithurine bird and its implication for Early Cretaceous avian radiation. ''[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]]'' '''102'''(52): 18998-19002. {{DOI|10.1073/pnas.0507106102}} {{PMID|16344487}} - Fulltext: [http://www.pnas.org/content/102/52/18998.full HTML], [http://www.pnas.org/content/102/52/18998.full.pdf PDF], [http://www.pnas.org/content/102/52/18998/suppl/DC1 Supporting Information]</ref> However, other scientists have pointed out that the \"predentary\" (or, technically, ''mandibular symphysial ossification'') of ''Hongshanornis'' lacks the characteristic pits and grooves associated with the beak in early beaked birds like ''[[Archaeorhynchus]]'', and that the presence or absence of any beak is unclear.<ref name=OGC10/><ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\nThe original describers of ''Hongshanornis'' noted the apparent presence of a large feathered crest on the head,<ref name=\"Zhou & Zhang 2005\"/> though the feather traces are extremely poor quality and it may be an artifact of preservation.<ref name=OGC10/> A second specimen from different fossil beds did not have long feathers on the head, but rather showed feathers which became shorter closer to the snout.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\nThe wings were long and broad, but tapered and pointed at the tips. The first few primary flight feathers were much shorter than the rest. The total wing area was 0.016 square meters. The wing digits bore small claws, with the claw on the first finger (the alular digit) much larger than that of the second finger (major digit).<ref name=hongshan2014/> ''Hongshanornis'' is characterized by very long legs, with the lower leg (''tibiotarsus'') more than one and a half times longer than the upper leg (''femur''). The toes were long and thin, with small claws. The first toe (''hallux'') was very small, and the second toe was much shorter than the fourth. The third toe was longest.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n[[File:Hongshanornis.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Restoration]]\nThe bones of the tail have not been preserved in any known specimen, but comparison with related species suggest it was short with a small, [[plowshare]]-shaped [[pygostyle]] bone, to which the tail feathers anchored. A mass of muscles, called the rectorial bulb, probably was present to control the fanning of the trail feathers. The tail feathers were long, with symmetrical vanes. There were at least 10 tail feathers (''rectrices''), more than in other primitive fan-tailed birds. The overall shape of the tail was rounded and wedge-shaped when viewed from above; due to the symmetrical feathers, the sides of the tail were probably not held fully fanned into the wind but swept back, forming a partially fanned wedge, as in some modern birds like [[accipiter]]s, [[tyrant flycatcher]]s and [[sunbittern]]s.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n==Biology==\n===Diet and ecology===\n[[File:DNHM D2945 6 skull.png|thumb|right|Skull of specimen DNHM D2945, highlighting teeth]]\nDue to the assumption of toothlessness, hongshanornithids were originally interpreted as having a very specialized diet and ecology, perhaps as waders or shorebirds due to their slim snouts and long legs. However, the confirmation that they did in fact have teeth in both jaws has led to a re-interpretation of their ecological niche. Though still considered probably wading birds, they probably had a more generalized diet than previously assumed, with the different snout shapes present in different members of the group indicating niche portioning within a general wading ecology (''Hongshanornis'' lived alongside the closely related ''Longicrusavis'', and both were very similar to each other except for the shape of the snout).<ref name=hongshan2014/> One specimen of ''Hongshanornis'' preserved several gizzard stones ([[gastrolith]]s) of various sizes, which is usually an indication of an herbivorous diet.<ref name=hongshan2014/> Another specimen originally assigned to the genus ''Hongshanornis'' preserved fossilized seeds in the [[Crop (anatomy)|crop]];<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Xiaoting Zheng |author2=Larry D. Martin |author3=Zhonghe Zhou |author4=David A. Burnham |author5=Fucheng Zhang |author6=Desui Miao |year=2011 |title=Fossil evidence of avian crops from the Early Cretaceous of China |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=108 |issue=38 |pages=15904\u201315907 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1112694108 |pmc=3179114 |pmid=21896733}}</ref><ref name=hongshan2014/> however, this specimen was subsequently transferred to a distinct taxon ''[[Eogranivora]] edentulata''.<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Xiaoting Zheng |author2=Jingmai K. O'Connor |author3=Xiaoli Wang |author4=Yan Wang |author5=Zhonghe Zhou |year=2018 |title=Reinterpretation of a previously described Jehol bird clarifies early trophic evolution in the Ornithuromorpha |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volume=285 |issue=1871 |pages=20172494 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2017.2494 |pmc=5805944 |pmid=29386367}}</ref>\n\n===Flight===\n[[File:Hongshanornis wingspan.png|thumb|left|Diagram of the wing and tail profile]]\nThe wings of ''H. longicresta'' were broad and tapered, with an average wing area and wing loading compared to modern birds in the same size range.<ref name=hongshan2014/> The presence or absence of slotting at the wing tips cannot be determined with known specimens, but modern birds with similar size and wing shape tend to lack wing slotting. The absence of wing slotting would suggest that ''Hongshanornis'' tended to fly mainly at relatively high speeds. Given the overall wing shape and comparison to modern birds, ''Hongshanornis'' probably flapped continuously when flying at lower speeds, and switched to bounding flight (rapid flapping alternating with periods of ballistic forward motion with the wings partly folded) at higher speeds. Overall, the wing and tail anatomy, and therefore probably flight style, of ''Hongshanornis'' was similar to many medium-sized [[passerine]] birds.<ref name=hongshan2014/>\n\n{{clearboth}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.palaeocritti.com/by-group/aves/ornithuromorpha/hongshanornis Information and photograph of the type specimen, Palaeocritti]\n\n{{portal|Paleontology}}\n{{Paraves|B.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3029892}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous birds of Asia]]\n[[Category:Yixian fauna]]\n[[Category:Basal Ornithurae]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2005]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hongshanornis"}
